<div class="NavHead" style="font-size: 105%; background-color:#FFCCFF;">Central institution membership</div>
<ul class="NavContent" style="text-align: left; font-size: 105%; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; line-height: inherit;"><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1917–53: Full member, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./6th_Central_Committee_of_the_Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="6th Central Committee of the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks)" class="mw-redirect">6th</a>–<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./19th_Presidium_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="19th Presidium of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union">19th</a> Presidium
</li><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1922–43: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./11th_Politburo_and_the_11th_Secretariat_of_the_Russian_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="11th Politburo and the 11th Secretariat of the Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks)">11th</a>–<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./19th_Secretariat_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="19th Secretariat of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union">19th</a> Secretariat
</li><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1920–52: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./9th_Politburo,_the_9th_Secretariat_and_the_9th_Orgburo_of_the_Russian_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="9th Politburo, the 9th Secretariat and the 9th Orgburo of the Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks)">9th</a>–<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./18th_Orgburo_of_the_All-Union_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="18th Orgburo of the All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks)">18th</a> Orgburo
</li><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1912–53: Full member, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./5th_Central_Committee_of_the_Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party" title="5th Central Committee of the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party" class="mw-redirect">5th</a>–<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./19th_Central_Committee_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="19th Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" class="mw-redirect">19th</a> Central Committee
</li></ul>
</div>
<hr/>
<div class="NavFrame collapsed" style="border: none; padding: 0;">
<div class="NavHead" style="font-size: 105%; background-color:#FFCCFF;">Other offices held</div>
<ul class="NavContent" style="text-align: left; font-size: 105%; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0; line-height: inherit;"><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1941–47: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Minister_of_Defence_(Soviet_Union)" title="Minister of Defence (Soviet Union)">Minister of Defense</a>
</li><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1941–45: Chairman, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./State_Defense_Committee" title="State Defense Committee">State Defense Committee</a>
</li><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1920–22: Chairman, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Rabkrin" title="Rabkrin">Workers' and Peasants' Inspectorate</a> of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Soviet_Federative_Socialist_Republic" title="Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic">Russian SFSR</a>
</li><li style="line-height: inherit; margin: 0"> 1917–22: People's Commissar, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./People's_Commissariat_of_Nationalities" title="People's Commissariat of Nationalities" class="mw-redirect">Nationalities</a> of the Russian SFSR
</li></ul>
</div>

<center><b><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leader_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Leader of the Soviet Union" class="mw-redirect">Leader of the Soviet Union</a></b><br/>
<div class="hlist ">
<ul><li><span style="font-size: 120%;"><b>←</b></span> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vladimir_Lenin" title="Vladimir Lenin">Lenin</a></li>
<li><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgy_Malenkov" title="Georgy Malenkov">Malenkov</a> <span style="font-size: 120%;"><b>→</b></span></li></ul>

</div>
</center>
<hr/>
<div class="plainlist" style="font-size:90%; line-height 1.3"><ul><li><span class="citation wikicite" id="endnote_reference_name_A"><sup>a</sup></span>  Despite abolishing the office of General Secretary in 1952, Stalin continued to exercise its powers as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Secretariat_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Secretariat of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union">Secretariat's</a> highest-ranking member.</li><li><span class="citation wikicite" id="endnote_reference_name_B"><sup>b</sup></span>  After Stalin's death, Malenkov temporarily emerged as the highest-ranking member of the Secretariat.</li></ul></div></td></tr></tbody></table>
<!--Basic introduction; name, dates, why he was notable-->
<p id="mwEw"><b id="mwFA">Joseph Vissarionovich Stalin</b><sup about="#mwt11" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-name_3-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"efn","href":"./Template:Efn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"{{IPAc-en|lang|ˈ|s|t|ɑː|l|ɪ|n}}&lt;ref>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/stalin \"Stalin\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151226103503/http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/stalin |date=26 December 2015}}. &apos;&apos;[[Random House Webster&apos;s Unabridged Dictionary]]&apos;&apos;.&lt;/ref>"},"name":{"wt":"\"name\""}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-name-3" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;" data-mw-group="lower-alpha"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[lower-alpha 2]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt12" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-4" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"efn","href":"./Template:Efn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"In Russian: &apos;&apos;Iosif Vissarionovich Stalin&apos;&apos; (Иосиф Виссарионович Сталин)."}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-4" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 3;" data-mw-group="lower-alpha"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[lower-alpha 3]</span></a></sup> (born <b id="mwFQ">Ioseb Besarionis dze Jughashvili</b>;<sup about="#mwt13" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-stalinsname_1-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"efn","href":"./Template:Efn"},"params":{"name":{"wt":"stalinsname"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-stalinsname-1" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 1;" data-mw-group="lower-alpha"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[lower-alpha 1]</span></a></sup> 18 December 1878 – 5 March 1953) was a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgians" title="Georgians" id="mwFg">Georgian</a> revolutionary and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_people" title="Soviet people" id="mwFw">Soviet</a>  politician. He led the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_Union" title="Soviet Union" id="mwGA">Soviet Union</a> from the mid–1920s until 1953 as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./General_Secretary_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwGQ">General Secretary</a> of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwGg">Communist Party of the Soviet Union</a> (1922–1952) and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Premier_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Premier of the Soviet Union" id="mwGw">Premier</a> (1941–1953). While initially presiding over a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Collective_leadership_in_the_Soviet_Union" title="Collective leadership in the Soviet Union" id="mwHA">collective leadership</a>  as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Primus_inter_pares" title="Primus inter pares" id="mwHQ">first among equals</a>, he ultimately consolidated enough power to become the country's <i id="mwHg">de facto</i> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dictator" title="Dictator" id="mwHw">dictator</a> by the 1930s. A <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communism" title="Communism" id="mwIA">communist</a> ideologically committed to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leninism" title="Leninism" id="mwIQ">Leninist</a> interpretation of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Marxism" title="Marxism" id="mwIg">Marxism</a>, Stalin helped to formalise these ideas as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Marxism–Leninism" title="Marxism–Leninism" id="mwIw">Marxism–Leninism</a>, while his own policies became known as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stalinism" title="Stalinism" id="mwJA">Stalinism</a>.</p>

<!--Early life, revolutionary activity and rise to power-->
<p id="mwJQ">Born to a poor family in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gori,_Georgia" title="Gori, Georgia" id="mwJg">Gori</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Empire" title="Russian Empire" id="mwJw">Russian Empire</a> (now <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgia_(country)" title="Georgia (country)" id="mwKA">Georgia</a>), Stalin joined the Marxist <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party" title="Russian Social Democratic Labour Party" id="mwKQ">Russian Social Democratic Labour Party</a> as a youth. He edited the party's newspaper, <i id="mwKg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pravda" title="Pravda" id="mwKw">Pravda</a></i>, and raised funds for <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vladimir_Lenin" title="Vladimir Lenin" id="mwLA">Vladimir Lenin</a>'s <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bolsheviks" title="Bolsheviks" id="mwLQ">Bolshevik</a> faction via robberies, kidnappings, and protection rackets. Repeatedly arrested, he underwent several internal exiles. After the Bolsheviks seized power during the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./October_Revolution" title="October Revolution" id="mwLg">1917 October Revolution</a> and created a one-party state under Lenin's newly renamed Communist Party, Stalin joined its governing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Politburo" title="Politburo" id="mwLw">Politburo</a>. Serving in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Civil_War" title="Russian Civil War" id="mwMA">Russian Civil War</a> before overseeing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Treaty_on_the_Creation_of_the_USSR" title="Treaty on the Creation of the USSR" id="mwMQ">the Soviet Union's establishment</a> in 1922, Stalin <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Rise_of_Joseph_Stalin" title="Rise of Joseph Stalin" id="mwMg">assumed leadership over the country</a> following Lenin's 1924 death. During Stalin's rule, "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Socialism_in_One_Country" title="Socialism in One Country" id="mwMw">Socialism in One Country</a>" became a central tenet of the party's dogma. Under the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Five-year_plans_for_the_national_economy_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Five-year plans for the national economy of the Soviet Union" id="mwNA">Five-Year Plans</a>, the country underwent <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Collectivization_in_the_Soviet_Union" title="Collectivization in the Soviet Union" id="mwNQ">agricultural collectivisation</a> and rapid industrialization, creating a centralized <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Command_economy" title="Command economy" id="mwNg" class="mw-redirect">command economy</a>. This led to significant disruptions in food production that contributed to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_famine_of_1932–33" title="Soviet famine of 1932–33" id="mwNw">famine of 1932–33</a>. To eradicate accused "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Enemies_of_the_working_class" title="Enemies of the working class" id="mwOA" class="mw-redirect">enemies of the working class</a>", Stalin instituted the "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Great_Purge" title="Great Purge" id="mwOQ">Great Purge</a>", in which over a million were imprisoned and at least 700,000 executed between 1934 and 1939. By 1937, he had complete personal control over the party and state.</p>

<!--Governance in the latter part of the 1930s through to his death-->
<p id="mwOg">Stalin's government promoted Marxism–Leninism abroad through the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_International" title="Communist International" id="mwOw">Communist International</a> and supported <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anti-fascism" title="Anti-fascism" id="mwPA">anti-fascist</a> movements throughout Europe during the 1930s, particularly in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Spanish_Civil_War" title="Spanish Civil War" id="mwPQ">Spanish Civil War</a>. In 1939, it signed a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Molotov–Ribbentrop_Pact" title="Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact" id="mwPg">non-aggression pact</a> with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nazi_Germany" title="Nazi Germany" id="mwPw">Nazi Germany</a>, resulting in the Soviet <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Invasion_of_Poland" title="Invasion of Poland" id="mwQA">invasion of Poland</a>. Germany ended the pact by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Operation_Barbarossa" title="Operation Barbarossa" id="mwQQ">invading the Soviet Union</a> in 1941. Despite initial setbacks, the Soviet <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Red_Army" title="Red Army" id="mwQg">Red Army</a> repelled the German incursion and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Battle_of_Berlin" title="Battle of Berlin" id="mwQw">captured Berlin</a> in 1945, ending <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./World_War_II" title="World War II" id="mwRA">World War II</a> in Europe. The Soviets <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Occupation_of_the_Baltic_states" title="Occupation of the Baltic states" id="mwRQ">annexed the Baltic states</a> and helped establish <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_state" title="Communist state" id="mwRg">Soviet-aligned governments</a> throughout Central and Eastern Europe, China and North Korea. The Soviet Union and the United States emerged from the war as the two world <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Superpower" title="Superpower" id="mwRw">superpowers</a>. Tensions arose between the Soviet-backed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Eastern_Bloc" title="Eastern Bloc" id="mwSA">Eastern Bloc</a> and U.S.-backed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Western_Bloc" title="Western Bloc" id="mwSQ">Western Bloc</a> which became known as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cold_War" title="Cold War" id="mwSg">Cold War</a>. Stalin led his country through its post-war reconstruction, during which it <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_atomic_bomb_project" title="Soviet atomic bomb project" id="mwSw">developed a nuclear weapon</a> in 1949. In these years, the country experienced <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_famine_of_1946–47" title="Soviet famine of 1946–47" id="mwTA">another major famine</a> and an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Antisemitism_in_the_Soviet_Union" title="Antisemitism in the Soviet Union" id="mwTQ">anti-semitic</a> campaign peaking in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Doctors'_plot" title="Doctors' plot" id="mwTg">Doctors' plot</a>. Stalin died in 1953; he was eventually succeeded by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikita_Khrushchev" title="Nikita Khrushchev" id="mwTw">Nikita Khrushchev</a>, who <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./On_the_Personality_Cult_and_its_Consequences" title="On the Personality Cult and its Consequences" id="mwUA" class="mw-redirect">denounced his predecessor</a> and initiated a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./De-Stalinisation" title="De-Stalinisation" id="mwUQ" class="mw-redirect">de-Stalinisation</a> process throughout Soviet society.</p>

<!--Reception and legacy-->
<p id="mwUg">Widely considered one of the 20th century's most significant figures, Stalin was the subject of a pervasive <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stalin's_cult_of_personality" title="Stalin's cult of personality" id="mwUw">personality cult</a> within the international Marxist–Leninist movement which revered him as a champion of the working class and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./World_socialism" title="World socialism" id="mwVA" class="mw-redirect">world socialism</a>. Since the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dissolution_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Dissolution of the Soviet Union" id="mwVQ">dissolution of the Soviet Union</a> in 1991, Stalin has retained popularity in Russia and Georgia as a victorious wartime leader who established the Soviet Union as a major world power. Conversely, his <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Totalitarianism" title="Totalitarianism" id="mwVg">totalitarian</a> government has been widely condemned for overseeing mass repressions, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ethnic_cleansing" title="Ethnic cleansing" id="mwVw">ethnic cleansing</a>, hundreds of thousands of executions, and famines which killed millions.</p>
<!--please do not remove, for ToC spacing-->
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r872693506" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" about="#mwt14" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"TOC limit","href":"./Template:TOC_limit"},"params":{"limit":{"wt":"3"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwWA">.mw-parser-output .toclimit-2 .toclevel-1 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-3 .toclevel-2 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-4 .toclevel-3 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-5 .toclevel-4 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-6 .toclevel-5 ul,.mw-parser-output .toclimit-7 .toclevel-6 ul{display:none}</style><div class="toclimit-3" about="#mwt14" id="mwWQ"><meta property="mw:PageProp/toc"/></div>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="1" id="mwWg"><h2 id="Early_life">Early life</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt15" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Early life of Joseph Stalin"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwWw">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Early_life_of_Joseph_Stalin" title="Early life of Joseph Stalin">Early life of Joseph Stalin</a></div>

<section data-mw-section-id="2" id="mwXA"><h3 id="Childhood_to_young_adulthood:_1878–1899"><span id="Childhood_to_young_adulthood:_1878.E2.80.931899" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Childhood to young adulthood: 1878–1899</h3>
<p id="mwXQ">Stalin was born in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgia_(country)" title="Georgia (country)" id="mwXg">Georgian</a> town of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gori,_Georgia" title="Gori, Georgia" id="mwXw">Gori</a><sup about="#mwt16" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19912Khlevniuk201511_5-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"2"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"11"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19912Khlevniuk201511-5" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 2;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[2]</span></a></sup> on <span about="#mwt17" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"OldStyleDate","href":"./Template:OldStyleDate"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"18 December"},"2":{"wt":"1878"},"3":{"wt":"6 December"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwYA">18 December</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt17"> </span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt17">[</span><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Old_Style_and_New_Style_dates" title="Old Style and New Style dates" about="#mwt17">O.S.</a><span about="#mwt17"> 6 December</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt17">]</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt17"> </span><span about="#mwt17">1878</span>.<sup about="#mwt18" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200414Montefiore200723_6-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"14"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"23"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200414Montefiore200723-6" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 3;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[3]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt19" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-8" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"efn","href":"./Template:Efn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Although there is an inconsistency among published sources about Stalin&apos;s year and date of birth, Ioseb Jughashvili is found in the records of the Uspensky Church in Gori, Georgia as born on 18 December ([[Julian calendar|Old Style]]: 6 December) 1878. This birth date is maintained in his School Leaving Certificate, his extensive tsarist Russia police file, a police arrest record from 18 April 1902 which gave his age as 23 years, and all other surviving pre-Revolution documents. As late as 1921, Stalin himself listed his birthday as 18 December 1878 in a curriculum vitae in his own handwriting. After coming to power in 1922, Stalin gave his birth date as 21 December 1879 ([[Adoption of the Gregorian calendar#Adoption in Eastern Europe|Old Style date]] 9 December 1879). That became the day his birthday was celebrated in the Soviet Union.{{sfn|Montefiore|2007|p=23}} "}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-8" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 4;" data-mw-group="lower-alpha"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[lower-alpha 4]</span></a></sup> He was the son of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Besarion_Jughashvili" title="Besarion Jughashvili" id="mwYQ">Besarion "Beso" Jughashvili</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Keke_Geladze" title="Keke Geladze" id="mwYg">Ekaterine "Keke" Geladze</a>,<sup about="#mwt20" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19912Volkogonov19915Service200414Montefiore200719Khlevniuk201511_9-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"2"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"5"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"14"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4p":{"wt":"19"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"11"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19912Volkogonov19915Service200414Montefiore200719Khlevniuk201511-9" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 5;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[5]</span></a></sup> who had married in May 1872,<sup about="#mwt21" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200414Montefiore200719Kotkin201416_10-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"14"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"19"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"16"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200414Montefiore200719Kotkin201416-10" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 6;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[6]</span></a></sup> and had lost two sons in infancy prior to Stalin's birth.<sup about="#mwt22" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19915Service200416Montefiore200722Kotkin201417Khlevniuk201511_11-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"5"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"16"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"22"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"17"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"11"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19915Service200416Montefiore200722Kotkin201417Khlevniuk201511-11" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 7;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[7]</span></a></sup> They were ethnically <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgians" title="Georgians" id="mwYw">Georgian</a>, and Stalin grew up speaking the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgian_language" title="Georgian language" id="mwZA">Georgian language</a>.<sup about="#mwt23" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19911Khlevniuk201511_12-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"1"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"11"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19911Khlevniuk201511-12" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 8;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[8]</span></a></sup> Gori was then part of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Empire" title="Russian Empire" id="mwZQ">Russian Empire</a>, and was home to a population of 20,000, the majority of whom were Georgian but with Armenian, Russian, and Jewish minorities.<sup about="#mwt24" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200415_13-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"15"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200415-13" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 9;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[9]</span></a></sup> Stalin was <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Baptism" title="Baptism" id="mwZg">baptised</a> on 29 December.<sup about="#mwt25" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200416_14-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"16"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200416-14" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 10;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[10]</span></a></sup> He was nicknamed "Soso", a diminutive of "Ioseb".<sup about="#mwt26" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199111Service200416Montefiore200723Kotkin201417_15-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"11"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"16"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"23"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"17"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199111Service200416Montefiore200723Kotkin201417-15" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 11;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[11]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwZw"><a href="./File:Stalin_1894.jpg" id="mwaA"><img resource="./File:Stalin_1894.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b5/Stalin_1894.jpg/170px-Stalin_1894.jpg" data-file-width="543" data-file-height="799" data-file-type="bitmap" height="250" width="170" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b5/Stalin_1894.jpg/340px-Stalin_1894.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b5/Stalin_1894.jpg/255px-Stalin_1894.jpg 1.5x" id="mwaQ"/></a><figcaption id="mwag">Stalin in 1894, aged about 15</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwaw">Besarion was a shoemaker and owned his own workshop;<sup about="#mwt27" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19915Service200414Montefiore200722Kotkin201416_16-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"5"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"14"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"22"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"16"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19915Service200414Montefiore200722Kotkin201416-16" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 12;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[12]</span></a></sup> it was initially a financial success, but later fell into decline.<sup about="#mwt28" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200416Montefiore200722,_32_17-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"16"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"22, 32"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200416Montefiore200722,_32-17" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 13;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[13]</span></a></sup> The family found themselves living in poverty,<sup about="#mwt29" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199111Service200419_18-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"11"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"19"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199111Service200419-18" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 14;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[14]</span></a></sup> moving through nine different rented rooms in ten years.<sup about="#mwt30" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200730–31Kotkin201420_19-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1pp":{"wt":"30–31"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"20"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200730–31Kotkin201420-19" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 15;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[15]</span></a></sup> Besarion became an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Alcoholism" title="Alcoholism" id="mwbA">alcoholic</a>,<sup about="#mwt31" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200417Montefiore200725Kotkin201420Khlevniuk201512_20-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"17"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"25"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"20"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"12"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200417Montefiore200725Kotkin201420Khlevniuk201512-20" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 16;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[16]</span></a></sup> and drunkenly beat his wife and son.<sup about="#mwt32" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199110Volkogonov19915Service200417Montefiore200729Kotkin201424Khlevniuk201512_21-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"10"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"5"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"17"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4p":{"wt":"29"},"5a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"5y":{"wt":"2014"},"5p":{"wt":"24"},"6a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"6y":{"wt":"2015"},"6p":{"wt":"12"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199110Volkogonov19915Service200417Montefiore200729Kotkin201424Khlevniuk201512-21" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 17;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[17]</span></a></sup> To escape the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abusive_relationship" title="Abusive relationship" id="mwbQ" class="mw-redirect">abusive relationship</a>, Keke took Stalin and moved into the house of a family friend, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Clergy" title="Clergy" id="mwbg">Fr.</a> Christopher Charkviani.<sup about="#mwt33" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Montefiore200731Kotkin201420–21_22-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"12"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"31"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"20–21"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Montefiore200731Kotkin201420–21-22" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 18;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[18]</span></a></sup> She worked as a house cleaner and launderer for local families sympathetic to her plight.<sup about="#mwt34" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200732_23-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"32"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200732-23" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[19]</span></a></sup> Keke was determined to send her son to school, something that none of the family had previously achieved.<sup about="#mwt35" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200731_24-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"31"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200731-24" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 20;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[20]</span></a></sup> In late 1888, aged 10 Stalin enrolled at the Gori Church School. This was normally reserved for the children of clergy, although Charkviani ensured that the boy received a place.<sup about="#mwt36" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199111Service200420Montefiore200732–34Kotkin201421_25-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"11"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"20"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"32–34"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"21"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199111Service200420Montefiore200732–34Kotkin201421-25" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 21;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[21]</span></a></sup> Stalin excelled academically,<sup about="#mwt37" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Service200430Montefiore200744Kotkin201426_26-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"12"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"30"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"44"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"26"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Service200430Montefiore200744Kotkin201426-26" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 22;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[22]</span></a></sup> displaying talent in painting and drama classes,<sup about="#mwt38" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200743–44_27-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"43–44"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200743–44-27" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 23;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[23]</span></a></sup> writing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stalin's_poetry" title="Stalin's poetry" id="mwbw">his own poetry</a>,<sup about="#mwt39" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200744_28-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"44"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200744-28" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 24;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[24]</span></a></sup> and singing as a choirboy.<sup about="#mwt40" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199113Service200430Montefiore200743Kotkin201426_29-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"13"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"30"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"43"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"26"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199113Service200430Montefiore200743Kotkin201426-29" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 25;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[25]</span></a></sup> He got into many fights,<sup about="#mwt41" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200420Montefiore200736_30-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"20"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"36"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200420Montefiore200736-30" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 26;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[26]</span></a></sup> and a childhood friend later noted that Stalin "was the best but also the naughtiest pupil" in the class.<sup about="#mwt42" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200745_31-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"45"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200745-31" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 27;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[27]</span></a></sup> Stalin faced several severe health problems; in 1884, he contracted <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Smallpox" title="Smallpox" id="mwcA">smallpox</a> and was left with facial pock scars.<sup about="#mwt43" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Volkogonov19915Service200419Montefiore200731Kotkin201420_32-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"12"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"5"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"19"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4p":{"wt":"31"},"5a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"5y":{"wt":"2014"},"5p":{"wt":"20"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Volkogonov19915Service200419Montefiore200731Kotkin201420-32" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 28;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[28]</span></a></sup> Aged 12, he was seriously injured after being hit by a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Phaeton_(carriage)" title="Phaeton (carriage)" id="mwcQ">phaeton</a>, which was the likely cause of a lifelong disability to his left arm.<sup about="#mwt44" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Service200425Montefiore200735,_46Kotkin201420–21_33-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"12"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"25"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"35, 46"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4pp":{"wt":"20–21"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Service200425Montefiore200735,_46Kotkin201420–21-33" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 29;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[29]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwcg"><a href="./File:The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg" id="mwcw"><img resource="./File:The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg/220px-The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg" data-file-width="686" data-file-height="510" data-file-type="bitmap" height="164" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg/440px-The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b1/The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg/330px-The_Orthodox_Theological_Seminary.jpg 1.5x" id="mwdA"/></a><figcaption id="mwdQ">In 1894 Stalin began his studies at the Tiflis Spiritual Seminary (pictured here in the 1870s)</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwdg">At his teachers' recommendation, Stalin proceeded to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tiflis_Spiritual_Seminary" title="Tiflis Spiritual Seminary" id="mwdw" class="mw-redirect">Spiritual Seminary</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tbilisi" title="Tbilisi" id="mweA">Tiflis</a>.<sup about="#mwt45" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200751Khlevniuk201515_34-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"51"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"15"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200751Khlevniuk201515-34" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 30;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[30]</span></a></sup> He enrolled at the school in August 1894,<sup about="#mwt46" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200753_35-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"53"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200753-35" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 31;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[31]</span></a></sup> enabled by a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Scholarship" title="Scholarship" id="mweQ">scholarship</a> that allowed him to study at a reduced rate.<sup about="#mwt47" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200752–53_36-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"52–53"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200752–53-36" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 32;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[32]</span></a></sup> Here he joined 600 trainee priests who boarded at the seminary.<sup about="#mwt48" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200754–55_37-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"54–55"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200754–55-37" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 33;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[33]</span></a></sup> Stalin was again academically successful and gained high grades.<sup about="#mwt49" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199119Service200436Montefiore200756Kotkin201432Khlevniuk201516_38-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"19"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"36"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"56"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"32"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"16"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199119Service200436Montefiore200756Kotkin201432Khlevniuk201516-38" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 34;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[34]</span></a></sup> He <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stalin's_poetry" title="Stalin's poetry" id="mweg">continued writing poetry</a>; five of his poems were published under the pseudonym of "Soselo" in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ilia_Chavchavadze" title="Ilia Chavchavadze" id="mwew">Ilia Chavchavadze</a>'s newspaper <i id="mwfA">Iveria</i> ('Georgia').<sup about="#mwt50" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199118Montefiore200757Kotkin201433_39-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"18"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"57"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"33"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199118Montefiore200757Kotkin201433-39" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 35;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[35]</span></a></sup> Thematically, they dealt with topics like nature, land, and patriotism.<sup about="#mwt51" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200438_40-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"38"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200438-40" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 36;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[36]</span></a></sup> According to Stalin's biographer <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Simon_Sebag_Montefiore" title="Simon Sebag Montefiore" id="mwfQ">Simon Sebag Montefiore</a> they became "minor Georgian classics",<sup about="#mwt52" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200758_41-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"58"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200758-41" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[37]</span></a></sup> and were included in various anthologies of Georgian poetry over the coming years.<sup about="#mwt53" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200758_41-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"58"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200758-41" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 37;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[37]</span></a></sup> As he grew older, Stalin lost interest in his studies; his grades dropped,<sup about="#mwt54" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200769Kotkin201432Khlevniuk201518_42-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"69"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"32"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"18"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200769Kotkin201432Khlevniuk201518-42" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 38;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[38]</span></a></sup> and he was repeatedly confined to a cell for his rebellious behaviour.<sup about="#mwt55" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199119Montefiore200769Kotkin201436–37Khlevniuk201519_43-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"19"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"69"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"36–37"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"19"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199119Montefiore200769Kotkin201436–37Khlevniuk201519-43" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 39;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[39]</span></a></sup> Teachers complained that he declared himself an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Atheism" title="Atheism" id="mwfg">atheist</a>, chatted in class and refused to doff his hat to monks.<sup about="#mwt56" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200770–71_44-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"70–71"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200770–71-44" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 40;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[40]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwfw">Stalin joined a forbidden book club active at the school;<sup about="#mwt57" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199119Montefiore200762Kotkin201436,_37Khlevniuk201518_45-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"19"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"62"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"36, 37"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"18"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199119Montefiore200762Kotkin201436,_37Khlevniuk201518-45" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 41;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[41]</span></a></sup> he was particularly influenced by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikolay_Chernyshevsky" title="Nikolay Chernyshevsky" id="mwgA">Nikolay Chernyshevsky</a>'s 1863 pro-revolutionary novel <i id="mwgQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./What_Is_To_Be_Done%3F_(novel)" title="What Is To Be Done? (novel)" id="mwgg" class="mw-redirect">What Is To Be Done?</a></i><sup about="#mwt58" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200763_46-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"63"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200763-46" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 42;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[42]</span></a></sup> Another influential text was <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Alexander_Kazbegi" title="Alexander Kazbegi" id="mwgw">Alexander Kazbegi</a>'s <i id="mwhA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./The_Patricide" title="The Patricide" id="mwhQ">The Patricide</a></i>, with Stalin adopting the nickname "Koba" from that of the book's bandit protagonist.<sup about="#mwt59" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199114Volkogonov19915Service200427–28Montefiore200763Kotkin201423–24Khlevniuk201517_47-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"14"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"5"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"27–28"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4p":{"wt":"63"},"5a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"5y":{"wt":"2014"},"5pp":{"wt":"23–24"},"6a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"6y":{"wt":"2015"},"6p":{"wt":"17"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199114Volkogonov19915Service200427–28Montefiore200763Kotkin201423–24Khlevniuk201517-47" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 43;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[43]</span></a></sup> He also read <i id="mwhg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Capital:_Critique_of_Political_Economy" title="Capital: Critique of Political Economy" id="mwhw" class="mw-redirect">Capital</a></i>, the 1867 book by German sociological theorist <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Karl_Marx" title="Karl Marx" id="mwiA">Karl Marx</a>.<sup about="#mwt60" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200764_48-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"64"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200764-48" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 44;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[44]</span></a></sup> Stalin devoted himself to Marx's socio-political theory, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Marxism" title="Marxism" id="mwiQ">Marxism</a>,<sup about="#mwt61" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200769_49-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"69"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200769-49" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 45;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[45]</span></a></sup> which was then on the rise in Georgia, one of various forms of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Socialism" title="Socialism" id="mwig">socialism</a> opposed to the empire's governing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tsarism" title="Tsarism" id="mwiw" class="mw-redirect">Tsarist</a> authorities.<sup about="#mwt62" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200440Kotkin201443_50-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"40"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"43"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200440Kotkin201443-50" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 46;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[46]</span></a></sup> At night, he attended secret workers' meetings,<sup about="#mwt63" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200766_51-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"66"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200766-51" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 47;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[47]</span></a></sup> and was introduced to Silibistro "Silva" Jibladze, the Marxist founder of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mesame_Dasi" title="Mesame Dasi" id="mwjA">Mesame Dasi</a> ('Third Group'), a Georgian socialist group.<sup about="#mwt64" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200765Kotkin201444_52-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"65"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"44"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200765Kotkin201444-52" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 48;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[48]</span></a></sup> Stalin left the seminary in April 1899; he never returned,<sup about="#mwt65" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200441Montefiore200771_53-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"41"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"71"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200441Montefiore200771-53" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 49;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[49]</span></a></sup> although the school encouraged him to come back.<sup about="#mwt66" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200773_54-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"73"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200773-54" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 50;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[50]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="3" id="mwjQ"><h3 id="Russian_Social-Democratic_Labour_Party:_1899–1904"><span id="Russian_Social-Democratic_Labour_Party:_1899.E2.80.931904" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Russian Social-Democratic Labour Party: 1899–1904</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwjg"><a href="./File:Stalin_1902.jpg" id="mwjw"><img resource="./File:Stalin_1902.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Stalin_1902.jpg/170px-Stalin_1902.jpg" data-file-width="1032" data-file-height="1400" data-file-type="bitmap" height="231" width="170" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Stalin_1902.jpg/340px-Stalin_1902.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Stalin_1902.jpg/255px-Stalin_1902.jpg 1.5x" id="mwkA"/></a><figcaption id="mwkQ">A mugshot of Stalin made in 1902 by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Batumi" title="Batumi" id="mwkg">Batumi</a> police gendarmerie</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwkw">In October 1899, Stalin began work as a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Meteorologist" title="Meteorologist" id="mwlA" class="mw-redirect">meteorologist</a> at a Tiflis observatory.<sup about="#mwt67" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199127Service200443–44Montefiore200776Kotkin201447–48_55-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"27"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"43–44"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"76"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4pp":{"wt":"47–48"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199127Service200443–44Montefiore200776Kotkin201447–48-55" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 51;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[51]</span></a></sup> He attracted a group of supporters through his classes in socialist theory,<sup about="#mwt68" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200779_56-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"79"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200779-56" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 52;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[52]</span></a></sup> and co-organised a secret workers' mass meeting for <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Workers'_Day" title="International Workers' Day" id="mwlQ">May Day</a> 1900,<sup about="#mwt69" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199127Montefiore200778_57-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"27"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"78"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199127Montefiore200778-57" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 53;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[53]</span></a></sup> at which he successfully encouraged many of the men to take strike action.<sup about="#mwt70" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200778_58-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"78"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200778-58" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 54;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[54]</span></a></sup> By this point, the empire's secret police—the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Okhrana" title="Okhrana" id="mwlg">Okhrana</a>—were aware of Stalin's activities within Tiflis' revolutionary milieu.<sup about="#mwt71" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200778_58-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"78"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200778-58" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 54;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[54]</span></a></sup> They attempted to arrest him in March 1901, but he escaped and went into hiding,<sup about="#mwt72" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199127Service200445Montefiore200781–82Kotkin201449_59-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"27"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"45"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"81–82"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"49"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199127Service200445Montefiore200781–82Kotkin201449-59" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 55;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[55]</span></a></sup> living off the donations of friends and sympathisers.<sup about="#mwt73" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200782_60-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"82"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200782-60" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 56;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[56]</span></a></sup> Remaining underground, he helped plan a demonstration for May Day 1901, in which 3,000 marchers clashed with the authorities.<sup about="#mwt74" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199128Montefiore200782Kotkin201450_61-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"28"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"82"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"50"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199128Montefiore200782Kotkin201450-61" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 57;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[57]</span></a></sup> He continued to evade arrest by using aliases and sleeping in different apartments.<sup about="#mwt75" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200787_62-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"87"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200787-62" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 58;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[58]</span></a></sup> In November 1901, he was elected to the Tiflis Committee of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party" title="Russian Social Democratic Labour Party" id="mwlw">Russian Social Democratic Labour Party</a> (RSDLP), a Marxist party founded in 1898.<sup about="#mwt76" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERieber200537–38Montefiore200787–88_63-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Rieber"},"1y":{"wt":"2005"},"1pp":{"wt":"37–38"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"87–88"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERieber200537–38Montefiore200787–88-63" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 59;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[59]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwmA">That month, Stalin travelled to the port city of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Batumi" title="Batumi" id="mwmQ">Batumi</a>.<sup about="#mwt77" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200452Rieber200539Montefiore2007101Kotkin201451_64-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"29"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"52"},"3a1":{"wt":"Rieber"},"3y":{"wt":"2005"},"3p":{"wt":"39"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4p":{"wt":"101"},"5a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"5y":{"wt":"2014"},"5p":{"wt":"51"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200452Rieber200539Montefiore2007101Kotkin201451-64" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 60;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[60]</span></a></sup> His militant rhetoric proved divisive among the city's Marxists, some of whom suspected that he might be an <i id="mwmg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Agent_provocateur" title="Agent provocateur" id="mwmw">agent provocateur</a></i> working for the government.<sup about="#mwt78" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200791,_95Kotkin201453_65-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1pp":{"wt":"91, 95"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"53"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200791,_95Kotkin201453-65" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 61;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[61]</span></a></sup> He found employment at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Rothschild_family" title="Rothschild family" id="mwnA">Rothschild</a> refinery storehouse, where he co-organised two workers' strikes.<sup about="#mwt79" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200790–93Kotkin201451Khlevniuk201522–23_66-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1pp":{"wt":"90–93"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"51"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"22–23"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200790–93Kotkin201451Khlevniuk201522–23-66" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 62;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[62]</span></a></sup> After several strike leaders were arrested, he co-organised a mass public demonstration that led to the storming of the prison; troops fired upon the demonstrators, 13 of whom were killed.<sup about="#mwt80" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200449Montefiore200794–95Kotkin201452Khlevniuk201523_67-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"29"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"49"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"94–95"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"52"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"23"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200449Montefiore200794–95Kotkin201452Khlevniuk201523-67" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 63;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[63]</span></a></sup> Stalin organised a second mass demonstration on the day of their funeral,<sup about="#mwt81" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200797–98_68-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"97–98"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200797–98-68" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 64;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[64]</span></a></sup> before being arrested in April 1902.<sup about="#mwt82" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200449Rieber200542Montefiore200798Kotkin201452_69-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"29"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"49"},"3a1":{"wt":"Rieber"},"3y":{"wt":"2005"},"3p":{"wt":"42"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4p":{"wt":"98"},"5a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"5y":{"wt":"2014"},"5p":{"wt":"52"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200449Rieber200542Montefiore200798Kotkin201452-69" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 65;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[65]</span></a></sup> He was initially held at Batumi Prison,<sup about="#mwt83" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200452Montefiore2007101_70-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"52"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"101"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200452Montefiore2007101-70" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 66;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[66]</span></a></sup> and later moved to the more secure Kutaisi Prison.<sup about="#mwt84" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200452Montefiore2007105_71-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"29"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"52"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"105"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200452Montefiore2007105-71" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 67;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[67]</span></a></sup> In mid-1903, Stalin was sentenced to three years of exile in eastern Siberia.<sup about="#mwt85" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Montefiore2007107Kotkin201453Khlevniuk201523_72-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"29"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"107"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"53"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"23"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Montefiore2007107Kotkin201453Khlevniuk201523-72" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 68;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[68]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwnQ">Stalin left Batumi in October, arriving at the small Siberian town of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Novaya_Uda,_Irkutsk_Oblast" title="Novaya Uda, Irkutsk Oblast" id="mwng">Novaya Uda</a> in late November.<sup about="#mwt87" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200452Montefiore2007108–110_73-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"29"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"52"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"108–110"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199129Service200452Montefiore2007108–110-73" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 69;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[69]</span></a></sup> There, he lived in a two-room peasant's house, sleeping in the building's larder.<sup about="#mwt88" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007111_74-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"111"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007111-74" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 70;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[70]</span></a></sup> He made two escape attempts; on the first he made it to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Balagansk" title="Balagansk" id="mwnw">Balagansk</a> before returning due to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Frostbite" title="Frostbite" id="mwoA">frostbite</a>.<sup about="#mwt89" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200452Montefiore2007114–115_75-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"52"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"114–115"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200452Montefiore2007114–115-75" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 71;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[71]</span></a></sup> His second attempt was successful and he made it to Tiflis.<sup about="#mwt90" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200452Montefiore2007115–116Kotkin201453_76-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"52"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"115–116"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"53"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200452Montefiore2007115–116Kotkin201453-76" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 72;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[72]</span></a></sup> There, he co-edited a Georgian Marxist newspaper, <i id="mwoQ"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Proletariatis_Brdzola" title="Proletariatis Brdzola" id="mwog">Proletariatis Brdzola</a></i> ("Proletarian Struggle"), with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Philip_Makharadze" title="Philip Makharadze" id="mwow" class="mw-redirect">Philip Makharadze</a>.<sup about="#mwt91" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200457Montefiore2007123_77-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"57"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"123"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200457Montefiore2007123-77" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 73;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[73]</span></a></sup> He called for the Georgian Marxist movement to split off from its Russian counterpart, resulting in several RSDLP members accusing him of holding views contrary to the ethos of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Proletarian_internationalism" title="Proletarian internationalism" id="mwpA">Marxist internationalism</a> and calling for his expulsion from the party; he soon recanted his opinions.<sup about="#mwt92" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200454Montefiore2007117–118Kotkin201477_78-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"54"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"117–118"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"77"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200454Montefiore2007117–118Kotkin201477-78" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 74;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[74]</span></a></sup> During his exile, the RSDLP had split between <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vladimir_Lenin" title="Vladimir Lenin" id="mwpQ">Vladimir Lenin</a>'s <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bolsheviks" title="Bolsheviks" id="mwpg">Bolsheviks</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Julius_Martov" title="Julius Martov" id="mwpw">Julius Martov</a>'s <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mensheviks" title="Mensheviks" id="mwqA">Mensheviks</a>.<sup about="#mwt93" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199133–34Service200453Montefiore2007113Kotkin201478–79Khlevniuk201524_79-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"33–34"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"53"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"113"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4pp":{"wt":"78–79"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"24"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199133–34Service200453Montefiore2007113Kotkin201478–79Khlevniuk201524-79" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 75;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[75]</span></a></sup> Stalin detested many of the Mensheviks in Georgia and aligned himself with the Bolsheviks.<sup about="#mwt94" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200459Kotkin201480Khlevniuk201524_80-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"59"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"80"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"24"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200459Kotkin201480Khlevniuk201524-80" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 76;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[76]</span></a></sup> Although Stalin established a Bolshevik stronghold in the mining town of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chiatura" title="Chiatura" id="mwqQ">Chiatura</a>,<sup about="#mwt95" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007131_81-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"131"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007131-81" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 77;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[77]</span></a></sup> Bolshevism remained a minority force in the Menshevik-dominated Georgian revolutionary scene.<sup about="#mwt96" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199138Service200459_82-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"38"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"59"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199138Service200459-82" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 78;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[78]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="4" id="mwqg"><h3 id="The_Revolution_of_1905_and_its_aftermath:_1905–1912"><span id="The_Revolution_of_1905_and_its_aftermath:_1905.E2.80.931912" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>The Revolution of 1905 and its aftermath: 1905–1912</h3>
<p id="mwqw">In January 1905, government troops <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bloody_Sunday_(1905)" title="Bloody Sunday (1905)" id="mwrA">massacred protesters</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Saint_Petersburg" title="Saint Petersburg" id="mwrQ">Saint Petersburg</a>.<sup about="#mwt98" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200456Montefiore2007126_83-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"56"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"126"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200456Montefiore2007126-83" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 79;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[79]</span></a></sup> Unrest soon spread across the Russian Empire in what came to be known as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Revolution_of_1905" title="Revolution of 1905" id="mwrg" class="mw-redirect">Revolution of 1905</a>.<sup about="#mwt99" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200456Montefiore2007126_83-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"56"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"126"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200456Montefiore2007126-83" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 79;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[79]</span></a></sup> Georgia was one of the regions particularly affected.<sup about="#mwt100" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200456_84-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"56"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200456-84" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 80;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[80]</span></a></sup> Stalin was in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Baku" title="Baku" id="mwrw">Baku</a> in February when ethnic violence broke out between Armenians and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Azerbaijanis" title="Azerbaijanis" id="mwsA">Azeris</a>; at least 2,000 were killed.<sup about="#mwt101" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200458Montefiore2007128–129_85-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"58"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"128–129"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200458Montefiore2007128–129-85" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 81;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[81]</span></a></sup> He publicly lambasted the "pogroms against Jews and Armenians" as being part of Tsar <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nicholas_II_of_Russia" title="Nicholas II of Russia" id="mwsQ">Nicholas II</a>'s attempts to "buttress his despicable throne".<sup about="#mwt102" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007129_86-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"129"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007129-86" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 82;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[82]</span></a></sup> Stalin formed a Bolshevik Battle Squad which he used to try and keep Baku's warring ethnic factions apart; he also used the unrest as a cover for stealing printing equipment.<sup about="#mwt103" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007129_86-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"129"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007129-86" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 82;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[82]</span></a></sup> Amid the growing violence throughout Georgia he formed further Battle Squads, with the Mensheviks doing the same.<sup about="#mwt104" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007131–132_87-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"131–132"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007131–132-87" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 83;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[83]</span></a></sup> Stalin's Squads disarmed local police and troops,<sup about="#mwt105" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007132_88-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"132"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007132-88" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 84;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[84]</span></a></sup> raided government arsenals,<sup about="#mwt106" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007143_89-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"143"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007143-89" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 85;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[85]</span></a></sup> and raised funds through <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Protection_rackets" title="Protection rackets" id="mwsg" class="mw-redirect">protection rackets</a> on large local businesses and mines.<sup about="#mwt107" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007132–133_90-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"132–133"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007132–133-90" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 86;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[86]</span></a></sup> They launched attacks on the government's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cossack" title="Cossack" id="mwsw" class="mw-redirect">Cossack</a> troops and pro-Tsarist <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Black_Hundreds" title="Black Hundreds" id="mwtA">Black Hundreds</a>,<sup about="#mwt108" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007135,_144_91-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"135, 144"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007135,_144-91" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 87;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[87]</span></a></sup> co-ordinating some of their operations with the Menshevik militia.<sup about="#mwt109" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007137_92-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"137"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007137-92" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 88;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[88]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwtQ"><a href="./File:LeninEnSuizaMarzo1916--barbaroussovietr00mcbr.png" id="mwtg"><img resource="./File:LeninEnSuizaMarzo1916--barbaroussovietr00mcbr.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/LeninEnSuizaMarzo1916--barbaroussovietr00mcbr.png/220px-LeninEnSuizaMarzo1916--barbaroussovietr00mcbr.png" data-file-width="387" data-file-height="527" data-file-type="bitmap" height="300" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/4a/LeninEnSuizaMarzo1916--barbaroussovietr00mcbr.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/LeninEnSuizaMarzo1916--barbaroussovietr00mcbr.png/330px-LeninEnSuizaMarzo1916--barbaroussovietr00mcbr.png 1.5x" id="mwtw"/></a><figcaption id="mwuA">Stalin first met Vladimir Lenin (pictured) at <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tampere_conference_of_1905" title="Tampere conference of 1905" id="mwuQ">a 1905 conference in Tampere</a>. Lenin became "Stalin's indispensable mentor".<sup about="#mwt110" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin201481_93-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"81"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin201481-93" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 89;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[89]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwug">In November 1905, the Georgian Bolsheviks elected Stalin as one of their delegates to a Bolshevik conference in Saint Petersburg.<sup about="#mwt111" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200460Montefiore2007145_94-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"60"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"145"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200460Montefiore2007145-94" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 90;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[90]</span></a></sup> On arrival, he met Lenin's wife <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nadezhda_Krupskaya" title="Nadezhda Krupskaya" id="mwuw">Nadezhda Krupskaya</a>, who informed him that the venue had been moved to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tampere" title="Tampere" id="mwvA">Tampere</a> in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Grand_Duchy_of_Finland" title="Grand Duchy of Finland" id="mwvQ">Grand Duchy of Finland</a>.<sup about="#mwt112" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007145_95-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"145"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007145-95" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 91;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[91]</span></a></sup> At <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tampere_conference_of_1905" title="Tampere conference of 1905" id="mwvg">the conference</a> Stalin met Lenin for the first time.<sup about="#mwt113" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199137Service200460Kotkin201481_96-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"37"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"60"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"81"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199137Service200460Kotkin201481-96" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 92;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[92]</span></a></sup> Although Stalin held Lenin in deep respect, he was vocal in his disagreement with Lenin's view that the Bolsheviks should field candidates for the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_legislative_election,_1906" title="Russian legislative election, 1906" id="mwvw" class="mw-redirect">forthcoming election</a> to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./State_Duma_(Russian_Empire)" title="State Duma (Russian Empire)" id="mwwA">State Duma</a>; Stalin saw the parliamentary process as a waste of time.<sup about="#mwt114" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007147Kotkin2014105_97-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"147"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"105"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007147Kotkin2014105-97" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 93;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[93]</span></a></sup> In April 1906, Stalin attended the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./4th_Congress_of_the_Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party" title="4th Congress of the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party" id="mwwQ">RSDLP Fourth Congress</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stockholm" title="Stockholm" id="mwwg">Stockholm</a>; this was his first trip outside the Russian Empire.<sup about="#mwt115" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199139–40Service200461,_62Montefiore2007156_98-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"39–40"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"61, 62"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"156"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199139–40Service200461,_62Montefiore2007156-98" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 94;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[94]</span></a></sup> At the conference, the RSDLP—then led by its Menshevik majority—agreed that it would not raise funds using armed robbery.<sup about="#mwt116" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199140Service200462Khlevniuk201526_99-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"40"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"62"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"26"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199140Service200462Khlevniuk201526-99" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 95;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[95]</span></a></sup> Lenin and Stalin disagreed with this decision,<sup about="#mwt117" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200462Kotkin2014113_100-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"62"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"113"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200462Kotkin2014113-100" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 96;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[96]</span></a></sup> and later privately discussed how they could continue the robberies for the Bolshevik cause.<sup about="#mwt118" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007168Kotkin2014113_101-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"168"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"113"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007168Kotkin2014113-101" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 97;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[97]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwww">Stalin married <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kato_Svanidze" title="Kato Svanidze" id="mwxA">Kato Svanidze</a> in a church ceremony at <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Senaki" title="Senaki" id="mwxQ">Senaki</a> in July 1906.<sup about="#mwt122" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200464Montefiore2007159Kotkin2014105_102-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"64"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"159"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"105"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200464Montefiore2007159Kotkin2014105-102" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 98;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[98]</span></a></sup> In March 1907 she bore a son, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Yakov_Dzhugashvili" title="Yakov Dzhugashvili" id="mwxg">Yakov</a>.<sup about="#mwt123" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200464Montefiore2007167Kotkin2014106Khlevniuk201525_103-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"64"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"167"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"106"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"25"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200464Montefiore2007167Kotkin2014106Khlevniuk201525-103" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 99;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[99]</span></a></sup> By that year—according to the historian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Robert_Service_(historian)" title="Robert Service (historian)" id="mwxw">Robert Service</a>—Stalin had established himself as "Georgia's leading Bolshevik".<sup about="#mwt124" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200465_104-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"65"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200465-104" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 100;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[100]</span></a></sup> He attended the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./5th_Congress_of_the_Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party" title="5th Congress of the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party" id="mwyA">Fifth RSDLP Congress</a>, held in London in May–June 1907.<sup about="#mwt125" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199141Service200465Montefiore2007168–170Kotkin2014108_105-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"41"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"65"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"168–170"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"108"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199141Service200465Montefiore2007168–170Kotkin2014108-105" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 101;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[101]</span></a></sup> After returning to Tiflis, Stalin organized the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./1907_Tiflis_bank_robbery" title="1907 Tiflis bank robbery" id="mwyQ">robbing of a large delivery of money to the Imperial Bank</a> in June 1907. His gang ambushed the armed convoy in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Freedom_Square,_Tbilisi" title="Freedom Square, Tbilisi" id="mwyg">Yerevan Square</a> with gunfire and home-made bombs. Around 40 people were killed, but all of his gang escaped alive.<sup about="#mwt126" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199141–42Service200475Kotkin2014113_106-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"41–42"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"75"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"113"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199141–42Service200475Kotkin2014113-106" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 102;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[102]</span></a></sup>
After the heist, Stalin settled in Baku with his wife and son.<sup about="#mwt140" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007180Kotkin2014114_107-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"180"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"114"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007180Kotkin2014114-107" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 103;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[103]</span></a></sup> There, Mensheviks confronted Stalin about the robbery and voted to expel him from the RSDLP, but he took no notice of them.<sup about="#mwt141" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199143–44Service200476Montefiore2007184_108-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"43–44"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"76"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"184"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199143–44Service200476Montefiore2007184-108" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 104;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[104]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwyw">In Baku, Stalin secured Bolshevik domination of the local RSDLP branch,<sup about="#mwt143" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007190_109-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"190"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007190-109" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 105;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[105]</span></a></sup> and edited two Bolshevik newspapers, <i id="mwzA">Bakinsky Proletary</i> and <i id="mwzQ">Gudok</i> ("Whistle").<sup about="#mwt144" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007186_110-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"186"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007186-110" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 106;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[106]</span></a></sup> In August 1907, he attended the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Socialist_Congress,_Stuttgart_1907" title="International Socialist Congress, Stuttgart 1907" id="mwzg">Seventh Congress</a> of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Second_International" title="Second International" id="mwzw">Second International</a>—an international socialist organisation—in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stuttgart" title="Stuttgart" id="mw0A">Stuttgart</a>, Germany.<sup about="#mwt145" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007189_111-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"189"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007189-111" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 107;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[107]</span></a></sup> In November 1907, his wife died of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Typhus" title="Typhus" id="mw0Q">typhus</a>,<sup about="#mwt146" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007191Kotkin2014115_112-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"191"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"115"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007191Kotkin2014115-112" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 108;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[108]</span></a></sup> and he left his son with her family in Tiflis.<sup about="#mwt147" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199144Service200471Montefiore2007193Kotkin2014116_113-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"44"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"71"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"193"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"116"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199144Service200471Montefiore2007193Kotkin2014116-113" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 109;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[109]</span></a></sup> In Baku he had reassembled his gang, the Outfit,<sup about="#mwt148" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007194_114-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"194"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007194-114" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 110;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[110]</span></a></sup> which continued to attack Black Hundreds and raised finances by running protection rackets, counterfeiting currency, and carrying out robberies.<sup about="#mwt149" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200474Montefiore2007196Kotkin2014115_115-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"74"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"196"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"115"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200474Montefiore2007196Kotkin2014115-115" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 111;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[111]</span></a></sup> They also kidnapped the children of several wealthy figures to extract ransom money.<sup about="#mwt150" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007197–198Kotkin2014115_116-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1pp":{"wt":"197–198"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"115"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007197–198Kotkin2014115-116" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 112;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[112]</span></a></sup> In early 1908, he travelled to the Swiss city of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Geneva" title="Geneva" id="mw0g">Geneva</a> to meet with Lenin and the prominent Russian Marxist <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgi_Plekhanov" title="Georgi Plekhanov" id="mw0w">Georgi Plekhanov</a>, although the latter exasperated him.<sup about="#mwt151" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007195_117-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"195"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007195-117" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 113;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[113]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mw1A">In March 1908, Stalin was arrested and interned in Bailov Prison.<sup about="#mwt154" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199144Service200468Montefiore2007203Kotkin2014116_118-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"44"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"68"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"203"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"116"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199144Service200468Montefiore2007203Kotkin2014116-118" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 114;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[114]</span></a></sup> There, he led the imprisoned Bolsheviks, organised discussion groups, and ordered the killing of suspected informants.<sup about="#mwt155" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199145Montefiore2007203–204_119-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"45"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"203–204"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199145Montefiore2007203–204-119" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 115;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[115]</span></a></sup> He was eventually sentenced to two years exile in the village of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Solvychegodsk" title="Solvychegodsk" id="mw1Q">Solvychegodsk</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vologda_Oblast" title="Vologda Oblast" id="mw1g">Vologda Province</a>, arriving there in February 1909.<sup about="#mwt156" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199145Service200468Montefiore2007206,_208Kotkin2014116_120-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"45"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"68"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"206, 208"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"116"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199145Service200468Montefiore2007206,_208Kotkin2014116-120" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 116;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[116]</span></a></sup> In June, he escaped the village and made it to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kotlas" title="Kotlas" id="mw1w">Kotlas</a> disguised as a woman and from there to Saint Petersburg.<sup about="#mwt157" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199146Montefiore2007212Kotkin2014117_121-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"46"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"212"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"117"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199146Montefiore2007212Kotkin2014117-121" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 117;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[117]</span></a></sup> In March 1910, he was arrested again, and sent back to Solvychegodsk.<sup about="#mwt158" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199146Montefiore2007222,_226Kotkin2014121_122-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"46"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"222, 226"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"121"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199146Montefiore2007222,_226Kotkin2014121-122" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 118;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[118]</span></a></sup> There he had affairs with at least two women; his landlady, Maria Kuzakova, later gave birth to his second son, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Constantine_Kuzakov" title="Constantine Kuzakov" id="mw2A" class="mw-redirect">Konstantin</a>.<sup about="#mwt159" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200479Montefiore2007227,_229,_230–231Kotkin2014121_123-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"79"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"227, 229, 230–231"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"121"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200479Montefiore2007227,_229,_230–231Kotkin2014121-123" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 119;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[119]</span></a></sup> In June 1911, Stalin was given permission to move to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vologda" title="Vologda" id="mw2Q">Vologda</a>, where he stayed for two months,<sup about="#mwt160" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199147Service200480Montefiore2007231,_234Kotkin2014121_124-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"47"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"80"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"231, 234"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"121"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199147Service200480Montefiore2007231,_234Kotkin2014121-124" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 120;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[120]</span></a></sup> having a relationship with Pelageya Onufrieva.<sup about="#mwt161" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200479Montefiore2007234Kotkin2014121_125-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"79"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"234"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"121"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200479Montefiore2007234Kotkin2014121-125" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 121;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[121]</span></a></sup> He escaped to Saint Petersburg,<sup about="#mwt162" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007236Kotkin2014121_126-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"236"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"121"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007236Kotkin2014121-126" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 122;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[122]</span></a></sup> where he was arrested in September 1911, and sentenced to a further three-year exile in Vologda.<sup about="#mwt163" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007237Kotkin2014121–22_127-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"237"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"121–22"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007237Kotkin2014121–22-127" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 123;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[123]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="5" id="mw2g"><h3 id="Rise_to_the_Central_Committee_and_editorship_of_Pravda:_1912–1917"><span id="Rise_to_the_Central_Committee_and_editorship_of_Pravda:_1912.E2.80.931917" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Rise to the Central Committee and editorship of <i id="mw2w">Pravda</i>: 1912–1917</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mw3A"><a href="./File:First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg" id="mw3Q"><img resource="./File:First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg/220px-First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg" data-file-width="4032" data-file-height="3024" data-file-type="bitmap" height="165" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg/440px-First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/0e/First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg/330px-First_Issue_of_PRAVDA.jpg 1.5x" id="mw3g"/></a><figcaption id="mw3w">The first issue of <i id="mw4A">Pravda</i>, the Bolshevik newspaper of which Stalin was editor</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mw4Q">While Stalin was in exile, the first <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Central_Committee_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mw4g">Bolshevik Central Committee</a> had been elected at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Prague_Conference" title="Prague Conference" id="mw4w">Prague Conference</a>, after which Lenin and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Grigory_Zinoviev" title="Grigory Zinoviev" id="mw5A">Grigory Zinoviev</a> invited Stalin to join it. Still in Vologda, Stalin agreed, remaining a Central Committee member for the rest of his life.<sup about="#mwt164" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199148Service200483Montefiore2007240Kotkin2014122–123_128-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"48"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"83"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"240"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4pp":{"wt":"122–123"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199148Service200483Montefiore2007240Kotkin2014122–123-128" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 124;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[124]</span></a></sup> Lenin believed that Stalin, as a Georgian, would help secure support for the Bolsheviks from the Empire's minority ethnicities.<sup about="#mwt165" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007240_129-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"240"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007240-129" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 125;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[125]</span></a></sup> In February 1912, Stalin again escaped to Saint Petersburg,<sup about="#mwt166" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007241_130-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"241"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007241-130" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 126;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[126]</span></a></sup> tasked with converting the Bolshevik weekly newspaper, <i id="mw5Q">Zvezda</i> ("Star") into a daily, <i id="mw5g"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pravda" title="Pravda" id="mw5w">Pravda</a></i> ("Truth").<sup about="#mwt167" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200484Montefiore2007243_131-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"84"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"243"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200484Montefiore2007243-131" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 127;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[127]</span></a></sup> The new newspaper was launched in April 1912,<sup about="#mwt168" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200484Montefiore2007247_132-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"84"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"247"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200484Montefiore2007247-132" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 128;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[128]</span></a></sup> although Stalin's role as editor was kept secret.<sup about="#mwt169" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200484Montefiore2007247_132-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"84"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"247"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200484Montefiore2007247-132" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 128;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[128]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mw6A">In May 1912, he was arrested again and imprisoned in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shpalerhy_Prison" title="Shpalerhy Prison" id="mw6Q" class="new">Shpalerhy Prison</a>, before being sentenced to three years exile in Siberia.<sup about="#mwt170" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199151Montefiore2007248_133-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"51"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"248"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199151Montefiore2007248-133" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 129;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[129]</span></a></sup> In July, he arrived at the Siberian village of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Narym" title="Narym" id="mw6g">Narym</a>,<sup about="#mwt171" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007249Kotkin2014133_134-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"249"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"133"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007249Kotkin2014133-134" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 130;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[130]</span></a></sup> where he shared a room with fellow Bolshevik <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Yakov_Sverdlov" title="Yakov Sverdlov" id="mw6w">Yakov Sverdlov</a>.<sup about="#mwt172" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200486Montefiore2007250Kotkin2014154_135-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"86"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"250"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"154"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200486Montefiore2007250Kotkin2014154-135" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 131;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[131]</span></a></sup> After two months, Stalin and Sverdlov escaped back to Saint Petersburg.<sup about="#mwt173" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199151Service200486–87Montefiore2007250–251_136-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"51"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"86–87"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"250–251"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199151Service200486–87Montefiore2007250–251-136" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 132;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[132]</span></a></sup>
During a brief period back in Tiflis, Stalin and the Outfit planned the ambush of a mail coach, during which most of the group—although not Stalin—were apprehended by the authorities.<sup about="#mwt174" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007252–253_137-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"252–253"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007252–253-137" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 133;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[133]</span></a></sup> Stalin returned to Saint Petersburg, where he continued editing and writing articles for <i id="mw7A">Pravda</i>.<sup about="#mwt175" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007255_138-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"255"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007255-138" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 134;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[134]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mw7Q"><a href="./File:Stalin_in_exile_1915.jpg" id="mw7g"><img resource="./File:Stalin_in_exile_1915.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Stalin_in_exile_1915.jpg/200px-Stalin_in_exile_1915.jpg" data-file-width="400" data-file-height="529" data-file-type="bitmap" height="265" width="200" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8f/Stalin_in_exile_1915.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/Stalin_in_exile_1915.jpg/300px-Stalin_in_exile_1915.jpg 1.5x" id="mw7w"/></a><figcaption id="mw8A">Stalin in 1915</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mw8Q">After the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_legislative_election,_1912" title="Russian legislative election, 1912" id="mw8g" class="mw-redirect">October 1912 Duma elections</a> resulted in six Bolsheviks and six Mensheviks being elected, Stalin wrote articles calling for reconciliation between the two Marxist factions, for which he was criticised by Lenin.<sup about="#mwt176" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007256_139-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"256"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007256-139" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 135;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[135]</span></a></sup> In late 1912, he twice crossed into the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Austro-Hungarian_Empire" title="Austro-Hungarian Empire" id="mw8w" class="mw-redirect">Austro-Hungarian Empire</a> to visit Lenin in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kraków" title="Kraków" id="mw9A">Kraków</a>,<sup about="#mwt177" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199152Service200487–88Montefiore2007256–259Kotkin2014133_140-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"52"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"87–88"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"256–259"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"133"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199152Service200487–88Montefiore2007256–259Kotkin2014133-140" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 136;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[136]</span></a></sup> eventually bowing to Lenin's opposition to reunification with the Mensheviks.<sup about="#mwt178" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007263_141-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"263"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007263-141" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 137;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[137]</span></a></sup> In January 1913 Stalin travelled to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vienna" title="Vienna" id="mw9Q">Vienna</a>,<sup about="#mwt179" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199154Service200489Montefiore2007263_142-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"54"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"89"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"263"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199154Service200489Montefiore2007263-142" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 138;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[138]</span></a></sup> there focusing on the 'national question' of how the Bolsheviks should deal with the Russian Empire's national and ethnic minorities.<sup about="#mwt180" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200489Montefiore2007264–265_143-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"89"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"264–265"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200489Montefiore2007264–265-143" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 139;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[139]</span></a></sup> Lenin wanted to attract these groups to the Bolshevik cause by offering them the right of secession from the Russian state, but at the same time hoped they would remain part of a future Bolshevik-governed Russia.<sup about="#mwt181" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007266_144-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"266"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007266-144" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 140;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[140]</span></a></sup> Stalin's finished article was titled <i id="mw9g"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Marxism_and_the_National_Question" title="Marxism and the National Question" id="mw9w">Marxism and the National Question</a></i>;<sup about="#mwt182" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199153Service200485Montefiore2007266Kotkin2014133_145-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"53"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"85"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"266"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"133"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199153Service200485Montefiore2007266Kotkin2014133-145" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 141;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[141]</span></a></sup> Lenin was very happy with it.<sup about="#mwt183" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007267_146-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"267"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007267-146" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 142;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[142]</span></a></sup> According to Montefiore, this was "Stalin's most famous work".<sup about="#mwt184" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007266_144-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"266"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007266-144" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 140;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[140]</span></a></sup> The article was published under the pseudonym of "K. Stalin",<sup about="#mwt185" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007267_146-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"267"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007267-146" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 142;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[142]</span></a></sup> a name he had been using since 1912.<sup about="#mwt186" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269Volkogonov19917Service200485_147-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Himmer"},"1y":{"wt":"1986"},"1p":{"wt":"269"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"7"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"85"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269Volkogonov19917Service200485-147" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 143;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[143]</span></a></sup> Derived from the Russian word for <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Steel" title="Steel" id="mw-A">steel</a> (<i id="mw-Q">stal</i>),<sup about="#mwt187" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269Service200485_148-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Himmer"},"1y":{"wt":"1986"},"1p":{"wt":"269"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"85"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269Service200485-148" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 144;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[144]</span></a></sup> this has been translated as "Man of Steel";<sup about="#mwt188" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269Volkogonov19917Montefiore2007268Kotkin2014133_149-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Himmer"},"1y":{"wt":"1986"},"1p":{"wt":"269"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"7"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"268"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"133"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269Volkogonov19917Montefiore2007268Kotkin2014133-149" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 145;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[145]</span></a></sup> Stalin may have intended it to imitate Lenin's pseudonym.<sup about="#mwt189" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269_150-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Himmer"},"2":{"wt":"1986"},"p":{"wt":"269"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269-150" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 146;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[146]</span></a></sup> Stalin retained this name for the rest of his life, possibly because it had been used on the article which established his reputation among the Bolsheviks.<sup about="#mwt190" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007267–268_151-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"267–268"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007267–268-151" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 147;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[147]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mw-g">In February 1913, Stalin was arrested while back in Saint Petersburg.<sup about="#mwt191" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007268–270Khlevniuk201528_152-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1pp":{"wt":"268–270"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"28"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007268–270Khlevniuk201528-152" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 148;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[148]</span></a></sup> He was sentenced to four years exile in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Turukhansk" title="Turukhansk" id="mw-w">Turukhansk</a>, a remote part of Siberia from which escape was particularly difficult.<sup about="#mwt192" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199154Service2004102–103Montefiore2007270,_273Khlevniuk201529_153-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"54"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"102–103"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"270, 273"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"29"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199154Service2004102–103Montefiore2007270,_273Khlevniuk201529-153" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 149;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[149]</span></a></sup> In August, he arrived in the village of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Monastyrskoe" title="Monastyrskoe" id="mw_A" class="new">Monastyrskoe</a>, although after four weeks was relocated to the hamlet of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kostino,_Krasnoyarsk_Krai" title="Kostino, Krasnoyarsk Krai" id="mw_Q" class="new">Kostino</a>.<sup about="#mwt193" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007273–274_154-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"273–274"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007273–274-154" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 150;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[150]</span></a></sup> In March 1914, concerned over a potential escape attempt, the authorities moved Stalin to the hamlet of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kureika_(village)" title="Kureika (village)" id="mw_g">Kureika</a> on the edge of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Arctic_Circle" title="Arctic Circle" id="mw_w">Arctic Circle</a>.<sup about="#mwt194" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199155Service2004105–106Montefiore2007277–278Khlevniuk201529_155-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"55"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"105–106"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"277–278"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"29"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199155Service2004105–106Montefiore2007277–278Khlevniuk201529-155" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 151;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[151]</span></a></sup> In the hamlet, Stalin had a relationship with Lidia Pereprygia, who was thirteen at the time and thus a year under the legal <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Age_of_consent" title="Age of consent" id="mwAQA">age of consent</a> in Tsarist Russia.<sup about="#mwt195" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004107Montefiore2007282–285Kotkin2014155Khlevniuk201530_156-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"107"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"282–285"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"155"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"30"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004107Montefiore2007282–285Kotkin2014155Khlevniuk201530-156" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 152;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[152]</span></a></sup> In or about December 1914, Pereprygia gave birth to Stalin's child, although the infant soon died.<sup about="#mwt196" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007292–293_157-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"292–293"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007292–293-157" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 153;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[153]</span></a></sup> She gave birth to another of his children, Alexander, circa April 1917.<sup about="#mwt197" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007298,_300_158-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"298, 300"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007298,_300-158" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 154;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[154]</span></a></sup> In Kureika, Stalin lived closely with the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Indigenous_peoples_of_Siberia" title="Indigenous peoples of Siberia" id="mwAQE">indigenous</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tunguses" title="Tunguses" id="mwAQI" class="mw-redirect">Tunguses</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ostyak" title="Ostyak" id="mwAQM">Ostyak</a>,<sup about="#mwt198" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007287_159-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"287"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007287-159" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 155;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[155]</span></a></sup> and spent much of his time fishing.<sup about="#mwt199" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199156Service2004110Montefiore2007288–289_160-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"56"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"110"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"288–289"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199156Service2004110Montefiore2007288–289-160" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 156;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[156]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="6" id="mwAQQ"><h3 id="The_Russian_Revolution:_1917">The Russian Revolution: 1917</h3>
<p id="mwAQU">While Stalin was in exile, Russia entered the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./First_World_War" title="First World War" id="mwAQY" class="mw-redirect">First World War</a>, and in October 1916 Stalin and other exiled Bolsheviks were <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Conscription_in_the_Russian_Empire" title="Conscription in the Russian Empire" id="mwAQc">conscripted into the Russian Army</a>, leaving for Monastyrskoe.<sup about="#mwt200" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199157Service2004113–114Montefiore2007300Kotkin2014155_161-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"57"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"113–114"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"300"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"155"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199157Service2004113–114Montefiore2007300Kotkin2014155-161" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 157;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[157]</span></a></sup> They arrived in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Krasnoyarsk" title="Krasnoyarsk" id="mwAQg">Krasnoyarsk</a> in February 1917,<sup about="#mwt201" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199157Montefiore2007301–302Kotkin2014155_162-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"57"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"301–302"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"155"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199157Montefiore2007301–302Kotkin2014155-162" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 158;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[158]</span></a></sup> where a medical examiner ruled Stalin unfit for military service due to his crippled arm.<sup about="#mwt202" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004114Montefiore2007302Kotkin2014155_163-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"114"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"302"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"155"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004114Montefiore2007302Kotkin2014155-163" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 159;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[159]</span></a></sup> Stalin was required to serve four more months on his exile, and he successfully requested that he serve it in nearby <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Achinsk" title="Achinsk" id="mwAQk">Achinsk</a>.<sup about="#mwt203" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004114Montefiore2007302_164-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"114"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"302"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004114Montefiore2007302-164" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 160;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[160]</span></a></sup> Stalin was in the city when the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./February_Revolution" title="February Revolution" id="mwAQo">February Revolution</a> took place; uprisings broke out in Petrograd—as Saint Petersburg had been renamed—and Tsar Nicholas II abdicated to escape being violently overthrown. The Russian Empire became a <i id="mwAQs">de facto</i> republic, headed by a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Provisional_Government" title="Russian Provisional Government" id="mwAQw">Provisional Government</a> dominated by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Liberalism" title="Liberalism" id="mwAQ0">liberals</a>.<sup about="#mwt204" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199157–58Service2004116–117Montefiore2007302–303Kotkin2014178Khlevniuk201542_165-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"57–58"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"116–117"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3pp":{"wt":"302–303"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"178"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"42"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199157–58Service2004116–117Montefiore2007302–303Kotkin2014178Khlevniuk201542-165" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 161;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[161]</span></a></sup> In a celebratory mood, Stalin travelled by train to Petrograd in March.<sup about="#mwt205" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199115,_19Service2004117Montefiore2007304Kotkin2014173_166-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"15, 19"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"117"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"304"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199115,_19Service2004117Montefiore2007304Kotkin2014173-166" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 162;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[162]</span></a></sup> There, Stalin and fellow Bolshevik <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lev_Kamenev" title="Lev Kamenev" id="mwAQ4">Lev Kamenev</a> assumed control of <i id="mwAQ8">Pravda</i>,<sup about="#mwt206" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199119Service2004120Montefiore2007310_167-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"19"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"120"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"310"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199119Service2004120Montefiore2007310-167" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 163;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[163]</span></a></sup> and Stalin was appointed the Bolshevik representative to the Executive Committee of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Petrograd_Soviet" title="Petrograd Soviet" id="mwARA">Petrograd Soviet</a>, an influential council of the city's workers.<sup about="#mwt207" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199159–60Montefiore2007310_168-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"59–60"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"310"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199159–60Montefiore2007310-168" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 164;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[164]</span></a></sup> In April, Stalin came third in the Bolshevik elections for the party's Central Committee; Lenin came first and Zinoviev came second.<sup about="#mwt208" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199164Service2004131Montefiore2007316Kotkin2014193Khlevniuk201546_169-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"64"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"131"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"316"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"193"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"46"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199164Service2004131Montefiore2007316Kotkin2014193Khlevniuk201546-169" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 165;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[165]</span></a></sup> This reflected his senior standing in the party at the time.<sup about="#mwt209" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007316_170-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"316"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007316-170" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 166;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[166]</span></a></sup></p>

<div class="quotebox pullquote floatleft " style="
    width:25em; 
    
;
     
    
    " about="#mwt210" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Quote box","href":"./Template:Quote_box"},"params":{"width":{"wt":"25em"},"align":{"wt":"left"},"quote":{"wt":"The existing government of landlords and capitalists must be replaced by a new government, a government of workers and peasants.&lt;br />The existing pseudo-government which was not elected by the people and which is not accountable to the people must be replaced by a government recognised by the people, elected by representatives of the workers, soldiers and peasants and held accountable to their representatives."},"source":{"wt":"— Stalin&apos;s editorial in &apos;&apos;Pravda&apos;&apos;, October 1917{{sfn|Service|2004|p=144}}"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwARE"><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r856303512" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" about="#mwt2514" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Template:Quote_box/styles.css"}}'>.mw-parser-output .quotebox{background-color:#F9F9F9;border:1px solid #aaa;box-sizing:border-box;padding:10px;font-size:88%}.mw-parser-output .quotebox.floatleft{margin:0.5em 1.4em 0.8em 0}.mw-parser-output .quotebox.floatright{margin:0.5em 0 0.8em 1.4em}.mw-parser-output .quotebox.centered{margin:0.5em auto 0.8em auto}.mw-parser-output .quotebox.floatleft p,.mw-parser-output .quotebox.floatright p{font-style:inherit}.mw-parser-output .quotebox-title{background-color:#F9F9F9;text-align:center;font-size:larger;font-weight:bold}.mw-parser-output .quotebox-quote.quoted:before{font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-weight:bold;font-size:large;color:gray;content:" “ ";vertical-align:-45%;line-height:0}.mw-parser-output .quotebox-quote.quoted:after{font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;font-weight:bold;font-size:large;color:gray;content:" ” ";line-height:0}.mw-parser-output .quotebox .left-aligned{text-align:left}.mw-parser-output .quotebox .right-aligned{text-align:right}.mw-parser-output .quotebox .center-aligned{text-align:center}.mw-parser-output .quotebox cite{display:block;font-style:normal}@media screen and (max-width:360px){.mw-parser-output .quotebox{min-width:100%;margin:0 0 0.8em!important;float:none!important}}</style>

<div class="quotebox-quote  left-aligned " style="
    ">The existing government of landlords and capitalists must be replaced by a new government, a government of workers and peasants.<br/>The existing pseudo-government which was not elected by the people and which is not accountable to the people must be replaced by a government recognised by the people, elected by representatives of the workers, soldiers and peasants and held accountable to their representatives.</div>
<p><cite class="left-aligned" style="">— Stalin's editorial in <i>Pravda</i>, October 1917<sup about="#mwt1118" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004144_171-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"FOOTNOTEService2004144"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004144-171"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004144-171" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 167;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[167]</span></a></sup></cite></p>
</div>

<p id="mwARI">Stalin helped organise the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./July_Days" title="July Days" id="mwARM">July Days</a> uprising, an armed display of strength by Bolshevik supporters.<sup about="#mwt211" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199165Montefiore2007319–320_172-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"65"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"319–320"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199165Montefiore2007319–320-172" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 168;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[168]</span></a></sup> After the demonstration was suppressed, the Provisional Government initiated a crackdown on the Bolsheviks, raiding <i id="mwARQ">Pravda</i>.<sup about="#mwt212" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200732_23-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"32"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200732-23" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 19;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[19]</span></a></sup> During this raid, Stalin smuggled Lenin out of the newspaper's office and took charge of the Bolshevik leader's safety, moving him between Petrograd safe houses before smuggling him to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Razliv" title="Razliv" id="mwARU" class="mw-redirect">Razliv</a>.<sup about="#mwt213" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007322–324Kotkin2014203Khlevniuk201548–49_173-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1pp":{"wt":"322–324"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"203"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"48–49"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007322–324Kotkin2014203Khlevniuk201548–49-173" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 169;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[169]</span></a></sup> In Lenin's absence, Stalin continued editing <i id="mwARY">Pravda</i> and served as acting leader of the Bolsheviks, overseeing the party's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./6th_Congress_of_the_Russian_Social_Democratic_Labour_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="6th Congress of the Russian Social Democratic Labour Party (Bolsheviks)" id="mwARc">Sixth Congress</a>, which was held covertly.<sup about="#mwt214" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007326Kotkin2014204_174-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"326"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"204"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007326Kotkin2014204-174" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 170;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[170]</span></a></sup> Lenin began calling for the Bolsheviks to seize power by toppling the Provisional Government in a <i id="mwARg"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Coup_d'état" title="Coup d'état" id="mwARk">coup d'état</a></i>. Stalin and fellow senior Bolshevik <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leon_Trotsky" title="Leon Trotsky" id="mwARo">Leon Trotsky</a> both endorsed Lenin's plan of action, but it was initially opposed by Kamenev and other party members.<sup about="#mwt215" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199168Service2004138_175-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"68"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"138"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4pp":{"wt":"331–332"},"5a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"5y":{"wt":"2014"},"5p":{"wt":"214"},"6a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"6y":{"wt":"2015"},"6p":{"wt":"50"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199168Service2004138-175" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 171;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[171]</span></a></sup> Lenin returned to Petrograd and secured a majority in favour of a <i id="mwARs">coup</i> at a meeting of the Central Committee on 10 October.<sup about="#mwt216" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007332–333,_335_176-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"332–333, 335"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007332–333,_335-176" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 172;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[172]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwARw">On 24 October, police raided the Bolshevik newspaper offices, smashing machinery and presses; Stalin salvaged some of this equipment to continue his activities.<sup about="#mwt217" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004144Montefiore2007337–338_177-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"144"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2pp":{"wt":"337–338"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004144Montefiore2007337–338-177" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 173;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[173]</span></a></sup> In the early hours of 25 October, Stalin joined Lenin in a Central Committee meeting in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Smolny_Institute" title="Smolny Institute" id="mwAR0">Smolny Institute</a>, from where the Bolshevik <i id="mwAR4">coup</i>—the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./October_Revolution" title="October Revolution" id="mwAR8">October Revolution</a>—was directed.<sup about="#mwt218" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004145Montefiore2007341_178-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"145"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"341"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004145Montefiore2007341-178" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 174;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[174]</span></a></sup> Bolshevik militia seized Petrograd's electric power station, main post office, state bank, telephone exchange, and several bridges.<sup about="#mwt219" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007341–342_179-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"341–342"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007341–342-179" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 175;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[175]</span></a></sup> A Bolshevik-controlled ship, the <i id="mwASA"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_cruiser_Aurora" title="Russian cruiser Aurora" id="mwASE">Aurora</a></i>, opened fire on the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Winter_Palace" title="Winter Palace" id="mwASI">Winter Palace</a>; the Provisional Government's assembled delegates surrendered and were arrested by the Bolsheviks.<sup about="#mwt220" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007344–346_180-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"344–346"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007344–346-180" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 176;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[176]</span></a></sup> Although he had been tasked with briefing the Bolshevik delegates of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./All-Russian_Congress_of_Soviets#Second_Congress" title="All-Russian Congress of Soviets" id="mwASM">Second Congress of Soviets</a> about the developing situation, Stalin's role in the coup had not been publicly visible.<sup about="#mwt221" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004145,_147_181-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"145, 147"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004145,_147-181" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 177;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[177]</span></a></sup> Trotsky and other later Bolshevik opponents of Stalin used this as evidence that his role in the <i id="mwASQ">coup</i> had been insignificant, although later historians reject this.<sup about="#mwt222" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004144–146Kotkin2014224Khlevniuk201552_182-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"144–146"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"224"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"52"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004144–146Kotkin2014224Khlevniuk201552-182" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 178;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[178]</span></a></sup> According to the historian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Oleg_Khlevniuk" title="Oleg Khlevniuk" id="mwASU">Oleg Khlevniuk</a>, Stalin "filled an important role [in the October Revolution]... as a senior Bolshevik, member of the party's Central Committee, and editor of its main newspaper";<sup about="#mwt223" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201553_183-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"53"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201553-183" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 179;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[179]</span></a></sup> the historian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stephen_Kotkin" title="Stephen Kotkin" id="mwASY">Stephen Kotkin</a> similarly noted that Stalin had been "in the thick of events" in the build-up to the <i id="mwASc">coup</i>.<sup about="#mwt224" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014177_184-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"177"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014177-184" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 180;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[180]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="7" id="mwASg"><h2 id="In_Lenin's_government"><span id="In_Lenin.27s_government" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>In Lenin's government</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt225" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Joseph Stalin in the Russian Revolution, Russian Civil War, and Polish–Soviet War"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwASk">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Joseph_Stalin_in_the_Russian_Revolution,_Russian_Civil_War,_and_Polish–Soviet_War" title="Joseph Stalin in the Russian Revolution, Russian Civil War, and Polish–Soviet War">Joseph Stalin in the Russian Revolution, Russian Civil War, and Polish–Soviet War</a></div>

<section data-mw-section-id="8" id="mwASo"><h3 id="Consolidating_power:_1917–1918"><span id="Consolidating_power:_1917.E2.80.931918" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Consolidating power: 1917–1918</h3>
<p id="mwASs">On 26 October, Lenin declared himself Chairman of a new government, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Council_of_People's_Commissars" title="Council of People's Commissars" id="mwASw">Council of People's Commissars</a> ("Sovnarkom").<sup about="#mwt226" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004147–148Kotkin2014227–228,_229Khlevniuk201552_185-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"147–148"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"227–228, 229"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"52"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004147–148Kotkin2014227–228,_229Khlevniuk201552-185" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 181;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[181]</span></a></sup> Stalin backed Lenin's decision not to form a coalition with the Mensheviks and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Socialist_Revolutionary_Party" title="Socialist Revolutionary Party" id="mwAS0">Socialist Revolutionary Party</a>, although they did form a coalition government with the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Left_Socialist_Revolutionaries" title="Left Socialist Revolutionaries" id="mwAS4" class="mw-redirect">Left Socialist Revolutionaries</a>.<sup about="#mwt227" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199128–29Service2004148_186-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"28–29"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"148"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199128–29Service2004148-186" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 182;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[182]</span></a></sup> Stalin became part of an informal foursome leading the government, alongside Lenin, Trotsky, and Sverdlov;<sup about="#mwt228" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Kotkin2014228_187-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"71"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"228"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Kotkin2014228-187" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 183;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[183]</span></a></sup> of these, Sverdlov was regularly absent, and died in March 1919.<sup about="#mwt229" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199171,_90Kotkin2014318_188-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"71, 90"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"318"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199171,_90Kotkin2014318-188" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 184;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[184]</span></a></sup> Stalin's office was based near to Lenin's in the Smolny Institute,<sup about="#mwt230" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Kotkin2014229_189-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"71"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"229"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Kotkin2014229-189" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 185;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[185]</span></a></sup> and he and Trotsky were the only individuals allowed access to Lenin's study without an appointment.<sup about="#mwt231" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200327Kotkin2014226_190-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"27"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"226"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200327Kotkin2014226-190" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 186;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[186]</span></a></sup> Although not so publicly well known as Lenin or Trotsky,<sup about="#mwt232" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004150_191-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"150"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004150-191" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 187;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[187]</span></a></sup> Stalin's importance among the Bolsheviks grew.<sup about="#mwt233" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003157_192-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"157"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003157-192" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 188;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[188]</span></a></sup> He co-signed Lenin's decrees shutting down hostile newspapers,<sup about="#mwt234" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004149_193-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"149"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004149-193" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 189;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[189]</span></a></sup> and with Sverdlov chaired the sessions of the committee drafting <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Constitution_of_1918" title="Russian Constitution of 1918" id="mwAS8">a constitution</a> for the new <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Soviet_Federative_Socialist_Republic" title="Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic" id="mwATA">Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic</a>.<sup about="#mwt235" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004155_194-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"155"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004155-194" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 190;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[190]</span></a></sup> He strongly supported Lenin's formation of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cheka" title="Cheka" id="mwATE">Cheka</a> security service and the subsequent <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Red_Terror" title="Red Terror" id="mwATI">Red Terror</a> that it initiated; noting that state violence had proved an effective tool for capitalist powers, he believed that it would prove the same for the Soviet government.<sup about="#mwt236" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004158_195-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"158"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004158-195" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 191;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[191]</span></a></sup> Unlike senior Bolsheviks like Kamenev and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikolai_Bukharin" title="Nikolai Bukharin" id="mwATM">Nikolai Bukharin</a>, Stalin never expressed concern about the rapid growth and expansion of the Cheka and Terror.<sup about="#mwt237" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004158_195-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"158"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004158-195" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 191;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[191]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwATQ"><a href="./File:Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg" id="mwATU"><img resource="./File:Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg/220px-Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg" data-file-width="700" data-file-height="552" data-file-type="bitmap" height="173" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg/440px-Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg/330px-Kremlin_birds_eye_view-1.jpg 1.5x" id="mwATY"/></a><figcaption id="mwATc">The Moscow Kremlin, which Stalin moved into in 1918</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwATg">Having dropped his editorship of <i id="mwATk">Pravda</i>,<sup about="#mwt257" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004148_196-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"148"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004148-196" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 192;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[192]</span></a></sup> Stalin was appointed the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./People's_Commissar" title="People's Commissar" id="mwATo" class="mw-redirect">People's Commissar</a> for Nationalities.<sup about="#mwt258" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199170Volkogonov199130Service2004148Kotkin2014228Khlevniuk201552_197-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"70"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"30"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"148"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"228"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"52"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199170Volkogonov199130Service2004148Kotkin2014228Khlevniuk201552-197" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 193;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[193]</span></a></sup> He took <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nadezhda_Alliluyeva" title="Nadezhda Alliluyeva" id="mwATs">Nadezhda Alliluyeva</a> as his secretary,<sup about="#mwt259" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199172Service2004151_198-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"72"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"151"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199172Service2004151-198" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 194;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[194]</span></a></sup> and at some point married her, although the wedding date is unknown.<sup about="#mwt260" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199172Service2004167Kotkin2014264Khlevniuk201549_199-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"72"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"167"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"264"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"49"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199172Service2004167Kotkin2014264Khlevniuk201549-199" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 195;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[195]</span></a></sup> In November 1917, he signed the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Declaration_of_the_Rights_of_the_Peoples_of_Russia" title="Declaration of the Rights of the Peoples of Russia" id="mwATw">Decree on Nationality</a>, according ethnic and national minorities living in Russia the right of secession and self-determination.<sup about="#mwt261" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199171_200-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"71"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199171-200" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 196;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[196]</span></a></sup> The decree's purpose was primarily strategic; the Bolsheviks wanted to gain favour among ethnic minorities but hoped that the latter would not actually desire independence.<sup about="#mwt262" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Service2004152_201-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"71"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"152"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Service2004152-201" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 197;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[197]</span></a></sup> That month, he travelled to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Helsinki" title="Helsinki" id="mwAT0">Helsinki</a> to talk with the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Social_Democratic_Party_of_Finland" title="Social Democratic Party of Finland" id="mwAT4">Finnish Social-Democrats</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Independence_of_Finland" title="Independence of Finland" id="mwAT8">granting Finland's request for independence in December</a>.<sup about="#mwt263" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Service2004152_201-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"71"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"152"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199171Service2004152-201" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 197;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[197]</span></a></sup> His department allocated funds for the establishment of presses and schools in the languages of various ethnic minorities.<sup about="#mwt264" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004153_202-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"153"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004153-202" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 198;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[198]</span></a></sup> Socialist Revolutionaries accused Stalin's talk of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Federalism" title="Federalism" id="mwAUA">federalism</a> and national self-determination as a front for Sovnarkom's centralising and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Imperialism" title="Imperialism" id="mwAUE">imperialist</a> policies.<sup about="#mwt265" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004155_194-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"155"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004155-194" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 190;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[190]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAUI">Due to the ongoing First World War, in which Russia was fighting the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Central_Powers" title="Central Powers" id="mwAUM">Central Powers</a> of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./German_Empire" title="German Empire" id="mwAUQ">Germany</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Austria-Hungary" title="Austria-Hungary" id="mwAUU">Austria-Hungary</a>, Lenin's government relocated from Petrograd to Moscow in March 1918. There, they based themselves in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moscow_Kremlin" title="Moscow Kremlin" id="mwAUY">Kremlin</a>; it was here that Stalin, Trotsky, Sverdlov, and Lenin lived.<sup about="#mwt266" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199172Service2004150–151Kotkin2014259–264_203-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"72"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"150–151"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"259–264"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199172Service2004150–151Kotkin2014259–264-203" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 199;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[199]</span></a></sup> Stalin supported Lenin's desire to sign an armistice with the Central Powers regardless of the cost in territory.<sup about="#mwt267" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199175Service2004158–161Kotkin2014250_204-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"75"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"158–161"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"250"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199175Service2004158–161Kotkin2014250-204" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 200;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[200]</span></a></sup> Stalin thought it necessary because—unlike Lenin—he was unconvinced that Europe was on the verge of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Proletarian_revolution" title="Proletarian revolution" id="mwAUc">proletarian revolution</a>.<sup about="#mwt268" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004159–160Kotkin2014250_205-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"159–160"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"250"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004159–160Kotkin2014250-205" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 201;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[201]</span></a></sup> Lenin eventually convinced the other senior Bolsheviks of his viewpoint, resulting in the signing of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Treaty_of_Brest-Litovsk_(Russia–Central_Powers)" title="Treaty of Brest-Litovsk (Russia–Central Powers)" id="mwAUg" class="mw-redirect">Treaty of Brest-Litovsk</a> in March 1918.<sup about="#mwt269" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199175Service2004161Kotkin2014257–258_206-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"75"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"161"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"257–258"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199175Service2004161Kotkin2014257–258-206" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 202;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[202]</span></a></sup> The treaty gave vast areas of land and resources to the Central Powers and angered many in Russia; the Left Socialist Revolutionaries withdrew from the coalition government over the issue.<sup about="#mwt270" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004161Kotkin2014258–259,_265_207-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"161"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"258–259, 265"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004161Kotkin2014258–259,_265-207" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 203;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[203]</span></a></sup> The governing RSDLP party was soon renamed, becoming the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwAUk">Russian Communist Party</a>.<sup about="#mwt271" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014259_208-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"259"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014259-208" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 204;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[204]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="9" id="mwAUo"><h3 id="Military_Command:_1918–1921"><span id="Military_Command:_1918.E2.80.931921" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Military Command: 1918–1921</h3>
<p id="mwAUs">After the Bolsheviks seized power, both right and left-wing armies rallied against them, generating the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_Civil_War" title="Russian Civil War" id="mwAUw">Russian Civil War</a>.<sup about="#mwt272" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004165Kotkin2014268–270_209-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"165"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"268–270"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004165Kotkin2014268–270-209" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 205;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[205]</span></a></sup> To secure access to the dwindling food supply, in May 1918 Sovnarkom sent Stalin to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Volgograd" title="Volgograd" id="mwAU0">Tsaritsyn</a> to take charge of food procurement in southern Russia.<sup about="#mwt273" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199177Volkogonov199139Montefiore200327Service2004163Kotkin2014300–301Khlevniuk201554_210-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"77"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"39"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2003"},"3p":{"wt":"27"},"4a1":{"wt":"Service"},"4y":{"wt":"2004"},"4p":{"wt":"163"},"5a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"5y":{"wt":"2014"},"5pp":{"wt":"300–301"},"6a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"6y":{"wt":"2015"},"6p":{"wt":"54"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199177Volkogonov199139Montefiore200327Service2004163Kotkin2014300–301Khlevniuk201554-210" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 206;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[206]</span></a></sup> Eager to prove himself as a commander,<sup about="#mwt274" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004173_211-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004173-211" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 207;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[207]</span></a></sup> once there he took control of regional military operations.<sup about="#mwt275" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004164Kotkin2014302–303_212-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"164"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"302–303"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004164Kotkin2014302–303-212" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 208;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[208]</span></a></sup> He befriended two military figures, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kliment_Voroshilov" title="Kliment Voroshilov" id="mwAU4">Kliment Voroshilov</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Semyon_Budyonny" title="Semyon Budyonny" id="mwAU8">Semyon Budyonny</a>, who would form the nucleus of his military and political support base.<sup about="#mwt276" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199178,_82Montefiore200728Khlevniuk201555_213-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"78, 82"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"28"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"55"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199178,_82Montefiore200728Khlevniuk201555-213" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 209;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[209]</span></a></sup> Believing that victory was assured by numerical superiority, he sent large numbers of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Red_Army" title="Red Army" id="mwAVA">Red Army</a> troops into battle against the region's anti-Bolshevik <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./White_movement" title="White movement" id="mwAVE">White armies</a>, resulting in heavy losses; Lenin was concerned by this costly tactic.<sup about="#mwt277" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199181Service2004170_214-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"81"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"170"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199181Service2004170-214" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 210;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[210]</span></a></sup> In Tsaritsyn, Stalin commanded the local Cheka branch to execute suspected counter-revolutionaries, sometimes without trial,<sup about="#mwt278" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199146Montefiore200727Kotkin2014305,_307Khlevniuk201556–57_215-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"46"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"27"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"305, 307"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"56–57"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199146Montefiore200727Kotkin2014305,_307Khlevniuk201556–57-215" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 211;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[211]</span></a></sup> and—in contravention of government orders—purged the military and food collection agencies of middle-class specialists, some of whom he also executed.<sup about="#mwt279" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199178–79Volkogonov199140Service2004166Khlevniuk201555_216-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"78–79"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"40"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"166"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"55"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199178–79Volkogonov199140Service2004166Khlevniuk201555-216" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 212;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[212]</span></a></sup> His use of state violence and terror was at a greater scale than most Bolshevik leaders approved of;<sup about="#mwt280" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004171_217-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"171"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004171-217" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 213;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[213]</span></a></sup> for instance, he ordered several villages to be torched to ensure compliance with his food procurement program.<sup about="#mwt281" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004169_218-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"169"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004169-218" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 214;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[214]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAVI"><a href="./File:Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg" id="mwAVM"><img resource="./File:Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg/325px-Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg" data-file-width="880" data-file-height="456" data-file-type="bitmap" height="168" width="325" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg/650px-Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg/488px-Stalin-Lenin-Kalinin-1919.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAVQ"/></a><figcaption id="mwAVU">Joseph Stalin, Lenin, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mikhail_Kalinin" title="Mikhail Kalinin" id="mwAVY">Mikhail Kalinin</a> meeting in 1919. All three of them were "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Old_Bolsheviks" title="Old Bolsheviks" id="mwAVc" class="mw-redirect">Old Bolsheviks</a>"—members of the Bolshevik party before the October Revolution.</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAVg">In December 1918, Stalin was sent to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Perm" title="Perm" id="mwAVk">Perm</a> to lead an inquiry into how <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Alexander_Kolchak" title="Alexander Kolchak" id="mwAVo">Alexander Kolchak</a>'s White forces had been able to decimate Red troops based there.<sup about="#mwt282" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199183–84Service2004172Kotkin2014314_219-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"83–84"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"172"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"314"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199183–84Service2004172Kotkin2014314-219" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 215;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[215]</span></a></sup> He returned to Moscow between January and March 1919,<sup about="#mwt283" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004172_220-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"172"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004172-220" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 216;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[216]</span></a></sup> before being assigned to the Western Front at Petrograd.<sup about="#mwt284" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199185Service2004172_221-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"85"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"172"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199185Service2004172-221" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 217;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[217]</span></a></sup> When the Red Third Regiment defected, he ordered the public execution of captured defectors.<sup about="#mwt285" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004172_220-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"172"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004172-220" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 216;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[216]</span></a></sup> In September he was returned to the Southern Front.<sup about="#mwt286" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004172_220-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"172"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004172-220" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 216;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[216]</span></a></sup> During the war, he proved his worth to the Central Committee, displaying decisiveness, determination, and a willingness to take on responsibility in conflict situations.<sup about="#mwt287" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004173_211-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004173-211" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 207;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[207]</span></a></sup> At the same time, he disregarded orders and repeatedly threatened to resign when affronted.<sup about="#mwt288" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004173,_174_222-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"173, 174"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004173,_174-222" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 218;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[218]</span></a></sup> In November 1919, the government awarded him the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Order_of_the_Red_Banner" title="Order of the Red Banner" id="mwAVs">Order of the Red Banner</a> for his wartime service.<sup about="#mwt289" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199186Volkogonov199145Kotkin2014331_223-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"86"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"45"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"331"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199186Volkogonov199145Kotkin2014331-223" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 219;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[219]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAVw">The Bolsheviks had won the civil war by late 1919.<sup about="#mwt290" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004175_224-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"175"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004175-224" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 220;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[220]</span></a></sup> Sovnarkom turned its attention to spreading proletarian revolution abroad, to this end forming the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_International" title="Communist International" id="mwAV0">Communist International</a> in March 1919; Stalin attended its inaugural ceremony.<sup about="#mwt291" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199191Service2004175_225-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"91"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"175"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199191Service2004175-225" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 221;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[221]</span></a></sup> Although Stalin did not share Lenin's belief that Europe's proletariat were on the verge of revolution, he acknowledged that as long as it stood alone, Soviet Russia remained vulnerable.<sup about="#mwt292" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004176_226-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"176"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004176-226" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 222;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[222]</span></a></sup> In December 1918, he drew up decrees recognising Marxist-governed Soviet republics in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Commune_of_the_Working_People_of_Estonia" title="Commune of the Working People of Estonia" id="mwAV4">Estonia</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lithuanian_Soviet_Socialist_Republic_(1918–19)" title="Lithuanian Soviet Socialist Republic (1918–19)" id="mwAV8">Lithuania</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Latvian_Socialist_Soviet_Republic" title="Latvian Socialist Soviet Republic" id="mwAWA">Latvia</a>;<sup about="#mwt293" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004199_227-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"199"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004199-227" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 223;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[223]</span></a></sup> during the civil war these Marxist governments were overthrown and the Baltic countries became fully independent of Russia, an act Stalin regarded as illegitimate.<sup about="#mwt294" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004203,_190_228-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"203, 190"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004203,_190-228" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 224;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[224]</span></a></sup> In February 1920, he was appointed to head the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Workers'_and_Peasants'_Inspectorate" title="Workers' and Peasants' Inspectorate" id="mwAWE" class="mw-redirect">Workers' and Peasants' Inspectorate</a>;<sup about="#mwt295" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004174_229-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"174"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004174-229" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 225;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[225]</span></a></sup> that same month he was also transferred to the Caucasian Front.<sup about="#mwt296" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004178_230-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"178"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004178-230" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 226;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[226]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAWI">Following <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_westward_offensive_of_1918–19" title="Soviet westward offensive of 1918–19" id="mwAWM">earlier clashes</a> between Polish and Russian troops, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Polish–Soviet_War" title="Polish–Soviet War" id="mwAWQ">Polish–Soviet War</a> broke out in early 1920, with the Poles invading Ukraine and taking <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kiev" title="Kiev" id="mwAWU">Kiev</a>.<sup about="#mwt297" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004176Kotkin2014352–354_231-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"176"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"352–354"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004176Kotkin2014352–354-231" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 227;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[227]</span></a></sup> Stalin was moved to Ukraine, on the Southwest Front.<sup about="#mwt298" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004178Kotkin2014357Khlevniuk201559_232-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"178"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"357"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"59"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004178Kotkin2014357Khlevniuk201559-232" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 228;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[228]</span></a></sup> The Red Army forced the Polish troops back into Poland.<sup about="#mwt299" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004176–177_233-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"176–177"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004176–177-233" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 229;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[229]</span></a></sup> Lenin believed that the Polish proletariat would rise up to support the Russians against <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Józef_Piłsudski" title="Józef Piłsudski" id="mwAWY">Józef Piłsudski</a>'s Polish government. Stalin had cautioned against this; he believed that <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Polish_nationalism" title="Polish nationalism" id="mwAWc">nationalism</a> would lead the Polish working-classes to support their government's war effort. He also believed that the Red Army was ill-prepared to conduct an offensive war and that it would give White Armies a chance to resurface in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Crimea" title="Crimea" id="mwAWg">Crimea</a>, potentially reigniting the civil war.<sup about="#mwt300" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004177_234-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"177"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004177-234" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 230;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[230]</span></a></sup> Stalin lost the argument, after which he accepted Lenin's decision and supported it.<sup about="#mwt301" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004178_230-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"178"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004178-230" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 226;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[226]</span></a></sup> Along the Southwest Front, he became determined to conquer <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lwów" title="Lwów" id="mwAWk" class="mw-redirect">Lwów</a>; in focusing on this goal he disobeyed orders to transfer his troops to assist <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mikhail_Tukhachevsky" title="Mikhail Tukhachevsky" id="mwAWo">Mikhail Tukhachevsky</a>'s forces.<sup about="#mwt302" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199187Service2004179Kotkin2014362Khlevniuk201560_235-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"87"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"179"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"362"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"60"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199187Service2004179Kotkin2014362Khlevniuk201560-235" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 231;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[231]</span></a></sup> In August, the Poles <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Battle_of_Warsaw_(1920)" title="Battle of Warsaw (1920)" id="mwAWs">repulsed the Russian advance</a> and Stalin returned to Moscow.<sup about="#mwt303" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004180,_182_236-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"180, 182"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004180,_182-236" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 232;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[232]</span></a></sup> A <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Peace_of_Riga" title="Peace of Riga" id="mwAWw">Polish-Soviet peace treaty</a> was signed; Stalin saw this as a failure for which he blamed Trotsky.<sup about="#mwt304" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004183_237-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"183"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004183-237" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 233;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[233]</span></a></sup> In turn, Trotsky accused Stalin of "strategic mistakes" in his handling of the war at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./9th_Congress_of_the_Russian_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="9th Congress of the Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks)" id="mwAW0">Ninth Bolshevik Conference</a>.<sup about="#mwt305" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDavies2003211Service2004183–185Kotkin2014376–377_238-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"211"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"183–185"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"376–377"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDavies2003211Service2004183–185Kotkin2014376–377-238" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 234;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[234]</span></a></sup> Stalin felt resentful and under-appreciated; in September he demanded demission from the military, which was granted.<sup about="#mwt306" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004182–183Kotkin2014365_239-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"182–183"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"365"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004182–183Kotkin2014365-239" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 235;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[235]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="10" id="mwAW4"><h3 id="Lenin's_final_years:_1921–1923"><span id="Lenin.27s_final_years:_1921.E2.80.931923" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Lenin's final years: 1921–1923</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAW8"><a href="./File:Lenin_and_stalin_crop.jpg" id="mwAXA"><img resource="./File:Lenin_and_stalin_crop.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Lenin_and_stalin_crop.jpg/220px-Lenin_and_stalin_crop.jpg" data-file-width="394" data-file-height="452" data-file-type="bitmap" height="252" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e3/Lenin_and_stalin_crop.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e3/Lenin_and_stalin_crop.jpg/330px-Lenin_and_stalin_crop.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAXE"/></a><figcaption id="mwAXI">Stalin (right) confers with an ailing Lenin at Gorky in September 1922</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAXM">The Soviet government sought to bring neighbouring states under its domination; <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Red_Army_invasion_of_Georgia" title="Red Army invasion of Georgia" id="mwAXQ">in February 1921 it invaded</a> the Menshevik-governed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Democratic_Republic_of_Georgia" title="Democratic Republic of Georgia" id="mwAXU">Georgia</a>,<sup about="#mwt308" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014396–397_240-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"pp":{"wt":"396–397"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014396–397-240" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 236;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[236]</span></a></sup> while in April 1921, Stalin ordered the Red Army into <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Turkestan_Autonomous_Soviet_Socialist_Republic" title="Turkestan Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republic" id="mwAXY">Turkestan</a> to reassert Russian state control.<sup about="#mwt309" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014388_241-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"388"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014388-241" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 237;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[237]</span></a></sup> As People's Commissar for Nationalities, Stalin believed that each national and ethnic group should have the right to self-expression,<sup about="#mwt310" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004202_242-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"202"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004202-242" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 238;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[238]</span></a></sup> facilitated through "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Autonomous_Soviet_Socialist_Republics_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Autonomous Soviet Socialist Republics of the Soviet Union" id="mwAXc">autonomous republics</a>" within the Russian state in which they could oversee various regional affairs.<sup about="#mwt311" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004199–200Kotkin2014371_243-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"199–200"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"371"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004199–200Kotkin2014371-243" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 239;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[239]</span></a></sup> In taking this view, some Marxists accused him of bending too much to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bourgeois_nationalism" title="Bourgeois nationalism" id="mwAXg">bourgeois nationalism</a>, while others accused him of remaining too Russocentric by seeking to retain these nations within the Russian state.<sup about="#mwt312" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004202_242-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"202"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004202-242" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 238;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[238]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAXk">Stalin's native Caucasus posed a particular problem due to its highly multi-ethnic mix.<sup about="#mwt313" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004200_244-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"200"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004200-244" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 240;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[240]</span></a></sup> Stalin opposed the idea of separate Georgian, Armenian, and Azerbaijani autonomous republics, arguing that these would likely oppress ethnic minorities within their respective territories; instead he called for a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Transcaucasian_Socialist_Federative_Soviet_Republic" title="Transcaucasian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic" id="mwAXo">Transcaucasian Socialist Federative Soviet Republic</a>.<sup about="#mwt314" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004194–196Kotkin2014400_245-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"194–196"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"400"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004194–196Kotkin2014400-245" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 241;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[241]</span></a></sup> The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_of_Georgia_(Soviet_Union)" title="Communist Party of Georgia (Soviet Union)" id="mwAXs">Georgian Communist Party</a> opposed the idea, resulting in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgian_Affair" title="Georgian Affair" id="mwAXw" class="mw-redirect">Georgian Affair</a>.<sup about="#mwt315" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004194–195Kotkin2014479–481_246-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"194–195"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"479–481"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004194–195Kotkin2014479–481-246" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 242;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[242]</span></a></sup> In mid-1921, Stalin returned to the southern Caucasus, there calling on Georgian Communists to avoid the chauvinistic Georgian nationalism which marginalised the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Abkhazians" title="Abkhazians" id="mwAX0">Abkhazian</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ossetian_people" title="Ossetian people" id="mwAX4" class="mw-redirect">Ossetian</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Adjarians" title="Adjarians" id="mwAX8">Adjarian</a> minorities in Georgia.<sup about="#mwt316" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004203–205Kotkin2014400_247-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"203–205"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"400"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004203–205Kotkin2014400-247" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 243;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[243]</span></a></sup> On this trip, Stalin met with his son Yakov, and brought him back to Moscow;<sup about="#mwt317" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004232_248-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"127"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"232"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004232-248" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 244;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[244]</span></a></sup> Nadya had given birth to another of Stalin's sons, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vasily_Stalin" title="Vasily Stalin" id="mwAYA">Vasily</a>, in March 1921.<sup about="#mwt318" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004232_248-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"127"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"232"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004232-248" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 244;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[244]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAYE">After the civil war, workers' strikes and peasant uprisings broke out across Russia, largely in opposition to Sovnarkom's food requisitioning project; as an antidote, Lenin introduced market-oriented reforms: the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./New_Economic_Policy" title="New Economic Policy" id="mwAYI">New Economic Policy</a> (NEP).<sup about="#mwt319" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199189Service2004187Kotkin2014344Khlevniuk201564_249-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"89"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"187"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"344"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"64"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199189Service2004187Kotkin2014344Khlevniuk201564-249" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 245;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[245]</span></a></sup> There was also internal turmoil in the Communist Party, as Trotsky led a faction calling for the abolition of trade unions; Lenin opposed this and Stalin helped rally opposition to Trotsky's position.<sup about="#mwt320" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004186_250-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"186"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004186-250" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 246;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[246]</span></a></sup> Stalin also agreed to supervise the Department of Agitation and Propaganda in the Central Committee Secretariat.<sup about="#mwt321" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004188_251-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"188"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004188-251" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 247;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[247]</span></a></sup> At the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./11th_Congress_of_the_Russian_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="11th Congress of the Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks)" id="mwAYM">11th Party Congress</a> in 1922, Lenin nominated Stalin as the party's new <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./General_Secretary_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="General Secretary of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwAYQ">General Secretary</a>. Although concerns were expressed that adopting this new post on top of his others would overstretch his workload and give him too much power, Stalin was appointed to the position.<sup about="#mwt322" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199196Volkogonov199178–70Service2004189–190Kotkin2014411_252-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"96"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"78–70"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"189–190"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"411"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199196Volkogonov199178–70Service2004189–190Kotkin2014411-252" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 248;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[248]</span></a></sup> For Lenin, it was advantageous to have a key ally in this crucial post.<sup about="#mwt323" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004190_253-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"190"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004190-253" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 249;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[249]</span></a></sup></p>

<div class="quotebox pullquote floatleft " style="
    width:25em; 
    
;
     
    
    " about="#mwt324" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Quote box ","href":"./Template:Quote_box"},"params":{"width":{"wt":"25em"},"align":{"wt":"left"},"quote":{"wt":"Stalin is too crude, and this defect which is entirely acceptable in our milieu and in relationships among us as communists, becomes unacceptable in the position of General Secretary. I therefore propose to comrades that they should devise a means of removing him from this job and should appoint to this job someone else who is distinguished from comrade Stalin in all other respects only by the single superior aspect that he should be more tolerant, more polite and more attentive towards comrades, less capricious, etc."},"source":{"wt":"— Lenin&apos;s Testament, 4 January 1923;{{sfnm|1a1=Service|1y=2000|1p=369|2a1=Service|2y=2004|2p=209|3a1=Kotkin|3y=2014|3p=504}} this was possibly composed by Krupskaya rather than Lenin himself.{{sfn|Kotkin|2014|p=501}}"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAYU"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r856303512" about="#mwt2516" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Template:Quote_box/styles.css"}}'/>

<div class="quotebox-quote  left-aligned " style="
    ">Stalin is too crude, and this defect which is entirely acceptable in our milieu and in relationships among us as communists, becomes unacceptable in the position of General Secretary. I therefore propose to comrades that they should devise a means of removing him from this job and should appoint to this job someone else who is distinguished from comrade Stalin in all other respects only by the single superior aspect that he should be more tolerant, more polite and more attentive towards comrades, less capricious, etc.</div>
<p><cite class="left-aligned" style="">— Lenin's Testament, 4 January 1923;<sup about="#mwt2120" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2000369Service2004209Kotkin2014504_254-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"FOOTNOTEService2000369Service2004209Kotkin2014504"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2000369Service2004209Kotkin2014504-254"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2000369Service2004209Kotkin2014504-254" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 250;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[250]</span></a></sup> this was possibly composed by Krupskaya rather than Lenin himself.<sup about="#mwt2122" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014501_255-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"FOOTNOTEKotkin2014501"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014501-255"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014501-255" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 251;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[251]</span></a></sup></cite></p>
</div>

<p id="mwAYY">In May 1922, a massive stroke left Lenin partially paralysed.<sup about="#mwt325" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199197Volkogonov199153Service2004191_256-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"97"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"53"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"191"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199197Volkogonov199153Service2004191-256" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 252;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[252]</span></a></sup> Residing at his <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Gorki_Leninskiye" title="Gorki Leninskiye" id="mwAYc">Gorki dacha</a>, Lenin's main connection to Sovnarkom was through Stalin, who was a regular visitor.<sup about="#mwt326" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004191–192Kotkin2014413_257-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"191–192"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"413"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004191–192Kotkin2014413-257" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 253;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[253]</span></a></sup> Lenin twice asked Stalin to procure poison so that he could commit suicide, but Stalin never did so.<sup about="#mwt327" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004192Kotkin2014414Khlevniuk201568_258-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"192"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"414"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"68"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004192Kotkin2014414Khlevniuk201568-258" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 254;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[254]</span></a></sup> Despite this comradeship, Lenin disliked what he referred to as Stalin's "Asiatic" manner, and told his sister <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Maria_Ilyinichna_Ulyanova" title="Maria Ilyinichna Ulyanova" id="mwAYg">Maria</a> that Stalin was "not intelligent".<sup about="#mwt328" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991102Service2004191–192Kotkin2014528_259-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"102"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"191–192"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"528"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991102Service2004191–192Kotkin2014528-259" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 255;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[255]</span></a></sup> Lenin and Stalin argued on the issue of foreign trade; Lenin believed that the Soviet state should have a monopoly on foreign trade, but Stalin supported <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Grigori_Sokolnikov" title="Grigori Sokolnikov" id="mwAYk">Grigori Sokolnikov</a>'s view that doing so was impractical at that stage.<sup about="#mwt329" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199198Service2004193Kotkin2014483Khlevniuk201569–70_260-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"98"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"193"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"483"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"69–70"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199198Service2004193Kotkin2014483Khlevniuk201569–70-260" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 256;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[256]</span></a></sup> Another disagreement came over the Georgian Affair, with Lenin backing the Georgian Central Committee's desire for a Georgian Soviet Republic over Stalin's idea of a Transcaucasian one.<sup about="#mwt330" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199195Service2004195Khlevniuk201571–72_261-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"95"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"195"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"71–72"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199195Service2004195Khlevniuk201571–72-261" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 257;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[257]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAYo">They also disagreed on the nature of the Soviet state. Lenin called for the country to be renamed the "Union of Soviet Republics of Europe and Asia", reflecting his desire for expansion across the two continents. Stalin believed this would encourage independence sentiment among non-Russians, instead arguing that ethnic minorities would be content as "autonomous republics" within the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic.<sup about="#mwt331" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199171Service2004194Kotkin2014475–476Khlevniuk201568–69_262-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"71"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"194"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"475–476"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"68–69"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199171Service2004194Kotkin2014475–476Khlevniuk201568–69-262" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 258;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[258]</span></a></sup> Lenin accused Stalin of "Great Russian chauvinism"; Stalin accused Lenin of "national liberalism".<sup about="#mwt332" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199198–99Service2004195Kotkin2014477,_478Khlevniuk201569_263-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"98–99"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"195"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"477, 478"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"69"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199198–99Service2004195Kotkin2014477,_478Khlevniuk201569-263" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 259;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[259]</span></a></sup> A compromise was reached, in which the country would be renamed the "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Union_of_Soviet_Socialist_Republics" title="Union of Soviet Socialist Republics" id="mwAYs" class="mw-redirect">Union of Soviet Socialist Republics</a>" (USSR).<sup about="#mwt333" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004195_264-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"195"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004195-264" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 260;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[260]</span></a></sup> The USSR's formation was ratified in December 1922; although officially a federal system, all major decisions were taken by the governing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Politburo_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Politburo of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwAYw">Politburo of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union</a> in Moscow.<sup about="#mwt334" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199174Service2004206Kotkin2014485_265-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"74"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"206"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"485"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199174Service2004206Kotkin2014485-265" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 261;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[261]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAY0">Their differences also became personal; Lenin was particularly angered when Stalin was rude to his wife Krupskaya during a telephone conversation.<sup about="#mwt335" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199199–100,_103Volkogonov199172–74Service2004210–211Khlevniuk201570–71_266-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"99–100, 103"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"72–74"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"210–211"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"70–71"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199199–100,_103Volkogonov199172–74Service2004210–211Khlevniuk201570–71-266" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 262;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[262]</span></a></sup> In the final years of his life, Krupskaya provided governing figures with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lenin's_Testament" title="Lenin's Testament" id="mwAY4">Lenin's Testament</a>, a series of increasingly disparaging notes about Stalin. These criticized Stalin's rude manners and excessive power, suggesting that Stalin should be removed from the position of General Secretary.<sup about="#mwt336" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991100–101Volkogonov199153,_79–82Service2004208–209Khlevniuk201571_267-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"100–101"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"53, 79–82"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"208–209"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"71"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991100–101Volkogonov199153,_79–82Service2004208–209Khlevniuk201571-267" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 263;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[263]</span></a></sup> Some historians have questioned whether Lenin ever produced these, suggesting instead that they may have been written by Krupskaya, who had personal differences with Stalin;<sup about="#mwt337" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014501_255-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"501"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014501-255" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 251;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[251]</span></a></sup> Stalin, however, never publicly voiced concerns about their authenticity.<sup about="#mwt338" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014528_268-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"528"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014528-268" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 264;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[264]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="11" id="mwAY8"><h2 id="Rise_to_power">Rise to power</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt339" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Rise of Joseph Stalin"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAZA">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Rise_of_Joseph_Stalin" title="Rise of Joseph Stalin">Rise of Joseph Stalin</a></div>

<section data-mw-section-id="12" id="mwAZE"><h3 id="Succeeding_Lenin:_1924–1927"><span id="Succeeding_Lenin:_1924.E2.80.931927" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Succeeding Lenin: 1924–1927</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAZI"><a href="./File:Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg" id="mwAZM"><img resource="./File:Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg/220px-Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg" data-file-width="2090" data-file-height="2422" data-file-type="bitmap" height="255" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg/440px-Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6e/Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg/330px-Stalin_Rykov_Kamenev_Zinoviev_1925.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAZQ"/></a><figcaption id="mwAZU">(From left to right) Stalin, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Alexei_Rykov" title="Alexei Rykov" id="mwAZY">Alexei Rykov</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lev_Kamenev" title="Lev Kamenev" id="mwAZc">Lev Kamenev</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Grigori_Zinoviev" title="Grigori Zinoviev" id="mwAZg" class="mw-redirect">Grigori Zinoviev</a> in 1925</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAZk">Lenin died in January 1924.<sup about="#mwt340" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991104Montefiore200330Service2004219Kotkin2014534Khlevniuk201579_269-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"104"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"30"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"219"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"534"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"79"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991104Montefiore200330Service2004219Kotkin2014534Khlevniuk201579-269" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 265;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[265]</span></a></sup> Stalin took charge of the funeral and was one of its pallbearers; against the wishes of Lenin's widow, the Politburo embalmed his corpse and placed it within a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lenin's_Mausoleum" title="Lenin's Mausoleum" id="mwAZo">mausoleum</a> in Moscow's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Red_Square" title="Red Square" id="mwAZs">Red Square</a>.<sup about="#mwt341" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991110Montefiore200330Service2004219Kotkin2014542–543_270-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"110"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"30"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"219"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4pp":{"wt":"542–543"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991110Montefiore200330Service2004219Kotkin2014542–543-270" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 266;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[266]</span></a></sup> It was incorporated into a growing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Personality_cult" title="Personality cult" id="mwAZw" class="mw-redirect">personality cult</a> devoted to Lenin, with Petrograd being renamed "Leningrad" that year.<sup about="#mwt342" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991130Montefiore200330Service2004221Kotkin2014540_271-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"130"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"30"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"221"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"540"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991130Montefiore200330Service2004221Kotkin2014540-271" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 267;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[267]</span></a></sup> To bolster his image as a devoted Leninist, Stalin gave nine lectures at <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sverdlov_University" title="Sverdlov University" id="mwAZ0" class="mw-redirect">Sverdlov University</a> on the "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Foundations_of_Leninism" title="Foundations of Leninism" id="mwAZ4">Foundations of Leninism</a>", later published in book form.<sup about="#mwt343" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991111–112Volkogonov1991117–118Service2004221Kotkin2014544_272-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"111–112"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"117–118"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"221"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"544"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991111–112Volkogonov1991117–118Service2004221Kotkin2014544-272" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 268;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[268]</span></a></sup> At the following <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./13th_Congress_of_the_Russian_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="13th Congress of the Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks)" id="mwAZ8">13th Party Congress</a>, "Lenin's Testament" was read to senior figures. Embarrassed by its contents, Stalin offered his resignation as General Secretary; this act of humility saved him and he was retained in the position.<sup about="#mwt344" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991111Volkogonov199193–94Service2004222–224Kotkin2014546–548Khlevniuk201579_273-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"111"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"93–94"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"222–224"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4pp":{"wt":"546–548"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"79"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991111Volkogonov199193–94Service2004222–224Kotkin2014546–548Khlevniuk201579-273" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 269;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[269]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAaA">As General Secretary, Stalin had had a free hand in making appointments to his own staff, implanting his loyalists throughout the party and administration.<sup about="#mwt345" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014426_274-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"426"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014426-274" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 270;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[270]</span></a></sup> Favouring new Communist Party members, many from worker and peasant backgrounds, to the "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Old_Bolsheviks" title="Old Bolsheviks" id="mwAaE" class="mw-redirect">Old Bolsheviks</a>" who tended to be university educated,<sup about="#mwt346" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014453_275-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"453"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014453-275" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 271;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[271]</span></a></sup> he ensured he had loyalists dispersed across the country's regions.<sup about="#mwt347" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014455_276-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"455"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014455-276" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 272;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[272]</span></a></sup> Stalin had much contact with young party functionaries,<sup about="#mwt348" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014469_277-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"469"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014469-277" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 273;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[273]</span></a></sup> and the desire for promotion led many provincial figures to seek to impress Stalin and gain his favour.<sup about="#mwt349" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014432_278-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"432"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014432-278" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 274;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[274]</span></a></sup> Stalin also developed close relations with the trio at the heart of the secret police (first the Cheka and then its replacement, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./State_Political_Directorate" title="State Political Directorate" id="mwAaI">State Political Directorate</a>): <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Felix_Dzerzhinsky" title="Felix Dzerzhinsky" id="mwAaM">Felix Dzerzhinsky</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Genrikh_Yagoda" title="Genrikh Yagoda" id="mwAaQ">Genrikh Yagoda</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vyacheslav_Menzhinsky" title="Vyacheslav Menzhinsky" id="mwAaU">Vyacheslav Menzhinsky</a>.<sup about="#mwt350" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014495–496_279-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"pp":{"wt":"495–496"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014495–496-279" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 275;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[275]</span></a></sup> In his private life, he divided his time between his Kremlin apartment and a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dacha" title="Dacha" id="mwAaY">dacha</a> at <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Zubalova" title="Zubalova" id="mwAac" class="new">Zubalova</a>;<sup about="#mwt351" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004235_280-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"127"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"235"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004235-280" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 276;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[276]</span></a></sup> his wife gave birth to a daughter, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Svetlana_Alliluyeva" title="Svetlana Alliluyeva" id="mwAag">Svetlana</a>, in February 1926.<sup about="#mwt352" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004238_281-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"127"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"238"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991127Service2004238-281" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 277;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[277]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAak">In the wake of Lenin's death, various protagonists emerged in the struggle to become his successor: alongside Stalin was Trotsky, Zinoviev, Kamenev, Bukharin, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Alexei_Rykov" title="Alexei Rykov" id="mwAao">Alexei Rykov</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mikhail_Tomsky" title="Mikhail Tomsky" id="mwAas">Mikhail Tomsky</a>.<sup about="#mwt353" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFainsodHough1979111_282-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Fainsod"},"2":{"wt":"Hough"},"3":{"wt":"1979"},"p":{"wt":"111"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFainsodHough1979111-282" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 278;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[278]</span></a></sup> Stalin saw Trotsky—whom he personally despised<sup about="#mwt354" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991136_283-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"136"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991136-283" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 279;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[279]</span></a></sup>—as the main obstacle to his dominance within the party.<sup about="#mwt355" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200327_284-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"27"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200327-284" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 280;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[280]</span></a></sup> While Lenin had been ill he had forged an anti-Trotsky alliance with Kamenev and Zinoviev.<sup about="#mwt356" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199198Kotkin2014474Khlevniuk201552_285-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"98"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"474"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"52"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199198Kotkin2014474Khlevniuk201552-285" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 281;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[281]</span></a></sup> Although Zinoviev was concerned about Stalin's growing authority, he rallied behind him at the 13th Congress as a counterweight to Trotsky, who now led a party faction known as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Left_Opposition" title="Left Opposition" id="mwAaw">Left Opposition</a>.<sup about="#mwt357" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004214–215,_217_286-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"214–215, 217"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004214–215,_217-286" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 282;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[282]</span></a></sup> The Left Opposition believed the NEP conceded too much to capitalism; Stalin was called a "rightist" for his support of the policy.<sup about="#mwt358" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201587_287-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"87"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201587-287" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 283;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[283]</span></a></sup> Stalin built up a retinue of his supporters in the Central Committee,<sup about="#mwt359" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004225_288-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"225"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004225-288" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 284;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[284]</span></a></sup> while the Left Opposition were gradually removed from their positions of influence.<sup about="#mwt360" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004227_289-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"227"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004227-289" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 285;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[285]</span></a></sup> He was supported in this by Bukharin, who like Stalin believed that the Left Opposition's proposals would plunge the Soviet Union into instability.<sup about="#mwt361" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004228_290-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"228"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004228-290" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 286;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[286]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAa0"><a href="./File:Ordzhonikidze,_Stalin_and_Mikoyan,_1925.jpg" id="mwAa4"><img resource="./File:Ordzhonikidze,_Stalin_and_Mikoyan,_1925.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Ordzhonikidze%2C_Stalin_and_Mikoyan%2C_1925.jpg/220px-Ordzhonikidze%2C_Stalin_and_Mikoyan%2C_1925.jpg" data-file-width="1500" data-file-height="1060" data-file-type="bitmap" height="155" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Ordzhonikidze%2C_Stalin_and_Mikoyan%2C_1925.jpg/440px-Ordzhonikidze%2C_Stalin_and_Mikoyan%2C_1925.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8c/Ordzhonikidze%2C_Stalin_and_Mikoyan%2C_1925.jpg/330px-Ordzhonikidze%2C_Stalin_and_Mikoyan%2C_1925.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAa8"/></a><figcaption id="mwAbA">Stalin and his close associates <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anastas_Mikoyan" title="Anastas Mikoyan" id="mwAbE">Anastas Mikoyan</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sergo_Ordzhonikidze" title="Sergo Ordzhonikidze" id="mwAbI">Sergo Ordzhonikidze</a> in Tbilisi, 1925</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAbM">In late 1924, Stalin moved against Kamenev and Zinoviev, removing their supporters from key positions.<sup about="#mwt362" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004228Kotkin2014563_291-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"228"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"563"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004228Kotkin2014563-291" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 287;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[287]</span></a></sup> In 1925, Kamenev and Zinoviev moved into open opposition of Stalin and Bukharin.<sup about="#mwt363" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004340_292-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"340"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004340-292" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 288;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[288]</span></a></sup> They attacked one another at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./14th_Congress_of_the_All-Union_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="14th Congress of the All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks)" id="mwAbQ">14th Party Congress</a>, where Stalin accused Kamenev and Zinoviev of reintroducing factionalism—and thus instability—into the party.<sup about="#mwt364" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004240–243Khlevniuk201582–83_293-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"240–243"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"82–83"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004240–243Khlevniuk201582–83-293" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 289;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[289]</span></a></sup> In mid-1926, Kamenev and Zinoviev joined with Trotsky's supporters to form the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./United_Opposition" title="United Opposition" id="mwAbU">United Opposition</a> against Stalin;<sup about="#mwt365" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991126Conquest200811Kotkin2014614Khlevniuk201583_294-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"126"},"2a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2y":{"wt":"2008"},"2p":{"wt":"11"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"614"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"83"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991126Conquest200811Kotkin2014614Khlevniuk201583-294" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 290;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[290]</span></a></sup> in October they agreed to stop factional activity under threat of expulsion, and later publicly recanted their views under Stalin's command.<sup about="#mwt366" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991137,_138Kotkin2014614_295-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"137, 138"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"614"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991137,_138Kotkin2014614-295" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 291;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[291]</span></a></sup> The factionalist arguments continued, with Stalin threatening to resign in October and then December 1926 and again in December 1927.<sup about="#mwt367" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004247Kotkin2014614,_618Khlevniuk201591_296-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"247"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"614, 618"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"91"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004247Kotkin2014614,_618Khlevniuk201591-296" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 292;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[292]</span></a></sup> In October 1927, Zinoviev and Trotsky were removed from the Central Committee;<sup about="#mwt368" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201585_297-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"85"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201585-297" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 293;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[293]</span></a></sup> the latter was exiled to Kazakhstan and later deported from the country in 1929.<sup about="#mwt369" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991139,_151Service2004282–283Conquest200811–12Kotkin2014676–677Khlevniuk201585_298-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"139, 151"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"282–283"},"3a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"3y":{"wt":"2008"},"3pp":{"wt":"11–12"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4pp":{"wt":"676–677"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"85"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991139,_151Service2004282–283Conquest200811–12Kotkin2014676–677Khlevniuk201585-298" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 294;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[294]</span></a></sup> Some of those United Opposition members who were repentant were later rehabilitated and returned to government.<sup about="#mwt370" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991164Service2004282_299-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"164"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"282"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991164Service2004282-299" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 295;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[295]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAbY">Stalin was now the party's supreme leader,<sup about="#mwt371" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004276_300-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"276"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004276-300" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 296;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[296]</span></a></sup> although was not the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Head_of_government" title="Head of government" id="mwAbc">head of government</a>, a task he entrusted to key ally <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vyacheslav_Molotov" title="Vyacheslav Molotov" id="mwAbg">Vyacheslav Molotov</a>.<sup about="#mwt372" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004277–278_301-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"277–278"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004277–278-301" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 297;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[297]</span></a></sup> Other important supporters on the Politburo were Voroshilov, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lazar_Kaganovich" title="Lazar Kaganovich" id="mwAbk">Lazar Kaganovich</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sergo_Ordzhonikidze" title="Sergo Ordzhonikidze" id="mwAbo">Sergo Ordzhonikidze</a>,<sup about="#mwt373" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004277,_280Conquest200812–13_302-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"277, 280"},"2a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2y":{"wt":"2008"},"2pp":{"wt":"12–13"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004277,_280Conquest200812–13-302" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 298;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[298]</span></a></sup> with Stalin ensuring his allies ran the various state institutions.<sup about="#mwt374" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004278_303-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"278"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004278-303" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 299;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[299]</span></a></sup> According to Montefiore, at this point "Stalin was the leader of the oligarchs but he was far from a dictator".<sup about="#mwt375" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200339_304-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"39"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200339-304" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 300;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[300]</span></a></sup> His growing influence was reflected in the naming of various locations after him; in June 1924 the Ukrainian mining town of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Yuzovka" title="Yuzovka" id="mwAbs" class="mw-redirect">Yuzovka</a> became Stalino,<sup about="#mwt376" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991130_305-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"130"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991130-305" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 301;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[301]</span></a></sup> and in April 1925, Tsaritsyn was renamed Stalingrad on the order of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mikhail_Kalinin" title="Mikhail Kalinin" id="mwAbw">Mikhail Kalinin</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Avel_Enukidze" title="Avel Enukidze" id="mwAb0" class="mw-redirect">Avel Enukidze</a>.<sup about="#mwt377" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991130Volkogonov1991160Kotkin2014689_306-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"130"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"160"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"689"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991130Volkogonov1991160Kotkin2014689-306" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 302;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[302]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAb4">In 1926, Stalin published <i id="mwAb8">On Questions of Leninism</i>.<sup about="#mwt378" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004244_307-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"244"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004244-307" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 303;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[303]</span></a></sup> Here, he introduced the concept of "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Socialism_in_One_Country" title="Socialism in One Country" id="mwAcA">Socialism in One Country</a>", which he presented as an orthodox Leninist perspective. It nevertheless clashed with established Bolshevik views that socialism could not be established in one country but could only be achieved globally through the process of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./World_revolution" title="World revolution" id="mwAcE">world revolution</a>.<sup about="#mwt379" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004244_307-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"244"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004244-307" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 303;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[303]</span></a></sup> In 1927, there was some argument in the party over Soviet policy regarding China. Stalin had called for the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_of_China" title="Communist Party of China" id="mwAcI">Communist Party of China</a>, led by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mao_Zedong" title="Mao Zedong" id="mwAcM">Mao Zedong</a>, to ally itself with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chiang_Kai-shek" title="Chiang Kai-shek" id="mwAcQ">Chiang Kai-shek</a>'s <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kuomintang" title="Kuomintang" id="mwAcU">Kuomintang</a> (KMT) nationalists, viewing a Communist-Kuomintang alliance as the best bulwark against Japanese imperial expansionism. Instead, the KMT repressed the Communists and a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chinese_civil_war" title="Chinese civil war" id="mwAcY" class="mw-redirect">civil war broke out</a> between the two sides.<sup about="#mwt380" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004392Kotkin2014626–631Khlevniuk201589–90_308-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"392"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2pp":{"wt":"626–631"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"89–90"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004392Kotkin2014626–631Khlevniuk201589–90-308" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 304;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[304]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="13" id="mwAcc"><h3 id="Dekulakisation,_collectivisation,_and_industrialisation:_1927–1931"><span id="Dekulakisation.2C_collectivisation.2C_and_industrialisation:_1927.E2.80.931931" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Dekulakisation, collectivisation, and industrialisation: 1927–1931</h3>

<section data-mw-section-id="14" id="mwAcg"><h4 id="Economic_policy">Economic policy</h4>
<div class="quotebox pullquote floatright " style="
    width:25em; 
    
;
     
    
    " about="#mwt381" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Quote box","href":"./Template:Quote_box"},"params":{"width":{"wt":"25em"},"align":{"wt":"right"},"quote":{"wt":"We have fallen behind the advanced countries by fifty to a hundred years. We must close that gap in ten years. Either we do this or we&apos;ll be crushed.\n\nThis is what our obligations before the workers and peasants of the USSR dictate to us."},"source":{"wt":"— Stalin, February 1931{{sfn|Service|2004|p=273}}"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAck"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r856303512" about="#mwt2518" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Template:Quote_box/styles.css"}}'/>

<div class="quotebox-quote  left-aligned " style="
    ">We have fallen behind the advanced countries by fifty to a hundred years. We must close that gap in ten years. Either we do this or we'll be crushed.

This is what our obligations before the workers and peasants of the USSR dictate to us.</div>
<p><cite class="left-aligned" style="">— Stalin, February 1931<sup about="#mwt2124" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004273_309-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"FOOTNOTEService2004273"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004273-309"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004273-309" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 305;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[305]</span></a></sup></cite></p>
</div>

<p id="mwAco">The Soviet Union lagged behind the industrial development of Western countries,<sup about="#mwt382" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004256_310-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"256"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004256-310" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 306;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[306]</span></a></sup> and there had been a shortfall of grain; 1927 produced only 70% of grain produced in 1926.<sup about="#mwt383" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004254_311-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"254"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004254-311" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 307;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[307]</span></a></sup> Stalin's government feared attack from Japan, France, the United Kingdom, Poland, and Romania.<sup about="#mwt384" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991172–173Service2004256Kotkin2014638–639_312-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"172–173"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"256"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"638–639"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991172–173Service2004256Kotkin2014638–639-312" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 308;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[308]</span></a></sup> Many Communists, including in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Komsomol" title="Komsomol" id="mwAcs">Komsomol</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./OGPU" title="OGPU" id="mwAcw" class="mw-redirect">OGPU</a>, and the Red Army, were eager to be rid of the NEP and its market-oriented approach;<sup about="#mwt385" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991144,_146Service2004258_313-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"144, 146"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"258"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991144,_146Service2004258-313" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 309;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[309]</span></a></sup> they had concerns about those who profited from the policy: affluent peasants known as "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kulak" title="Kulak" id="mwAc0">kulaks</a>" and the small business owners or "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nepmen" title="Nepmen" id="mwAc4" class="mw-redirect">Nepmen</a>".<sup about="#mwt386" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004256Kotkin2014571_314-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"256"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"571"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004256Kotkin2014571-314" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 310;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[310]</span></a></sup> At this point, Stalin turned against the NEP, putting him on a course to the "left" even of Trotsky or Zinoviev.<sup about="#mwt387" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004253Khlevniuk2015101_315-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"253"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"101"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004253Khlevniuk2015101-315" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 311;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[311]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAc8">In early 1928 Stalin travelled to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Novosibirsk" title="Novosibirsk" id="mwAdA">Novosibirsk</a>, where he alleged that kulaks were hoarding their grain and ordered that the kulaks be arrested and their grain confiscated, with Stalin bringing much of the area's grain back to Moscow with him in February.<sup about="#mwt388" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991147–148Service2004257–258Kotkin2014661,_668–669,_679–684Khlevniuk2015102–103_316-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"147–148"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"257–258"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"661, 668–669, 679–684"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"102–103"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991147–148Service2004257–258Kotkin2014661,_668–669,_679–684Khlevniuk2015102–103-316" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 312;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[312]</span></a></sup> At his command, grain procurement squads surfaced across Western Siberia and the Urals, with violence breaking out between these squads and the peasantry.<sup about="#mwt389" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004258Khlevniuk2015103_317-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"258"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"103"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004258Khlevniuk2015103-317" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 313;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[313]</span></a></sup> Stalin announced that both kulaks and the "middle peasants" must be coerced into releasing their harvest.<sup about="#mwt390" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004258_318-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"258"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004258-318" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 314;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[314]</span></a></sup> Bukharin and several other Central Committee members were angry that they had not been consulted about this measure, which they deemed rash.<sup about="#mwt391" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004258Khlevniuk2015105_319-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"258"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"105"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004258Khlevniuk2015105-319" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 315;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[315]</span></a></sup> In January 1930, the Politburo approved the liquidation of the kulak class; accused kulaks were rounded up and exiled to other parts of the country or to concentration camps.<sup about="#mwt392" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004267_320-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"267"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004267-320" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 316;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[316]</span></a></sup> Large numbers died during the journey.<sup about="#mwt393" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991160Volkogonov1991166_321-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"160"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"166"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991160Volkogonov1991166-321" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 317;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[317]</span></a></sup> By July 1930, over 320,000 households had been affected by the de-kulakisation policy.<sup about="#mwt394" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004267_320-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"267"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004267-320" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 316;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[316]</span></a></sup> According to Stalin biographer <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dmitri_Volkogonov" title="Dmitri Volkogonov" id="mwAdE">Dmitri Volkogonov</a>, de-kulakisation was "the first mass terror applied by Stalin in his own country".<sup about="#mwt395" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991167_322-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"167"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991167-322" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 318;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[318]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAdI"><a href="./File:Stakhanov.JPG" id="mwAdM"><img resource="./File:Stakhanov.JPG" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Stakhanov.JPG/220px-Stakhanov.JPG" data-file-width="4060" data-file-height="2678" data-file-type="bitmap" height="145" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Stakhanov.JPG/440px-Stakhanov.JPG 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Stakhanov.JPG/330px-Stakhanov.JPG 1.5x" id="mwAdQ"/></a><figcaption id="mwAdU"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aleksei_Grigorievich_Stakhanov" title="Aleksei Grigorievich Stakhanov" id="mwAdY" class="mw-redirect">Aleksei Grigorievich Stakhanov</a> with a fellow miner; Stalin's government initiated the Stakhanovite movement to encourage hard work. It was partly responsible for a substantial rise in production during the 1930s.<sup about="#mwt396" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999231_323-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"231"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999231-323" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 319;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[319]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAdc">In 1929, the Politburo announced the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Collectivization_in_the_Soviet_Union" title="Collectivization in the Soviet Union" id="mwAdg">mass collectivisation of agriculture</a>,<sup about="#mwt397" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004265–266Khlevniuk2015110–111_324-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"265–266"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"110–111"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004265–266Khlevniuk2015110–111-324" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 320;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[320]</span></a></sup> establishing both <i id="mwAdk"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kolkhozy" title="Kolkhozy" id="mwAdo" class="mw-redirect">kolkhozy</a></i> collective farms and <i id="mwAds"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sovkhoz" title="Sovkhoz" id="mwAdw">sovkhoz</a></i> state farms.<sup about="#mwt398" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999234_325-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"234"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999234-325" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 321;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[321]</span></a></sup> Stalin barred kulaks from joining these collectives.<sup about="#mwt399" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004266Khlevniuk2015112_326-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"266"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"112"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004266Khlevniuk2015112-326" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 322;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[322]</span></a></sup> Although officially voluntary, many peasants joined the collectives out of fear they would face the fate of the kulaks; others joined amid intimidation and violence from party loyalists.<sup about="#mwt400" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015113_327-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"113"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015113-327" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 323;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[323]</span></a></sup>
By 1932, about 62% of households involved in agriculture were part of collectives, and by 1936 this had risen to 90%.<sup about="#mwt401" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004271_328-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"271"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004271-328" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 324;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[324]</span></a></sup> Many of the collectivised peasants resented the loss of their private farmland,<sup about="#mwt402" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004270_329-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"270"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004270-329" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 325;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[325]</span></a></sup> and productivity slumped.<sup about="#mwt403" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004270Khlevniuk2015116_330-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"270"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"116"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004270Khlevniuk2015116-330" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 326;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[326]</span></a></sup> Famine broke out in many areas,<sup about="#mwt404" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004272Khlevniuk2015116_331-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"272"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"116"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004272Khlevniuk2015116-331" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 327;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[327]</span></a></sup> with the Politburo frequently ordering the distribution of emergency food relief to these regions.<sup about="#mwt405" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004272_332-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"272"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004272-332" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 328;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[328]</span></a></sup> Armed peasant uprisings against dekulakisation and collectivisation broke out in Ukraine, northern Caucasus, southern Russia, and central Asia, reaching their apex in March 1930; these were suppressed by the Red Army.<sup about="#mwt406" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004270Khlevniuk2015113–114_333-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"270"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"113–114"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004270Khlevniuk2015113–114-333" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 329;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[329]</span></a></sup> Stalin responded to the uprisings with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dizzy_with_Success" title="Dizzy with Success" id="mwAd0">an article</a> insisting that collectivisation was voluntary and blaming any violence and other excesses on local officials.<sup about="#mwt407" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991160Khlevniuk2015114_334-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"160"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"114"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991160Khlevniuk2015114-334" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 330;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[330]</span></a></sup> Although he and Stalin had been close for many years,<sup about="#mwt408" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991174_335-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"174"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991174-335" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 331;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[331]</span></a></sup> Bukharin expressed concerns about these policies; he regarded them as a return to Lenin's old "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./War_communism" title="War communism" id="mwAd4">war communism</a>" policy and believed that it would fail. By mid-1928 he was unable to rally sufficient support in the party to oppose the reforms.<sup about="#mwt409" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991172Service2004260Kotkin2014708_336-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"172"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"260"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3p":{"wt":"708"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991172Service2004260Kotkin2014708-336" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 332;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[332]</span></a></sup> In November 1929 Stalin removed him from the Politburo.<sup about="#mwt410" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991158Service2004266Conquest200818_337-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"158"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"266"},"3a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"3y":{"wt":"2008"},"3p":{"wt":"18"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991158Service2004266Conquest200818-337" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 333;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[333]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAd8">Officially, the Soviet Union had replaced the "irrationality" and "wastefulness" of a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Market_economy" title="Market economy" id="mwAeA">market economy</a> with a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Planned_economy" title="Planned economy" id="mwAeE">planned economy</a> organised along a long-term, precise, and scientific framework; in reality, Soviet economics were based on <i id="mwAeI">ad hoc</i> commandments issued from the centre, often to make short-term targets.<sup about="#mwt411" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999227,_229_338-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"pp":{"wt":"227, 229"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999227,_229-338" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 334;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[334]</span></a></sup> In 1928, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./First_five-year_plan" title="First five-year plan" id="mwAeM">first five-year plan</a> was launched, its main focus on boosting heavy industry;<sup about="#mwt412" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004259_339-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"259"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004259-339" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 335;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[335]</span></a></sup> it was finished a year ahead of schedule, in 1932.<sup about="#mwt413" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004274_340-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"274"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004274-340" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 336;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[336]</span></a></sup> The USSR underwent a massive economic transformation.<sup about="#mwt414" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004265_341-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"265"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004265-341" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 337;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[337]</span></a></sup> New mines were opened, new cities like <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Magnitogorsk" title="Magnitogorsk" id="mwAeQ">Magnitogorsk</a> constructed, and work on the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./White_Sea-Baltic_Canal" title="White Sea-Baltic Canal" id="mwAeU" class="mw-redirect">White Sea-Baltic Canal</a> begun.<sup about="#mwt415" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004265_341-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"265"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004265-341" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 337;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[337]</span></a></sup> Millions of peasants moved to the cities, although urban house building could not keep up with the demand.<sup about="#mwt416" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004265_341-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"265"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004265-341" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 337;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[337]</span></a></sup> Large debts were accrued purchasing foreign-made machinery.<sup about="#mwt417" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015118_342-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"118"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015118-342" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 338;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[338]</span></a></sup> Many of the major construction projects, including the White Sea-Baltic Canal and the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moscow_Metro" title="Moscow Metro" id="mwAeY">Moscow Metro</a>, were constructed largely through forced labour.<sup about="#mwt418" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991186,_190_343-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"pp":{"wt":"186, 190"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991186,_190-343" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 339;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[339]</span></a></sup> The last elements of workers' control over industry were removed, with factory managers increasing their authority and receiving privileges and perks;<sup about="#mwt419" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999231–233_344-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"pp":{"wt":"231–233"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999231–233-344" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 340;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[340]</span></a></sup> Stalin defended wage disparity by pointing to Marx's argument that it was necessary during the lower stages of socialism.<sup about="#mwt420" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999241–242_345-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"pp":{"wt":"241–242"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999241–242-345" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 341;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[341]</span></a></sup> To promote the intensification of labour, a series of medals and awards as well as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stakhanovite_movement" title="Stakhanovite movement" id="mwAec">Stakhanovite movement</a> were introduced.<sup about="#mwt421" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999231_323-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"231"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999231-323" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 319;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[319]</span></a></sup> Stalin's message was that socialism was being established in the USSR while capitalism was crumbling amid the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wall_Street_crash" title="Wall Street crash" id="mwAeg" class="mw-redirect">Wall Street crash</a>.<sup about="#mwt422" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004269_346-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"269"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004269-346" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 342;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[342]</span></a></sup> His speeches and articles reflected his <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Utopianism" title="Utopianism" id="mwAek" class="mw-redirect">utopian</a> vision of the Soviet Union rising to unparalleled heights of human development, creating a "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./New_Soviet_man" title="New Soviet man" id="mwAeo">new Soviet person</a>". <sup about="#mwt423" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004300_347-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"300"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004300-347" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 343;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[343]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="15" id="mwAes"><h4 id="Cultural_and_foreign_policy">Cultural and foreign policy</h4>
<p id="mwAew">In 1928, Stalin declared that class war between the proletariat and their enemies would intensify as socialism developed.<sup about="#mwt424" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991152–153Sandle1999214Khlevniuk2015107–108_348-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"152–153"},"2a1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2y":{"wt":"1999"},"2p":{"wt":"214"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"107–108"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991152–153Sandle1999214Khlevniuk2015107–108-348" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 344;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[344]</span></a></sup> He warned of a "danger from the right", including in the Communist Party itself.<sup about="#mwt425" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015108_349-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"108"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015108-349" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 345;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[345]</span></a></sup> The first major <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Show_trial" title="Show trial" id="mwAe0">show trial</a> in the USSR was the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Shakhty_Trial" title="Shakhty Trial" id="mwAe4">Shakhty Trial</a> of 1928, in which several middle-class "industrial specialists" were convicted of sabotage.<sup about="#mwt426" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991152–155Service2004259Kotkin2014687,_702–704,_709Khlevniuk2015107_350-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"152–155"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"259"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"687, 702–704, 709"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"107"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991152–155Service2004259Kotkin2014687,_702–704,_709Khlevniuk2015107-350" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 346;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[346]</span></a></sup> From 1929 to 1930, further show trials were held to intimidate opposition:<sup about="#mwt427" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004268_351-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"268"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004268-351" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 347;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[347]</span></a></sup> these included the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Industrial_Party_Trial" title="Industrial Party Trial" id="mwAe8">Industrial Party Trial</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./1931_Menshevik_Trial" title="1931 Menshevik Trial" id="mwAfA">Menshevik Trial</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Metro-Vickers_Affair" title="Metro-Vickers Affair" id="mwAfE">Metro-Vickers Trial</a>.<sup about="#mwt428" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991155_352-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"155"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991155-352" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 348;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[348]</span></a></sup> Aware that the ethnic Russian majority may have concerns about being ruled by a Georgian,<sup about="#mwt429" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004324_353-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"324"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004324-353" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 349;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[349]</span></a></sup> he promoted ethnic Russians throughout the state hierarchy and made the Russian language compulsory throughout schools and offices, albeit to be used in tandem with local languages in areas with non-Russian majorities.<sup about="#mwt430" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004326_354-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"326"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004326-354" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 350;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[350]</span></a></sup> Nationalist sentiment among ethnic minorities was suppressed.<sup about="#mwt431" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004301_355-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"301"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004301-355" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 351;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[351]</span></a></sup> Conservative social policies were promoted to enhance social discipline and boost population growth; this included a focus on strong family units and motherhood, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./LGBT_rights_in_the_Soviet_Union" title="LGBT rights in the Soviet Union" id="mwAfI" class="mw-redirect">re-criminalisation of homosexuality</a>, restrictions placed on abortion and divorce, and the abolition of the <i id="mwAfM"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Zhenotdel" title="Zhenotdel" id="mwAfQ">Zhenotdel</a></i> women's department.<sup about="#mwt432" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999244,_246_356-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"pp":{"wt":"244, 246"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999244,_246-356" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 352;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[352]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAfU"><a href="./File:Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg" id="mwAfY"><img resource="./File:Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg/220px-Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="610" data-file-type="bitmap" height="168" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg/440px-Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/72/Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg/330px-Christ_saviour_explosion.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAfc"/></a><figcaption id="mwAfg">Photograph taken of the 1931 demolition of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cathedral_of_Christ_the_Saviour" title="Cathedral of Christ the Saviour" id="mwAfk">Cathedral of Christ the Saviour</a> in Moscow in order to make way for the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Palace_of_the_Soviets" title="Palace of the Soviets" id="mwAfo">Palace of the Soviets</a></figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAfs">Stalin desired a "cultural revolution",<sup about="#mwt433" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004299_357-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"299"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004299-357" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 353;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[353]</span></a></sup> entailing both the creation of a culture for the "masses" and the wider dissemination of previously elite culture.<sup about="#mwt434" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004304_358-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"304"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004304-358" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 354;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[354]</span></a></sup> He oversaw the proliferation of schools, newspapers, and libraries, as well as the advancement of literacy and numeracy.<sup about="#mwt435" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991111,_127Service2004308_359-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"111, 127"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"308"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991111,_127Service2004308-359" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 355;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[355]</span></a></sup> "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Socialist_realism" title="Socialist realism" id="mwAfw">Socialist realism</a>" was promoted throughout the arts,<sup about="#mwt436" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999246Montefiore200385_360-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"1y":{"wt":"1999"},"1p":{"wt":"246"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"85"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999246Montefiore200385-360" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 356;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[356]</span></a></sup> while Stalin personally wooed prominent writers, namely <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Maxim_Gorky" title="Maxim Gorky" id="mwAf0">Maxim Gorky</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mikhail_Sholokhov" title="Mikhail Sholokhov" id="mwAf4">Mikhail Sholokhov</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aleksey_Nikolayevich_Tolstoy" title="Aleksey Nikolayevich Tolstoy" id="mwAf8">Aleksey Nikolayevich Tolstoy</a>.<sup about="#mwt437" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004302–303_361-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"302–303"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004302–303-361" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 357;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[357]</span></a></sup> He also expressed patronage for scientists whose research fitted within his preconceived interpretation of Marxism; he for instance endorsed the research of agrobiologist <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Trofim_Lysenko" title="Trofim Lysenko" id="mwAgA">Trofim Lysenko</a> despite the fact that it was rejected by the majority of Lysenko's scientific peers as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pseudo-science" title="Pseudo-science" id="mwAgE" class="mw-redirect">pseudo-scientific</a>.<sup about="#mwt438" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991211,_276–277Service2004307_362-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"211, 276–277"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"307"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991211,_276–277Service2004307-362" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 358;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[358]</span></a></sup> The government's anti-religious campaign was re-intensified,<sup about="#mwt439" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991157_363-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"157"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991157-363" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 359;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[359]</span></a></sup> with increased funding given to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./League_of_Militant_Atheists" title="League of Militant Atheists" id="mwAgI">League of Militant Atheists</a>.<sup about="#mwt440" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004301_355-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"301"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004301-355" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 351;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[351]</span></a></sup> Christian, Muslim, and Buddhist clergy faced persecution.<sup about="#mwt441" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004268_351-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"268"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004268-351" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 347;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[347]</span></a></sup> Many religious buildings were demolished, most notably Moscow's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cathedral_of_Christ_the_Saviour" title="Cathedral of Christ the Saviour" id="mwAgM">Cathedral of Christ the Saviour</a>, destroyed in 1931 to make way for the (never completed) <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Palace_of_the_Soviets" title="Palace of the Soviets" id="mwAgQ">Palace of the Soviets</a>.<sup about="#mwt442" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991191_364-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"191"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991191-364" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 360;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[360]</span></a></sup> Religion retained an influence over much of the population; in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_Census_(1937)" title="Soviet Census (1937)" id="mwAgU">1937 census</a>, 57% of respondents identified as religious.<sup about="#mwt443" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015325_365-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"325"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015325-365" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 361;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[361]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAgY">Throughout the 1920s and beyond, Stalin placed a high priority on foreign policy.<sup about="#mwt444" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004379_366-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"379"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004379-366" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 362;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[362]</span></a></sup> He personally met with a range of Western visitors, including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./George_Bernard_Shaw" title="George Bernard Shaw" id="mwAgc">George Bernard Shaw</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./H._G._Wells" title="H. G. Wells" id="mwAgg">H. G. Wells</a>, both of whom were impressed with him.<sup about="#mwt445" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991183–184_367-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"pp":{"wt":"183–184"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991183–184-367" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 363;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[363]</span></a></sup> Through the Communist International, Stalin's government exerted a strong influence over Marxist parties elsewhere in the world;<sup about="#mwt446" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004282_368-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"282"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004282-368" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 364;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[364]</span></a></sup> initially, Stalin left the running of the organisation largely to Bukharin.<sup about="#mwt447" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004261_369-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"261"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004261-369" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 365;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[365]</span></a></sup> At its 6th Congress in July 1928, Stalin informed delegates that the main threat to socialism came not from the right but from non-Marxist socialists and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Social_democracy" title="Social democracy" id="mwAgk">social democrats</a>, whom he called "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Social_fascism" title="Social fascism" id="mwAgo">social fascists</a>";<sup about="#mwt448" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott1995410–411Conquest1991176Service2004261,_383Kotkin2014720_370-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"1y":{"wt":"1995"},"1pp":{"wt":"410–411"},"2a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"176"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"261, 383"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"720"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott1995410–411Conquest1991176Service2004261,_383Kotkin2014720-370" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 366;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[366]</span></a></sup> Stalin recognised that in many countries, the social democrats were the Marxist-Leninists' main rivals for working-class support.<sup about="#mwt449" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991173_371-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991173-371" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 367;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[367]</span></a></sup> This preoccupation with opposing rival leftists concerned Bukharin, who regarded the growth of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fascism" title="Fascism" id="mwAgs">fascism</a> and the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Far_right" title="Far right" id="mwAgw" class="mw-redirect">far right</a> across Europe as a far greater threat.<sup about="#mwt450" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004261_369-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"261"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004261-369" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 365;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[365]</span></a></sup> After Bukharin's departure, Stalin placed the Communist International under the administration of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dmitry_Manuilsky" title="Dmitry Manuilsky" id="mwAg0">Dmitry Manuilsky</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Osip_Piatnitsky" title="Osip Piatnitsky" id="mwAg4">Osip Piatnitsky</a>.<sup about="#mwt451" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004282_368-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"282"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004282-368" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 364;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[364]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAg8">Stalin faced problems in his family life. In 1929, his son Yakov unsuccessfully attempted suicide; his failure earned Stalin's contempt.<sup about="#mwt452" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004289Kotkin2014595_372-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"289"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"595"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004289Kotkin2014595-372" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 368;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[368]</span></a></sup> His relationship with Nadya was also strained amid their arguments and her mental health problems.<sup about="#mwt453" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004289_373-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"289"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004289-373" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 369;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[369]</span></a></sup> In November 1932, after a group dinner in the Kremlin in which Stalin flirted with other women, Nadya shot herself.<sup about="#mwt454" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991169Montefiore200390Service2004291–292_374-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"169"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"90"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"291–292"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991169Montefiore200390Service2004291–292-374" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 370;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[370]</span></a></sup>
Publicly, the cause of death was given as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Appendicitis" title="Appendicitis" id="mwAhA">appendicitis</a>; Stalin also concealed the real cause of death from his children.<sup about="#mwt455" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200394,_95Service2004292,_294_375-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1pp":{"wt":"94, 95"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"292, 294"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200394,_95Service2004292,_294-375" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 371;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[371]</span></a></sup> Stalin's friends noted that he underwent a significant change following her suicide, becoming emotionally harder.<sup about="#mwt456" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004297_376-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"297"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004297-376" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 372;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[372]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="16" id="mwAhE"><h3 id="Major_crises:_1932–1939"><span id="Major_crises:_1932.E2.80.931939" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Major crises: 1932–1939</h3>

<section data-mw-section-id="17" id="mwAhI"><h4 id="Famine">Famine</h4>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt457" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Further","href":"./Template:Further"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Soviet famine of 1932–33"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAhM">Further information: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_famine_of_1932–33" title="Soviet famine of 1932–33">Soviet famine of 1932–33</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAhQ"><a href="./File:GolodomorKharkiv.jpg" id="mwAhU"><img resource="./File:GolodomorKharkiv.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/GolodomorKharkiv.jpg/220px-GolodomorKharkiv.jpg" data-file-width="650" data-file-height="471" data-file-type="bitmap" height="159" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/GolodomorKharkiv.jpg/440px-GolodomorKharkiv.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a3/GolodomorKharkiv.jpg/330px-GolodomorKharkiv.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAhY"/></a><figcaption id="mwAhc">Starved peasants on streets of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kharkiv" title="Kharkiv" id="mwAhg">Kharkiv</a> in 1933</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAhk">Within the Soviet Union, there was widespread civic disgruntlement against Stalin's government.<sup about="#mwt458" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004316_377-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"316"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004316-377" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 373;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[373]</span></a></sup> Social unrest, previously restricted largely to the countryside, was increasingly evident in urban areas, prompting Stalin to ease on some of his economic policies in 1932.<sup about="#mwt459" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004310_378-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"310"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004310-378" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 374;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[374]</span></a></sup> In May 1932, he introduced a system of kolkhoz markets where peasants could trade their surplus produce.<sup about="#mwt460" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004310DaviesWheatcroft2006627_379-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"310"},"2a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"627"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004310DaviesWheatcroft2006627-379" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 375;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[375]</span></a></sup> At the same time, penal sanctions became more severe; at Stalin's instigation, in August 1932 a decree was introduced meaning that the theft of even a handful of grain could be a capital offense.<sup about="#mwt461" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006628_380-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"1a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"1y":{"wt":"2006"},"1p":{"wt":"628"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006628-380" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 376;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[376]</span></a></sup> The second five-year plan had its production quotas reduced from that of the first, with the main emphasis now being on improving living conditions.<sup about="#mwt462" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004310_378-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"310"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004310-378" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 374;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[374]</span></a></sup> It therefore emphasised the expansion of housing space and the production of consumer goods.<sup about="#mwt463" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004310_378-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"310"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004310-378" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 374;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[374]</span></a></sup> Like its predecessor, this Plan was repeatedly amended to meet changing situations; there was for instance an increasing emphasis placed on armament production after <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Adolf_Hitler" title="Adolf Hitler" id="mwAho">Adolf Hitler</a> became <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chancellor_of_Germany" title="Chancellor of Germany" id="mwAhs">German Chancellor</a> in 1933.<sup about="#mwt464" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004318_381-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"318"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004318-381" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 377;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[377]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAhw">The Soviet Union experienced a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_famine_of_1932–33" title="Soviet famine of 1932–33" id="mwAh0">major famine which peaked in the winter of 1932–33</a>;<sup about="#mwt465" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004312Conquest200819–20Khlevniuk2015117_382-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"312"},"2a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2y":{"wt":"2008"},"2pp":{"wt":"19–20"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"117"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004312Conquest200819–20Khlevniuk2015117-382" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 378;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[378]</span></a></sup> between five and seven million people died.<sup about="#mwt466" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015117_383-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"117"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015117-383" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 379;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[379]</span></a></sup> Worst affected were Ukraine and the North Caucuses, although the famine also impacted Kazakhstan and several Russian provinces.<sup about="#mwt467" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015119_384-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"119"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015119-384" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 380;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[380]</span></a></sup> Historians have long debated whether Stalin's government had intended the famine to occur or not;<sup about="#mwt468" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2005823_385-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2005"},"p":{"wt":"823"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2005823-385" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 381;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[381]</span></a></sup> there are no known documents in which Stalin or his government explicitly called for starvation to be used against the population.<sup about="#mwt469" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2005824DaviesWheatcroft2006628,_631_386-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"1y":{"wt":"2005"},"1p":{"wt":"824"},"2a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2pp":{"wt":"628, 631"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2005824DaviesWheatcroft2006628,_631-386" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 382;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[382]</span></a></sup> The 1931 and 1932 harvests had been poor ones due to weather conditions,<sup about="#mwt470" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2005823–824DaviesWheatcroft2006626Khlevniuk2015117_387-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"1y":{"wt":"2005"},"1pp":{"wt":"823–824"},"2a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"626"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"117"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2005823–824DaviesWheatcroft2006626Khlevniuk2015117-387" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 383;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[383]</span></a></sup> and had followed several years in which lower productivity had resulted in a gradual decline in output.<sup about="#mwt471" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015117_383-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"117"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015117-383" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 379;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[379]</span></a></sup> Government policies—including the focus on rapid industrialisation, the socialisation of livestock, and the emphasis on sown areas over <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Crop_rotation" title="Crop rotation" id="mwAh4">crop rotation</a>—exacerbated the problem;<sup about="#mwt472" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2005834_388-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2005"},"p":{"wt":"834"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2005834-388" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 384;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[384]</span></a></sup> the state had also failed to build reserve grain stocks for such an emergency.<sup about="#mwt473" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006626_389-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"3":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"626"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006626-389" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 385;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[385]</span></a></sup> Stalin blamed the famine on hostile elements and wreckers within the peasantry;<sup about="#mwt474" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2005824DaviesWheatcroft2006627–628Khlevniuk2015120_390-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"1y":{"wt":"2005"},"1p":{"wt":"824"},"2a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2pp":{"wt":"627–628"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"120"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2005824DaviesWheatcroft2006627–628Khlevniuk2015120-390" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 386;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[386]</span></a></sup> his government provided small amounts of food to famine-struck rural areas, although this was wholly insufficient to deal with the levels of starvation.<sup about="#mwt475" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006627_391-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"3":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"627"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006627-391" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 387;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[387]</span></a></sup> In keeping with their ideology, the Communists believed that food supplies should be prioritised for the urban workforce;<sup about="#mwt476" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2005833Kuromiya2008665_392-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"1y":{"wt":"2005"},"1p":{"wt":"833"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kuromiya"},"2y":{"wt":"2008"},"2p":{"wt":"665"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2005833Kuromiya2008665-392" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 388;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[388]</span></a></sup> for Stalin, the fate of Soviet industrialisation was far more important than the lives of the peasantry.<sup about="#mwt477" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006628Ellman2007664_393-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"1a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"1y":{"wt":"2006"},"1p":{"wt":"628"},"2a1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"664"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006628Ellman2007664-393" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 389;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[389]</span></a></sup> Grain exports, which were a major means of Soviet payment for machinery, declined heavily.<sup about="#mwt478" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006627_391-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"3":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"627"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006627-391" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 387;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[387]</span></a></sup> Stalin would not acknowledge that his policies had contributed to the famine,<sup about="#mwt479" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006628_380-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"3":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"628"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2006628-380" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 376;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[376]</span></a></sup> the existence of which was denied to foreign observers.<sup about="#mwt480" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991164Kotkin2014724_394-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"164"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"724"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991164Kotkin2014724-394" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 390;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[390]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="18" id="mwAh8"><h4 id="Ideological_and_foreign_affairs">Ideological and foreign affairs</h4>
<p id="mwAiA">In 1935–36, Stalin oversaw a new constitution; its dramatic liberal features were designed as propaganda weapons, for all power rested in the hands of Stalin and his Politburo.<sup about="#mwt790" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004319_395-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"319"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004319-395" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 391;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[391]</span></a></sup> He declared that "socialism, which is the first phase of communism, has basically been achieved in this country".<sup about="#mwt791" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004319_395-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"319"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004319-395" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 391;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[391]</span></a></sup> In 1938, <i id="mwAiE"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./The_History_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union_(Bolsheviks)" title="The History of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union (Bolsheviks)" id="mwAiI">The History of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union (Bolsheviks)</a></i>, colloquially known as the <i id="mwAiM">Short Course</i>, was released;<sup about="#mwt792" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991212Volkogonov1991552–443Service2004361_396-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"212"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"552–443"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"361"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991212Volkogonov1991552–443Service2004361-396" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 392;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[392]</span></a></sup> Conquest later referred to it as the "central text of Stalinism".<sup about="#mwt793" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991212_397-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"212"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991212-397" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 393;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[393]</span></a></sup> A number of authorised Stalin biographies were also published,<sup about="#mwt794" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004361_398-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"361"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004361-398" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 394;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[394]</span></a></sup> although Stalin generally wanted to be portrayed as the embodiment of the Communist Party rather than have his life story explored.<sup about="#mwt795" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004362_399-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"362"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004362-399" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 395;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[395]</span></a></sup> During the later 1930s, Stalin placed "a few limits on the worship of his own greatness".<sup about="#mwt796" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004362_399-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"362"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004362-399" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 395;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[395]</span></a></sup> By 1938, Stalin's inner circle had gained a degree of stability, containing the personalities who would remain there until Stalin's death.<sup about="#mwt797" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991216_400-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"216"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991216-400" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 396;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[396]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAiQ"><a href="./File:Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png" id="mwAiU"><img resource="./File:Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png/220px-Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png" data-file-width="1297" data-file-height="782" data-file-type="bitmap" height="133" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png/440px-Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png/330px-Soviet_armor_in_the_spanish_civil_war.png 1.5x" id="mwAiY"/></a><figcaption id="mwAic">Review of Soviet armored fighting vehicles used to equip the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Republican_People's_Army" title="Republican People's Army" id="mwAig" class="mw-redirect">Republican People's Army</a> during the Spanish Civil War</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwAik">Seeking improved international relations, in 1934 the Soviet Union secured membership of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./League_of_Nations" title="League of Nations" id="mwAio">League of Nations</a>, of which it had previously been excluded.<sup about="#mwt1105" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004386_401-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"386"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004386-401" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 397;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[397]</span></a></sup> Stalin initiated confidential communications with Hitler in October 1933, shortly after the latter came to power in Germany.<sup about="#mwt1106" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991217_402-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"217"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991217-402" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 398;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[398]</span></a></sup> Stalin admired Hitler, particularly his manoeuvres to remove rivals within the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nazi_Party" title="Nazi Party" id="mwAis">Nazi Party</a> in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Night_of_the_Long_Knives" title="Night of the Long Knives" id="mwAiw">Night of the Long Knives</a>.<sup about="#mwt1107" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991176Montefiore2003116Service2004340_403-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"176"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"116"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"340"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991176Montefiore2003116Service2004340-403" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 399;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[399]</span></a></sup> Stalin nevertheless recognised the threat posed by fascism and sought to establish better links with the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Liberal_democracy" title="Liberal democracy" id="mwAi0">liberal democracies</a> of Western Europe;<sup about="#mwt1108" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991218Khlevniuk2015123,_135_404-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"218"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"123, 135"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991218Khlevniuk2015123,_135-404" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 400;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[400]</span></a></sup> in May 1935, the Soviets signed a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Franco-Soviet_Treaty_of_Mutual_Assistance" title="Franco-Soviet Treaty of Mutual Assistance" id="mwAi4">treaty of mutual assistance</a> with France and Czechoslovakia.<sup about="#mwt1109" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015135_405-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"135"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015135-405" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 401;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[401]</span></a></sup> At the Communist International's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Seventh_World_Congress_of_the_Comintern" title="Seventh World Congress of the Comintern" id="mwAi8">7th Congress</a>, held in July–August 1935, the Soviet government encouraged Marxist-Leninists to unite with other leftists as part of a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Popular_front" title="Popular front" id="mwAjA">popular front</a> against fascism.<sup about="#mwt1110" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHaslam1979682–683Conquest1991218Service2004385Khlevniuk2015135_406-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Haslam"},"1y":{"wt":"1979"},"1pp":{"wt":"682–683"},"2a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"218"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"385"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"135"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHaslam1979682–683Conquest1991218Service2004385Khlevniuk2015135-406" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 402;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[402]</span></a></sup> In turn, the anti-communist governments of Germany, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fascist_Italian" title="Fascist Italian" id="mwAjE" class="mw-redirect">Fascist Italy</a> and Japan signed the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anti-Comintern_Pact" title="Anti-Comintern Pact" id="mwAjI">Anti-Comintern Pact</a> of 1936.<sup about="#mwt1111" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004392Khlevniuk2015154_407-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"392"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"154"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004392Khlevniuk2015154-407" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 403;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[403]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAjM">When the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Spanish_Civil_War" title="Spanish Civil War" id="mwAjQ">Spanish Civil War</a> broke out in July 1936, the Soviets sent 648 aircraft and 407 tanks to the left-wing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Republican_faction_(Spanish_Civil_War)" title="Republican faction (Spanish Civil War)" id="mwAjU">Republican faction</a>; these were accompanied by 3000 Soviet troops and 42,000 members of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./International_Brigades" title="International Brigades" id="mwAjY">International Brigades</a> set up by the Communist International.<sup about="#mwt1112" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991219Service2004387_408-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"219"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"387"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991219Service2004387-408" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 404;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[404]</span></a></sup> Stalin took a strong personal involvement in the Spanish situation.<sup about="#mwt1113" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015154_409-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"154"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015154-409" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 405;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[405]</span></a></sup> Germany and Italy backed the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nationalist_faction_(Spanish_Civil_War)" title="Nationalist faction (Spanish Civil War)" id="mwAjc">Nationalist faction</a>, which was ultimately victorious in March 1939.<sup about="#mwt1114" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004387,_389_410-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"387, 389"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004387,_389-410" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 406;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[406]</span></a></sup> With the outbreak of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Second_Sino-Japanese_War" title="Second Sino-Japanese War" id="mwAjg">Second Sino-Japanese War</a> in July 1937, the Soviet Union and China signed a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sino-Soviet_Non-Aggression_Pact" title="Sino-Soviet Non-Aggression Pact" id="mwAjk">non-aggression pact</a> the following August.<sup about="#mwt1115" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015156_411-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"156"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015156-411" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 407;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[407]</span></a></sup> Stalin aided the Chinese as the KMT and the Communists had suspended their civil war and formed the desired <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Second_United_Front" title="Second United Front" id="mwAjo">United Front</a>.<sup about="#mwt1116" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004392_412-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"392"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004392-412" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 408;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[408]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="19" id="mwAjs"><h4 id="The_Great_Terror">The Great Terror</h4>

<p id="mwAjw">Stalin often gave conflicting signals regarding state repression.<sup about="#mwt1119" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015126_413-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"126"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015126-413" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 409;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[409]</span></a></sup> In May 1933, he released from prison many convicted of minor offenses, ordering the security services not to enact further mass arrests and deportations.<sup about="#mwt1120" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015125_414-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"125"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015125-414" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 410;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[410]</span></a></sup> In September 1934, he launched a commission to investigate false imprisonments; that same month he called for the execution of workers at the Stalin Metallurgical Factory accused of spying for Japan.<sup about="#mwt1121" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015126_413-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"126"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015126-413" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 409;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[409]</span></a></sup> This mixed approach began to change in December 1934, after prominent party member <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sergey_Kirov" title="Sergey Kirov" id="mwAj0">Sergey Kirov</a> was murdered.<sup about="#mwt1122" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991179Montefiore2003126–127Service2004314Khlevniuk2015128–129_415-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"179"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2pp":{"wt":"126–127"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"314"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"128–129"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991179Montefiore2003126–127Service2004314Khlevniuk2015128–129-415" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 411;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[411]</span></a></sup> After the murder, Stalin became increasingly concerned by the threat of assassination, improved his personal security, and rarely went out in public.<sup about="#mwt1123" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEOvery2004327_416-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Overy"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"327"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEOvery2004327-416" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 412;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[412]</span></a></sup> State repression intensified after Kirov's death;<sup about="#mwt1124" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015128,_137_417-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"128, 137"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015128,_137-417" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 413;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[413]</span></a></sup> Stalin instigated this, reflecting his prioritisation of security above other considerations.<sup about="#mwt1125" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004347_418-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"347"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004347-418" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 414;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[414]</span></a></sup> Stalin issued a decree establishing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./NKVD_troika" title="NKVD troika" id="mwAj4">NKVD troikas</a> which could mete out rulings without involving the courts.<sup about="#mwt1126" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004315_419-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"315"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004315-419" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 415;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[415]</span></a></sup> In 1935, he ordered the NKVD to expel suspected counter-revolutionaries from urban areas;<sup about="#mwt1127" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004318_381-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"318"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004318-381" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 377;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[377]</span></a></sup> in early 1935, over 11,000 were expelled from Leningrad.<sup about="#mwt1128" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004318_381-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"318"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004318-381" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 377;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[377]</span></a></sup> In 1936, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikolai_Yezhov" title="Nikolai Yezhov" id="mwAj8">Nikolai Yezhov</a> became head of the NKVD.<sup about="#mwt1129" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015139_420-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"139"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015139-420" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 416;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[416]</span></a></sup></p>

<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r856303569" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles mw:Transclusion" about="#mwt1132" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"multiple image ","href":"./Template:Multiple_image"},"params":{"align":{"wt":"left"},"direction":{"wt":"vertical"},"width":{"wt":"250"},"image1":{"wt":"Voroshilov, Molotov, Stalin, with Nikolai Yezhov.jpg"},"caption1":{"wt":"In this well-known image, [[Nikolai Yezhov]] is shown with Voroshilov, Molotov, and Stalin inspecting the White Sea Canal"},"image2":{"wt":"The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg"},"caption2":{"wt":"The image was later altered to remove Yezhov completely"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAkA">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti>.thumbinner{width:100%!important;max-width:none!important}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:none!important;width:100%!important;text-align:center}}</style><div class="thumb tmulti tleft" about="#mwt1132" id="mwAkE"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:254px;max-width:254px"><div class="tsingle" style="margin:1px;width:252px;max-width:252px"><div class="thumbimage"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:Voroshilov,_Molotov,_Stalin,_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg"><img alt="" resource="./File:Voroshilov,_Molotov,_Stalin,_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Voroshilov%2C_Molotov%2C_Stalin%2C_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg/250px-Voroshilov%2C_Molotov%2C_Stalin%2C_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg" data-file-width="1064" data-file-height="762" data-file-type="bitmap" height="179" width="250" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Voroshilov%2C_Molotov%2C_Stalin%2C_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg/500px-Voroshilov%2C_Molotov%2C_Stalin%2C_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/91/Voroshilov%2C_Molotov%2C_Stalin%2C_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg/375px-Voroshilov%2C_Molotov%2C_Stalin%2C_with_Nikolai_Yezhov.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="thumbcaption" style="clear:left">In this well-known image, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikolai_Yezhov" title="Nikolai Yezhov">Nikolai Yezhov</a> is shown with Voroshilov, Molotov, and Stalin inspecting the White Sea Canal</div></div><div class="tsingle" style="margin:1px;width:252px;max-width:252px"><div class="thumbimage"><figure-inline typeof="mw:Image"><a href="./File:The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg"><img alt="" resource="./File:The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg/250px-The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg" data-file-width="1165" data-file-height="796" data-file-type="bitmap" height="171" width="250" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg/500px-The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/bd/The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg/375px-The_Commissar_Vanishes_2.jpg 1.5x"/></a></figure-inline></div><div class="thumbcaption" style="clear:left">The image was later altered to remove Yezhov completely</div></div></div></div>

<p id="mwAkI">Stalin orchestrated the arrest of many former opponents in the Communist Party <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Central_Committee_elected_by_the_17th_Congress_of_the_All-Union_Communist_Party_(Bolsheviks)" title="Central Committee elected by the 17th Congress of the All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks)" id="mwAkM">as well as sitting members of the Central Committee</a>: denounced as Western-backed mercenaries, many were imprisoned or exiled internally.<sup about="#mwt1133" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004314–317_421-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"314–317"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004314–317-421" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 417;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[417]</span></a></sup> The first <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moscow_Trials" title="Moscow Trials" id="mwAkQ">Moscow Trial</a> took place in August 1936; Kamenev and Zinoviev were among those accused of plotting assassinations, found guilty in a show trial, and executed.<sup about="#mwt1134" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003139,_154–155,_164–172,_175–176Service2004320Khlevniuk2015139_422-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1pp":{"wt":"139, 154–155, 164–172, 175–176"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"320"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"139"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003139,_154–155,_164–172,_175–176Service2004320Khlevniuk2015139-422" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 418;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[418]</span></a></sup> The second Moscow Show Trial took place in January 1937,<sup about="#mwt1135" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015139–140_423-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"139–140"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015139–140-423" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 419;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[419]</span></a></sup> and the third in March 1938, in which Bukharin and Rykov were accused of involvement in the alleged Trotskyite-Zinovievite terrorist plot and sentenced to death.<sup about="#mwt1136" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003192–193Service2004346Conquest200824Khlevniuk2015140_424-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1pp":{"wt":"192–193"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"346"},"3a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"3y":{"wt":"2008"},"3p":{"wt":"24"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"140"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003192–193Service2004346Conquest200824Khlevniuk2015140-424" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 420;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[420]</span></a></sup> By late 1937, all remnants of collective leadership were gone from the Politburo, which was controlled entirely by Stalin.<sup about="#mwt1137" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015176–177_425-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"176–177"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015176–177-425" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 421;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[421]</span></a></sup>
There were mass expulsions from the party,<sup about="#mwt1138" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004349_426-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"349"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004349-426" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 422;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[422]</span></a></sup> with Stalin commanding foreign communist parties to also purge anti-Stalinist elements.<sup about="#mwt1139" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004391_427-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"391"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004391-427" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 423;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[423]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAkU">During the 1930s and 1940s, NKVD groups assassinated defectors and opponents abroad;<sup about="#mwt1140" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004394_428-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"394"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004394-428" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 424;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[424]</span></a></sup> in August 1940, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Assassination_of_Trotsky" title="Assassination of Trotsky" id="mwAkY" class="mw-redirect">Trotsky was assassinated</a> in Mexico, eliminating the last of Stalin's opponents among the former Party leadership.<sup about="#mwt1141" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991230Service2004394Overy2004338Khlevniuk2015174_429-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"230"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"394"},"3a1":{"wt":"Overy"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"338"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"174"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991230Service2004394Overy2004338Khlevniuk2015174-429" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 425;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[425]</span></a></sup> In May, this was followed by the arrest of most members of the military Supreme Command and mass arrests throughout the military, often on fabricated charges.<sup about="#mwt1142" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003201Service2004349Khlevniuk2015140_430-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"201"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"349"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"140"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003201Service2004349Khlevniuk2015140-430" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 426;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[426]</span></a></sup> These purges replaced most of the party's old guard with younger officials who did not remember a time before Stalin's leadership and who were regarded as more personally loyal to him.<sup about="#mwt1143" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015137–138,_147_431-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"137–138, 147"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015137–138,_147-431" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 427;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[427]</span></a></sup> Party functionaries readily carried out their commands and sought to ingratiate themselves with Stalin to avoid becoming the victim of the purge.<sup about="#mwt1144" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015140_432-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"140"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015140-432" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 428;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[428]</span></a></sup> Such functionaries often carried out a greater number of arrests and executions than their quotas set by Stalin's central government.<sup about="#mwt1145" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003204_433-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"204"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003204-433" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 429;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[429]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAkc">Repressions further intensified in December 1936 and remained at a high level until November 1938, a period known as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Great_Purge" title="Great Purge" id="mwAkg">Great Purge</a>.<sup about="#mwt1146" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004347_418-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"347"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004347-418" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 414;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[414]</span></a></sup> By the latter part of 1937, the purges had moved beyond the party and were affecting the wider population.<sup about="#mwt1147" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015141,_150_434-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"141, 150"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015141,_150-434" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 430;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[430]</span></a></sup> In July 1937, the Politburo ordered a purge of "anti-Soviet elements" in society, targeting anti-Stalin Bolsheviks, former Mensheviks and Socialist Revolutionaries, priests, ex-White Army soldiers, and common criminals.<sup about="#mwt1148" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004350Khlevniuk2015150–151_435-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"350"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"150–151"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004350Khlevniuk2015150–151-435" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 431;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[431]</span></a></sup> That month, Stalin and Yezhov signed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./NKVD_Order_No._00447" title="NKVD Order No. 00447" id="mwAkk">Order No. 00447</a>, listing 268,950 people for arrest, of whom 75,950 were executed.<sup about="#mwt1149" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003203–204Service2004350–351Khlevniuk2015150_436-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1pp":{"wt":"203–204"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"350–351"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"150"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003203–204Service2004350–351Khlevniuk2015150-436" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 432;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[432]</span></a></sup> He also initiated "national operations", the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ethnic_cleansing" title="Ethnic cleansing" id="mwAko">ethnic cleansing</a> of non-Soviet ethnic groups—among them Poles, Germans, Latvians, Finns, Greeks, Koreans, and Chinese—through internal or external exile.<sup about="#mwt1150" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003204Service2004351,_390Khlevniuk2015151_437-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"204"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"351, 390"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"151"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003204Service2004351,_390Khlevniuk2015151-437" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 433;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[433]</span></a></sup> During these years, approximately 1.6 million people were arrested,<sup about="#mwt1151" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151_438-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"151"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151-438" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 434;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[434]</span></a></sup> 700,000 were shot, and an unknown number died under NKVD torture.<sup about="#mwt1152" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151_438-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"151"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151-438" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 434;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[434]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAks">Stalin initiated all key decisions during the Terror, personally directing many of its operations and taking an interest in their implementation.<sup about="#mwt1153" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151,_159_439-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"151, 159"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151,_159-439" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 435;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[435]</span></a></sup> His motives in doing so have been much debated by historians.<sup about="#mwt1154" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151_438-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"151"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015151-438" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 434;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[434]</span></a></sup> His personal writings from the period were — according to Khlevniuk — "unusually convoluted and incoherent", filled with claims about enemies encircling him.<sup about="#mwt1155" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015152_440-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"152"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015152-440" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 436;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[436]</span></a></sup> He was particularly concerned at the success that right-wing forces had in overthrowing the leftist Spanish government,<sup about="#mwt1156" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004347–248Khlevniuk2015125,_156–157_441-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"347–248"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"125, 156–157"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004347–248Khlevniuk2015125,_156–157-441" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 437;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[437]</span></a></sup> fearing a domestic <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fifth_column" title="Fifth column" id="mwAkw">fifth column</a> in the event of future war with Japan and Germany.<sup about="#mwt1157" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015153,_156–157_442-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"153, 156–157"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015153,_156–157-442" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 438;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[438]</span></a></sup> The Great Terror ended when Yezhov was removed as the head of the NKVD, to be replaced by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lavrentiy_Beria" title="Lavrentiy Beria" id="mwAk0">Lavrentiy Beria</a>,<sup about="#mwt1158" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004367_443-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"367"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004367-443" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 439;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[439]</span></a></sup> a man totally devoted to Stalin.<sup about="#mwt1159" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003245_444-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"245"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003245-444" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 440;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[440]</span></a></sup> Yezhov was arrested in April 1939 and executed in 1940.<sup about="#mwt1160" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991209Service2004369Khlevniuk2015160_445-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"209"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"369"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"160"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991209Service2004369Khlevniuk2015160-445" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 441;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[441]</span></a></sup> The Terror damaged the Soviet Union's reputation abroad, particularly among sympathetic leftists.<sup about="#mwt1161" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015162_446-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"162"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015162-446" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 442;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[442]</span></a></sup> As it wound down, Stalin sought to deflect responsibility from himself,<sup about="#mwt1162" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015157_447-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"157"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015157-447" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 443;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[443]</span></a></sup> blaming its "excesses" and "violations of law" on Yezhov.<sup about="#mwt1163" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015159_448-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"159"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015159-448" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 444;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[444]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section></section><section data-mw-section-id="20" id="mwAk4"><h2 id="World_War_II">World War II</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1164" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Soviet Union in World War II"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwAk8">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_Union_in_World_War_II" title="Soviet Union in World War II">Soviet Union in World War II</a></div>

<section data-mw-section-id="21" id="mwAlA"><h3 id="Pact_with_Germany:_1939–1941"><span id="Pact_with_Germany:_1939.E2.80.931941" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Pact with Germany: 1939–1941</h3>
<p id="mwAlE">As a Marxist–Leninist, Stalin expected an inevitable conflict between competing capitalist powers; after <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nazi_Germany" title="Nazi Germany" id="mwAlI">Nazi Germany</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anschluss" title="Anschluss" id="mwAlM">annexed Austria</a> and then <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./German_occupation_of_Czechoslovakia" title="German occupation of Czechoslovakia" id="mwAlQ">part of Czechoslovakia</a> in 1938, Stalin recognised this war was looming. He sought to maintain Soviet neutrality, hoping that a German war against France and Britain would lead to Soviet dominance in Europe.<sup about="#mwt1165" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991220–221Service2004380–381_449-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"220–221"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"380–381"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991220–221Service2004380–381-449" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 445;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[445]</span></a></sup> Militarily, the Soviets also faced a threat from the east, with Soviet troops <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet–Japanese_border_conflicts" title="Soviet–Japanese border conflicts" id="mwAlU">clashing with the expansionist Japanese</a> in the latter part of the 1930s.<sup about="#mwt1166" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004392–393Khlevniuk2015163,_168–169_450-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"392–393"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"163, 168–169"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004392–393Khlevniuk2015163,_168–169-450" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 446;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[446]</span></a></sup> Stalin initiated a military build-up, with the Red Army more than doubling between January 1939 and June 1941, although in its haste to expand many of its officers were poorly trained.<sup about="#mwt1167" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015185–186_451-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"185–186"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015185–186-451" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 447;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[447]</span></a></sup> Between 1940 and 1941 he also purged the military, leaving it with a severe shortage of trained officers when war broke out.<sup about="#mwt1168" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991232–233,_236_452-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"pp":{"wt":"232–233, 236"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991232–233,_236-452" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 448;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[448]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAlY"><a href="./File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337,_Moskau,_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg" id="mwAlc"><img resource="./File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337,_Moskau,_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337%2C_Moskau%2C_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg/220px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337%2C_Moskau%2C_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg" data-file-width="545" data-file-height="800" data-file-type="bitmap" height="323" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337%2C_Moskau%2C_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg/440px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337%2C_Moskau%2C_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337%2C_Moskau%2C_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg/330px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-H27337%2C_Moskau%2C_Stalin_und_Ribbentrop_im_Kreml.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAlg"/></a><figcaption id="mwAlk">Stalin greeting the German foreign minister Joachim von Ribbentrop in the Kremlin, 1939</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwAlo">As Britain and France seemed unwilling to commit to an alliance with the Soviet Union, Stalin saw a better deal with the Germans.<sup about="#mwt1169" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004399–400_453-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"399–400"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004399–400-453" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 449;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[449]</span></a></sup> In May 1939, Germany began negotiations with the Soviets, proposing that Eastern Europe be divided between the two powers.<sup about="#mwt1170" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991220Khlevniuk2015166_454-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"220"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"166"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991220Khlevniuk2015166-454" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 450;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[450]</span></a></sup> Stalin saw this as an opportunity both for territorial expansion and temporary peace with Germany.<sup about="#mwt1171" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991220Khlevniuk2015168,_169_455-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"220"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"168, 169"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991220Khlevniuk2015168,_169-455" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 451;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[451]</span></a></sup> In August 1939, the Soviet Union signed a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Molotov–Ribbentrop_Pact" title="Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact" id="mwAls">non-aggression pact</a> with Germany, negotiated by Soviet foreign minister <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vyacheslav_Molotov" title="Vyacheslav Molotov" id="mwAlw">Vyacheslav Molotov</a> and German foreign minister <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Joachim_von_Ribbentrop" title="Joachim von Ribbentrop" id="mwAl0">Joachim von Ribbentrop</a>.<sup about="#mwt1172" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991221Roberts199257–78Service2004399Khlevniuk2015166_456-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"221"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"1992"},"2pp":{"wt":"57–78"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"399"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"166"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991221Roberts199257–78Service2004399Khlevniuk2015166-456" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 452;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[452]</span></a></sup> A week later, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Invasion_of_Poland" title="Invasion of Poland" id="mwAl4">Germany invaded Poland</a>, sparking the UK and France to declare war on it.<sup about="#mwt1173" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991222Roberts199257–78Khlevniuk2015169_457-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"222"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"1992"},"2pp":{"wt":"57–78"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"169"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991222Roberts199257–78Khlevniuk2015169-457" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 453;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[453]</span></a></sup> On 17 September, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_invasion_of_Poland" title="Soviet invasion of Poland" id="mwAl8">the Red Army entered eastern Poland</a>, officially to restore order amid the collapse of the Polish state.<sup about="#mwt1174" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991222Roberts200643_458-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"222"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"43"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991222Roberts200643-458" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 454;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[454]</span></a></sup> On 28 September, Germany and the Soviet Union exchanged some of their newly conquered territories; Germany gained the linguistically Polish-dominated areas of Lublin Province and part of Warsaw Province while the Soviets gained Lithuania.<sup about="#mwt1175" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991223Service2004402–403Wettig200820_459-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"223"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"402–403"},"3a1":{"wt":"Wettig"},"3y":{"wt":"2008"},"3p":{"wt":"20"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991223Service2004402–403Wettig200820-459" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 455;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[455]</span></a></sup> A <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./German–Soviet_Frontier_Treaty" title="German–Soviet Frontier Treaty" id="mwAmA">German–Soviet Frontier Treaty</a> was signed shortly after, in Stalin's presence.<sup about="#mwt1176" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991224_460-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"224"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991224-460" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 456;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[456]</span></a></sup> The two states <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nazi–Soviet_economic_relations_(1934–41)" title="Nazi–Soviet economic relations (1934–41)" id="mwAmE">continued trading</a>, undermining the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Blockade_of_Germany_(1939–45)" title="Blockade of Germany (1939–45)" id="mwAmI" class="mw-redirect">British blockade of Germany</a>.<sup about="#mwt1177" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991224Service2004405_461-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"224"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"405"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991224Service2004405-461" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 457;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[457]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAmM">The Soviets further demanded parts of eastern Finland, but the Finnish government refused. The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Winter_War" title="Winter War" id="mwAmQ">Soviets invaded Finland</a> in November 1939, yet despite numerical inferiority, the Finns kept the Red Army at bay.<sup about="#mwt1178" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991228Service2004403Khlevniuk2015172–173_462-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"228"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"403"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"172–173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991228Service2004403Khlevniuk2015172–173-462" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 458;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[458]</span></a></sup> International opinion backed Finland, with the Soviets being expelled from the League of Nations.<sup about="#mwt1179" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991279Khlevniuk2015173_463-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"279"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991279Khlevniuk2015173-463" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 459;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[459]</span></a></sup> Embarrassed by their inability to defeat the Finns, the Soviets signed an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Moscow_Peace_Treaty" title="Moscow Peace Treaty" id="mwAmU">interim peace treaty</a>, in which they received territorial concessions from Finland.<sup about="#mwt1180" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004403Khlevniuk2015173_464-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"403"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004403Khlevniuk2015173-464" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 460;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[460]</span></a></sup> In June 1940, the Red Army entered the Baltic states, which were forcibly <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Occupation_of_the_Baltic_states" title="Occupation of the Baltic states" id="mwAmY">merged into the Soviet Union</a> in August;<sup about="#mwt1181" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991227Service2004404–405Wettig200820–21Khlevniuk2015173_465-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"227"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"404–405"},"3a1":{"wt":"Wettig"},"3y":{"wt":"2008"},"3pp":{"wt":"20–21"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991227Service2004404–405Wettig200820–21Khlevniuk2015173-465" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 461;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[461]</span></a></sup> they also invaded and annexed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_occupation_of_Bessarabia_and_Northern_Bukovina" title="Soviet occupation of Bessarabia and Northern Bukovina" id="mwAmc">Bessarabia and northern Bukovina</a>, parts of Romania.<sup about="#mwt1182" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBrackman2001341Khlevniuk2015173_466-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Brackman"},"1y":{"wt":"2001"},"1p":{"wt":"341"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBrackman2001341Khlevniuk2015173-466" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 462;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[462]</span></a></sup> The Soviets sought to forestall dissent in these new East European territories with mass repressions.<sup about="#mwt1183" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015170_467-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"170"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015170-467" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 463;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[463]</span></a></sup> One of the most noted instances was the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Katyn_massacre" title="Katyn massacre" id="mwAmg">Katyn massacre</a> of April and May 1940, in which around 22,000 members of the Polish armed forces, police, and intelligentsia were executed.<sup about="#mwt1184" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991229Khlevniuk2015170_468-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"229"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"170"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991229Khlevniuk2015170-468" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 464;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[464]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAmk">The speed of the German victory over and occupation of France in mid-1940 took Stalin by surprise.<sup about="#mwt1185" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991229Service2004405_469-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"229"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"405"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991229Service2004405-469" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 465;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[465]</span></a></sup> He increasingly focused on appeasement with the Germans to delay any conflict with them.<sup about="#mwt1186" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991229Service2004406_470-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"229"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"406"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991229Service2004406-470" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 466;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[466]</span></a></sup> After the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tripartite_Pact" title="Tripartite Pact" id="mwAmo">Tripartite Pact</a> was signed by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Axis_Powers" title="Axis Powers" id="mwAms" class="mw-redirect">Axis Powers</a> Germany, Japan and Italy, in October 1940, Stalin proposed that <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./German–Soviet_Axis_talks" title="German–Soviet Axis talks" id="mwAmw">the USSR also join the Axis alliance</a>.<sup about="#mwt1187" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991231Brackman2001341,_343Roberts200658_471-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"231"},"2a1":{"wt":"Brackman"},"2y":{"wt":"2001"},"2pp":{"wt":"341, 343"},"3a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"3y":{"wt":"2006"},"3p":{"wt":"58"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991231Brackman2001341,_343Roberts200658-471" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 467;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[467]</span></a></sup> To demonstrate peaceful intentions toward Germany, in April 1941 the Soviets signed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet-Japanese_Neutrality_Pact" title="Soviet-Japanese Neutrality Pact" id="mwAm0" class="mw-redirect">a neutrality pact</a> with Japan.<sup about="#mwt1188" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991233Roberts200663_472-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"233"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"63"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991233Roberts200663-472" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 468;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[468]</span></a></sup> Although <i id="mwAm4">de facto</i> head of government for a decade and a half, Stalin concluded that relations with Germany had deteriorated to such an extent that he needed to deal with the problem as <i id="mwAm8">de jure</i> head of government as well: on 6 May, Stalin replaced Molotov as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Premier_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Premier of the Soviet Union" id="mwAnA">Premier of the Soviet Union</a>.<sup about="#mwt1189" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991234Khlevniuk2015180_473-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"234"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"180"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991234Khlevniuk2015180-473" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 469;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[469]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="22" id="mwAnE"><h3 id="German_invasion:_1941–1942"><span id="German_invasion:_1941.E2.80.931942" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>German invasion: 1941–1942</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAnI"><a href="./File:Battle_of_Moscow.jpg" id="mwAnM"><img resource="./File:Battle_of_Moscow.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Battle_of_Moscow.jpg/220px-Battle_of_Moscow.jpg" data-file-width="1393" data-file-height="971" data-file-type="bitmap" height="153" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Battle_of_Moscow.jpg/440px-Battle_of_Moscow.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Battle_of_Moscow.jpg/330px-Battle_of_Moscow.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAnQ"/></a><figcaption id="mwAnU">With all the men at the front, Moscow women dig <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anti-tank_trench" title="Anti-tank trench" id="mwAnY">anti-tank trenches</a> around Moscow in 1941</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAnc">In June 1941, Germany <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Operation_Barbarossa" title="Operation Barbarossa" id="mwAng">invaded the Soviet Union</a>, initiating the war on the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Eastern_Front_(World_War_II)" title="Eastern Front (World War II)" id="mwAnk">Eastern Front</a>.<sup about="#mwt1190" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004410–411Roberts200682Khlevniuk2015198_474-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"410–411"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"82"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"198"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004410–411Roberts200682Khlevniuk2015198-474" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 470;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[470]</span></a></sup> Although intelligence agencies had repeatedly warned him of Germany's intentions, Stalin was taken by surprise.<sup about="#mwt1191" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004408-409,_411–412Roberts200667Khlevniuk2015199–200,_202_475-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"408-409, 411–412"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"67"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"199–200, 202"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004408-409,_411–412Roberts200667Khlevniuk2015199–200,_202-475" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 471;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[471]</span></a></sup> He formed a State Committee of Defence, which he headed as Supreme Commander,<sup about="#mwt1192" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004414–415Khlevniuk2015206–207_476-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"414–415"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"206–207"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004414–415Khlevniuk2015206–207-476" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 472;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[472]</span></a></sup> as well as a military <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stavka" title="Stavka" id="mwAno">Supreme Command</a> (Stavka),<sup about="#mwt1193" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004413_477-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"413"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004413-477" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 473;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[473]</span></a></sup> with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgy_Zhukov" title="Georgy Zhukov" id="mwAns">Georgy Zhukov</a> as its Chief of Staff.<sup about="#mwt1194" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004420_478-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"420"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004420-478" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 474;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[474]</span></a></sup> The German tactic of <i id="mwAnw"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Blitzkrieg" title="Blitzkrieg" id="mwAn0">blitzkrieg</a></i> was initially highly effective; the Soviet air force in the western borderlands was destroyed within two days.<sup about="#mwt1195" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004417Khlevniuk2015201–202_479-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"417"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"201–202"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004417Khlevniuk2015201–202-479" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 475;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[475]</span></a></sup> The German <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wehrmacht" title="Wehrmacht" id="mwAn4">Wehrmacht</a> pushed deep into Soviet territory;<sup about="#mwt1196" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991235Service2004416_480-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"235"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"416"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991235Service2004416-480" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 476;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[476]</span></a></sup> soon, Ukraine, Belorussia, and the Baltic states were under German occupation, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Siege_of_Leningrad" title="Siege of Leningrad" id="mwAn8">Leningrad was under siege</a>;<sup about="#mwt1197" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004418_481-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"418"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004418-481" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 477;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[477]</span></a></sup> and Soviet refugees were flooding into Moscow and surrounding cities.<sup about="#mwt1198" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004417_482-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"417"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004417-482" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 478;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[478]</span></a></sup> By July, Germany's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Luftwaffe" title="Luftwaffe" id="mwAoA">Luftwaffe</a> was bombing Moscow,<sup about="#mwt1199" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004418_481-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"418"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004418-481" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 477;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[477]</span></a></sup> and by October the Wehrmacht was amassing for a full assault on the capital. Plans were made for the Soviet government to evacuate to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Samara" title="Samara" id="mwAoE">Kuibyshev</a>, although Stalin decided to remain in Moscow, believing his flight would damage troop morale.<sup about="#mwt1200" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991248–249Service2004420Khlevniuk2015214–215_483-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"248–249"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"420"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"214–215"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991248–249Service2004420Khlevniuk2015214–215-483" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 479;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[479]</span></a></sup> The German advance on Moscow was halted after <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Battle_of_Moscow" title="Battle of Moscow" id="mwAoI">two months of battle</a> in increasingly harsh weather conditions.<sup about="#mwt1201" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGlantz200126_484-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Glantz"},"2":{"wt":"2001"},"p":{"wt":"26"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGlantz200126-484" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 480;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[480]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAoM">Against the advice of Zhukov and other generals, Stalin emphasised attack over defence.<sup about="#mwt1202" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004421,_424Khlevniuk2015220_485-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"421, 424"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"220"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004421,_424Khlevniuk2015220-485" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 481;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[481]</span></a></sup> In June 1941, he ordered a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Scorched_earth" title="Scorched earth" id="mwAoQ">scorched earth</a> policy of destroying infrastructure and food supplies before the Germans could seize them,<sup about="#mwt1203" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004482Roberts200690_486-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"482"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"90"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004482Roberts200690-486" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 482;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[482]</span></a></sup> also commanding the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./NKVD_prisoner_massacres" title="NKVD prisoner massacres" id="mwAoU">NKVD to kill</a> around 100,000 political prisoners in areas the Wehrmacht approached.<sup about="#mwt1204" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGellately2007391_487-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Gellately"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"391"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGellately2007391-487" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 483;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[483]</span></a></sup> He purged the military command; several high-ranking figures were demoted or reassigned and others were arrested and executed.<sup about="#mwt1205" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991239–240Roberts200698Khlevniuk2015209_488-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"239–240"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"98"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"209"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991239–240Roberts200698Khlevniuk2015209-488" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 484;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[484]</span></a></sup> With <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Order_No._270" title="Order No. 270" id="mwAoY">Order No. 270</a>, Stalin commanded soldiers risking capture to commit suicide or fight to the death, describing the captured as traitors;<sup about="#mwt1206" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991241Khlevniuk2015210_489-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"241"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"210"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991241Khlevniuk2015210-489" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 485;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[485]</span></a></sup> among those taken as a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Prisoner_of_war" title="Prisoner of war" id="mwAoc">prisoner of war</a> by the Germans was Stalin's son Yakov, who died in their custody.<sup about="#mwt1207" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991241–242Service2004521_490-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"241–242"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"521"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991241–242Service2004521-490" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 486;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[486]</span></a></sup> Stalin issued <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Order_No._227" title="Order No. 227" id="mwAog">Order No. 227</a> in July 1942, which directed that those retreating would be placed in "penal battalions" used as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cannon_fodder" title="Cannon fodder" id="mwAok">cannon fodder</a> on the front lines.<sup about="#mwt1208" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006132Khlevniuk2015223_491-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"1y":{"wt":"2006"},"1p":{"wt":"132"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"223"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006132Khlevniuk2015223-491" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 487;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[487]</span></a></sup> Amid the fighting, both the German and Soviet armies disregarded the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Law_of_war" title="Law of war" id="mwAoo">law of war</a> set forth in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Geneva_Conventions" title="Geneva Conventions" id="mwAos">Geneva Conventions</a>;<sup about="#mwt1209" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004423_492-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"423"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004423-492" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 488;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[488]</span></a></sup> the Soviets heavily publicised Nazi massacres of communists, Jews, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Romani_people" title="Romani people" id="mwAow">Romani</a>.<sup about="#mwt1210" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004422_493-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"422"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004422-493" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 489;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[489]</span></a></sup> Stalin exploited Nazi anti-Semitism, and in April 1942 he sponsored the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jewish_Anti-Fascist_Committee" title="Jewish Anti-Fascist Committee" id="mwAo0">Jewish Anti-Fascist Committee</a> (JAC) to garner Jewish and foreign support for the Soviet war effort.<sup about="#mwt1211" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEOvery2004568_494-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Overy"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"568"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEOvery2004568-494" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 490;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[490]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAo4"><a href="./File:RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg" id="mwAo8"><img resource="./File:RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg/220px-RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg" data-file-width="600" data-file-height="399" data-file-type="bitmap" height="146" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg/440px-RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c0/RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg/330px-RIAN_archive_602161_Center_of_Stalingrad_after_liberation.jpg 1.5x" id="mwApA"/></a><figcaption id="mwApE">Center of Stalingrad after liberation, 2 February 1943</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwApI">The Soviets allied with the United Kingdom and United States;<sup about="#mwt1212" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015211_495-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"211"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015211-495" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 491;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[491]</span></a></sup> although the US joined the war against Germany in 1941, little direct American assistance reached the Soviets until late 1942.<sup about="#mwt1213" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004423_492-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"423"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004423-492" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 488;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[488]</span></a></sup> Responding to the invasion, the Soviets intensified their industrial enterprises in central Russia, focusing almost entirely on production for the military.<sup about="#mwt1214" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004421_496-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"421"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004421-496" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 492;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[492]</span></a></sup> They achieved high levels of industrial productivity, outstripping that of Germany.<sup about="#mwt1215" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004422_493-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"422"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004422-493" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 489;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[489]</span></a></sup> During the war, Stalin was more tolerant of the Russian Orthodox Church, allowing it to resume some of its activities and meeting with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Patriarch_Sergius_of_Moscow" title="Patriarch Sergius of Moscow" id="mwApM">Patriarch Sergius</a> in September 1943.<sup about="#mwt1216" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004442–443Khlevniuk2015242–243_497-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"442–443"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"242–243"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004442–443Khlevniuk2015242–243-497" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 493;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[493]</span></a></sup> He also permitted a wider range of cultural expression, notably permitting formerly suppressed writers and artists like <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anna_Akhmatova" title="Anna Akhmatova" id="mwApQ">Anna Akhmatova</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dmitri_Shostakovich" title="Dmitri Shostakovich" id="mwApU">Dmitri Shostakovich</a> to disperse their work more widely.<sup about="#mwt1217" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004441_498-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"441"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004441-498" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 494;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[494]</span></a></sup> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./The_Internationale" title="The Internationale" id="mwApY">The Internationale</a> was dropped as the country's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./National_anthem" title="National anthem" id="mwApc">national anthem</a>, to be replaced with <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./State_Anthem_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="State Anthem of the Soviet Union" id="mwApg">a more patriotic song</a>.<sup about="#mwt1218" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004442_499-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"442"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004442-499" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 495;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[495]</span></a></sup> The government increasingly promoted <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Pan-Slavism" title="Pan-Slavism" id="mwApk">Pan-Slavist</a> sentiment,<sup about="#mwt1219" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004446_500-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"446"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004446-500" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 496;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[496]</span></a></sup> while encouraging increased criticism of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cosmopolitanism" title="Cosmopolitanism" id="mwApo">cosmopolitanism</a>, particularly the idea of "rootless cosmopolitanism", an approach with particular repercussions for Soviet Jews.<sup about="#mwt1220" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004446–447_501-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"446–447"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004446–447-501" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 497;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[497]</span></a></sup> Comintern was dissolved in 1943,<sup about="#mwt1221" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991260Service2004444_502-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"260"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"444"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991260Service2004444-502" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 498;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[498]</span></a></sup> and Stalin encouraged foreign Marxist–Leninist parties to emphasise nationalism over internationalism to broaden their domestic appeal.<sup about="#mwt1222" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004446_500-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"446"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004446-500" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 496;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[496]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAps">In April 1942 Stalin overrode Stavka by ordering the Soviets' first serious counter-attack, an attempt to seize German-held <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kharkov" title="Kharkov" id="mwApw" class="mw-redirect">Kharkov</a> in eastern Ukraine. This attack proved unsuccessful.<sup about="#mwt1223" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991254Service2004424Khlevniuk2015221–222_503-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"254"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"424"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"221–222"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991254Service2004424Khlevniuk2015221–222-503" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 499;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[499]</span></a></sup> That year, Hitler shifted his primary goal from a overall victory on the Eastern Front, to the goal of securing the oil fields southern Soviet Union crucial to a long-term German war effort.<sup about="#mwt1224" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006117–8_504-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"pp":{"wt":"117–8"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006117–8-504" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 500;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[500]</span></a></sup> While Red Army generals saw evidence that Hitler would shift efforts south, Stalin considered this to be a flanking move in a renewed effort to take Moscow.<sup about="#mwt1225" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006124_505-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"124"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006124-505" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 501;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[501]</span></a></sup> In June 1942, the German Army began a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Case_Blue" title="Case Blue" id="mwAp0">major offensive</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Southern_Russia" title="Southern Russia" id="mwAp4">Southern Russia</a>, threatening Stalingrad; Stalin ordered the Red Army to hold the city at all costs.<sup about="#mwt1226" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004425_506-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"425"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004425-506" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 502;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[502]</span></a></sup> This resulted in the protracted <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Battle_of_Stalingrad" title="Battle of Stalingrad" id="mwAp8">Battle of Stalingrad</a>.<sup about="#mwt1227" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004426_507-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"426"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004426-507" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 503;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[503]</span></a></sup> In December 1942 he placed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Konstantin_Rokossovski" title="Konstantin Rokossovski" id="mwAqA" class="mw-redirect">Konstantin Rokossovski</a> in charge of holding the city.<sup about="#mwt1228" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004427_508-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"427"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004427-508" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 504;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[504]</span></a></sup> In February 1943, the German troops attacking Stalingrad surrendered.<sup about="#mwt1229" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004428Khlevniuk2015225_509-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"428"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"225"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004428Khlevniuk2015225-509" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 505;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[505]</span></a></sup> The Soviet victory there marked a major turning point in the war;<sup about="#mwt1230" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015225_510-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"225"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015225-510" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 506;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[506]</span></a></sup> in commemoration, Stalin declared himself <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Marshal_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Marshal of the Soviet Union" id="mwAqE">Marshal of the Soviet Union</a>.<sup about="#mwt1231" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004429Khlevniuk2015226_511-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"429"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"226"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004429Khlevniuk2015226-511" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 507;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[507]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="23" id="mwAqI"><h3 id="Soviet_counter-attack:_1942–1945"><span id="Soviet_counter-attack:_1942.E2.80.931945" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Soviet counter-attack: 1942–1945</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAqM"><a href="./File:Teheran_conference-1943.jpg" id="mwAqQ"><img resource="./File:Teheran_conference-1943.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Teheran_conference-1943.jpg/220px-Teheran_conference-1943.jpg" data-file-width="5805" data-file-height="4693" data-file-type="bitmap" height="178" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Teheran_conference-1943.jpg/440px-Teheran_conference-1943.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/Teheran_conference-1943.jpg/330px-Teheran_conference-1943.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAqU"/></a><figcaption id="mwAqY">The Big Three: Stalin, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States" id="mwAqc">U.S. President</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Franklin_D._Roosevelt" title="Franklin D. Roosevelt" id="mwAqg">Franklin D. Roosevelt</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom" title="Prime Minister of the United Kingdom" id="mwAqk">British Prime Minister</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Winston_Churchill" title="Winston Churchill" id="mwAqo">Winston Churchill</a> at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tehran_Conference" title="Tehran Conference" id="mwAqs">Tehran Conference</a>, November 1943</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAqw">By November 1942, the Soviets had begun to repulse the important <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Operation_Blau" title="Operation Blau" id="mwAq0" class="mw-redirect">German strategic southern campaign</a> and, although there were 2.5<span typeof="mw:Entity" id="mwAq4"> </span>million Soviet casualties in that effort, it permitted the Soviets to take the offensive for most of the rest of the war on the Eastern Front.<sup about="#mwt1232" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006155_512-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"155"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006155-512" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 508;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[508]</span></a></sup> Germany <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Battle_of_Kursk" title="Battle of Kursk" id="mwAq8">attempted an encirclement attack at Kursk</a>, which was successfully repulsed by the Soviets.<sup about="#mwt1233" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991255Roberts2006156Khlevniuk2015227_513-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"255"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"156"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"227"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991255Roberts2006156Khlevniuk2015227-513" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 509;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[509]</span></a></sup> By the end of 1943, the Soviets occupied half of the territory taken by the Germans from 1941 to 1942.<sup about="#mwt1234" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006159_514-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"159"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006159-514" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 510;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[510]</span></a></sup> Soviet military industrial output also had increased substantially from late 1941 to early 1943 after Stalin had moved factories well to the east of the front, safe from German invasion and aerial assualt.<sup about="#mwt1235" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006163_515-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"163"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006163-515" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 511;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[511]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwArA">In Allied countries, Stalin was increasingly depicted in a positive light over the course of the war.<sup about="#mwt1236" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004452_516-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"452"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004452-516" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 512;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[512]</span></a></sup> In 1941, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./London_Philharmonic_Orchestra" title="London Philharmonic Orchestra" id="mwArE">London Philharmonic Orchestra</a> performed a concert to celebrate his birthday,<sup about="#mwt1237" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004466_517-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"466"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004466-517" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 513;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[513]</span></a></sup> and in 1942, <i id="mwArI"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Time_(magazine)" title="Time (magazine)" id="mwArM">Time</a></i> magazine named him "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Time_Person_of_the_Year" title="Time Person of the Year" id="mwArQ">Man of the Year</a>".<sup about="#mwt1238" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004452_516-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"452"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004452-516" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 512;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[512]</span></a></sup> When Stalin learned that people in Western countries affectionately called him "Uncle Joe" he was initially offended, regarding it as undignified.<sup about="#mwt1239" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991317Service2004466_518-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"317"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"466"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991317Service2004466-518" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 514;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[514]</span></a></sup> There remained mutual suspicions between Stalin, British Prime Minister <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Winston_Churchill" title="Winston Churchill" id="mwArU">Winston Churchill</a>, and U.S. President <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Franklin_D._Roosevelt" title="Franklin D. Roosevelt" id="mwArY">Franklin D. Roosevelt</a>, who were together known as the "Big Three".<sup about="#mwt1240" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004458_519-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"458"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004458-519" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 515;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[515]</span></a></sup> Churchill flew to Moscow to visit Stalin in August 1942 and again in October 1944.<sup about="#mwt1241" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991252Service2004460224,_244Khlevniuk2015_520-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"252"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"460"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"224, 244"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991252Service2004460224,_244Khlevniuk2015-520" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 516;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[516]</span></a></sup> Stalin scarcely left Moscow throughout the war,<sup about="#mwt1242" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004456_521-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"456"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004456-521" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 517;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[517]</span></a></sup> with Roosevelt and Churchill frustrated with his reluctance to travel to meet them.<sup about="#mwt1243" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004460_522-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"460"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004460-522" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 518;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[518]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwArc">In November 1943, Stalin met with Churchill and Roosevelt <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tehran_Conference" title="Tehran Conference" id="mwArg">in Tehran</a>, a location of Stalin's choosing.<sup about="#mwt1244" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991262Service2004460Roberts2006180Khlevniuk2015229–230_523-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"262"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"460"},"3a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"3y":{"wt":"2006"},"3p":{"wt":"180"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"229–230"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991262Service2004460Roberts2006180Khlevniuk2015229–230-523" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 519;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[519]</span></a></sup> There, Stalin and Roosevelt got on well, with both desiring the post-war dismantling of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./British_Empire" title="British Empire" id="mwArk">British Empire</a>.<sup about="#mwt1245" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004462_524-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"462"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004462-524" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 520;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[520]</span></a></sup> At Tehran, the trio agreed that to prevent Germany rising to military prowess yet again, the German state should be broken up.<sup about="#mwt1246" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004463_525-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"463"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004463-525" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 521;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[521]</span></a></sup> Roosevelt and Churchill also agreed to Stalin's demand that the German city of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Königsberg" title="Königsberg" id="mwAro">Königsberg</a> be declared Soviet territory.<sup about="#mwt1247" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004463_525-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"463"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004463-525" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 521;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[521]</span></a></sup> Stalin was impatient for the UK and US to open up a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Western_Front_(World_War_II)" title="Western Front (World War II)" id="mwArs">Western Front</a> to take the pressure off of the East; they eventually did so in mid-1944.<sup about="#mwt1248" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991244,_251Service2004461,_469Roberts2006185Khlevniuk2015223,_229_526-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"244, 251"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"461, 469"},"3a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"3y":{"wt":"2006"},"3p":{"wt":"185"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"223, 229"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991244,_251Service2004461,_469Roberts2006185Khlevniuk2015223,_229-526" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 522;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[522]</span></a></sup> Stalin insisted that, after the war, the Soviet Union should incorporate the portions of Poland it occupied pursuant to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Molotov–Ribbentrop_Pact" title="Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact" id="mwArw">Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact</a> with Germany, which Churchill opposed.<sup about="#mwt1249" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006186–7_527-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"pp":{"wt":"186–7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006186–7-527" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 523;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[523]</span></a></sup> Discussing the fate of the Balkans, later in 1944 Churchill agreed to Stalin's suggestion that after the war, Bulgaria, Romania, Hungary, and Yugoslavia would come under the Soviet sphere of influence while Greece would come under that of the West.<sup about="#mwt1250" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004464–465Khlevniuk2015244_528-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"464–465"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"244"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004464–465Khlevniuk2015244-528" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 524;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[524]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAr0"><a href="./File:Soviet_soldiers_in_Polozk_(Belarus),_passing_by_propaganda_poster_celebrating_the_reconquest_of_the_city_and_urging_the_liberation_of_the_Baltic_from_Nazi_German_occupation._July_4,_1944.jpg" id="mwAr4"><img resource="./File:Soviet_soldiers_in_Polozk_(Belarus),_passing_by_propaganda_poster_celebrating_the_reconquest_of_the_city_and_urging_the_liberation_of_the_Baltic_from_Nazi_German_occupation._July_4,_1944.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Soviet_soldiers_in_Polozk_%28Belarus%29%2C_passing_by_propaganda_poster_celebrating_the_reconquest_of_the_city_and_urging_the_liberation_of_the_Baltic_from_Nazi_German_occupation._July_4%2C_1944.jpg/220px-thumbnail.jpg" data-file-width="797" data-file-height="597" data-file-type="bitmap" height="165" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Soviet_soldiers_in_Polozk_%28Belarus%29%2C_passing_by_propaganda_poster_celebrating_the_reconquest_of_the_city_and_urging_the_liberation_of_the_Baltic_from_Nazi_German_occupation._July_4%2C_1944.jpg/440px-thumbnail.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Soviet_soldiers_in_Polozk_%28Belarus%29%2C_passing_by_propaganda_poster_celebrating_the_reconquest_of_the_city_and_urging_the_liberation_of_the_Baltic_from_Nazi_German_occupation._July_4%2C_1944.jpg/330px-thumbnail.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAr8"/></a><figcaption id="mwAsA">Soviet soldiers in Polotsk, 4 July 1944</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAsE">In 1944, the Soviet Union made significant advances across Eastern Europe toward Germany,<sup about="#mwt1251" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006194–5_529-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"pp":{"wt":"194–5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006194–5-529" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 525;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[525]</span></a></sup> including <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Operation_Bagration" title="Operation Bagration" id="mwAsI">Operation Bagration</a>, a massive offensive in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Byelorussian_Soviet_Socialist_Republic" title="Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic" id="mwAsM">Byelorussian SSR</a> against the German Army Group Centre.<sup about="#mwt1252" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004469Roberts2006199–201_530-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"469"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2pp":{"wt":"199–201"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004469Roberts2006199–201-530" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 526;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[526]</span></a></sup> In 1944 the German armies were pushed out of the Baltic states, which were then re-annexed into the Soviet Union.<sup about="#mwt1253" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004492_531-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"492"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004492-531" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 527;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[527]</span></a></sup> As the Red Army reconquered the Caucasus and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Crimea" title="Crimea" id="mwAsQ">Crimea</a>, various ethnic groups living in the region—the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kalmyks" title="Kalmyks" id="mwAsU">Kalmyks</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chechens" title="Chechens" id="mwAsY">Chechens</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ingush_people" title="Ingush people" id="mwAsc">Ingushi</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Karachai" title="Karachai" id="mwAsg" class="mw-redirect">Karachai</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Balkars" title="Balkars" id="mwAsk">Balkars</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Crimean_Tatars" title="Crimean Tatars" id="mwAso">Crimean Tatars</a>—were accused of having collaborated with the Germans. Using the idea of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Collective_responsibility" title="Collective responsibility" id="mwAss">collective responsibility</a> as a basis, Stalin's government abolished their autonomous republics and between late 1943 and 1944 deported the majority of their populations to Central Asia and Siberia.<sup about="#mwt1254" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991258Service2004492Khlevniuk2015232–233_532-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"258"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"492"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"232–233"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991258Service2004492Khlevniuk2015232–233-532" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 528;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[528]</span></a></sup> Over one million people were deported as a result of the policy.<sup about="#mwt1255" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015233_533-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"233"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015233-533" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 529;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[529]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAsw">In February 1945, the three leaders met at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Yalta_Conference" title="Yalta Conference" id="mwAs0">Yalta Conference</a>.<sup about="#mwt1256" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991264Service2004465Khlevniuk2015244_534-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"264"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"465"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"244"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991264Service2004465Khlevniuk2015244-534" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 530;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[530]</span></a></sup> Roosevelt and Churchill conceded to Stalin's demand that Germany pay the Soviet Union 20 billion dollars in reparations, and that his country be permitted to annex <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sakhalin" title="Sakhalin" id="mwAs4">Sakhalin</a> and the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kurile_Islands" title="Kurile Islands" id="mwAs8" class="mw-redirect">Kurile Islands</a> in exchange for <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet-Japanese_War" title="Soviet-Japanese War" id="mwAtA" class="mw-redirect">entering the war</a> against Japan.<sup about="#mwt1257" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004465–466_535-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"465–466"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004465–466-535" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 531;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[531]</span></a></sup> An agreement was also made that a post-war Polish government should be a coalition consisting of both communist and conservative elements.<sup about="#mwt1258" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004465–466Roberts2006241–244_536-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"465–466"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2pp":{"wt":"241–244"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004465–466Roberts2006241–244-536" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 532;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[532]</span></a></sup> Privately, Stalin sought to ensure that Poland would come fully under Soviet influence.<sup about="#mwt1259" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004471Khlevniuk2015245_537-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"471"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"245"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004471Khlevniuk2015245-537" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 533;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[533]</span></a></sup> The Red Army withheld assistance to Polish resistance fighters battling the Germans in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Warsaw_Uprising" title="Warsaw Uprising" id="mwAtE">Warsaw Uprising</a>, with Stalin believing that any victorious Polish militants could interfere with his aspirations to dominate Poland through a future Marxist government.<sup about="#mwt1260" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004471–472Khlevniuk2015244_538-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"471–472"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"244"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004471–472Khlevniuk2015244-538" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 534;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[534]</span></a></sup> Although concealing his desires from the other Allied leaders, Stalin placed great emphasis on capturing Berlin first, believing that this would enable him to bring more of Europe under long-term Soviet control. Churchill was concerned that this was the case, and unsuccessfully tried to convince the US that the Western Allies should pursue the same goal.<sup about="#mwt1261" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004473_539-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"473"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004473-539" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 535;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[535]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="24" id="mwAtI"><h3 id="Victory:_1945">Victory: 1945</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAtM"><a href="./File:Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg" id="mwAtQ"><img resource="./File:Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg/220px-Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg" data-file-width="740" data-file-height="585" data-file-type="bitmap" height="174" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg/440px-Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg/330px-Potsdam_conference_1945-8.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAtU"/></a><figcaption id="mwAtY"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Prime_Minister_of_the_United_Kingdom" title="Prime Minister of the United Kingdom" id="mwAtc">British Prime Minister</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Clement_Attlee" title="Clement Attlee" id="mwAtg">Clement Attlee</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./President_of_the_United_States" title="President of the United States" id="mwAtk">U.S. President</a> <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Harry_S._Truman" title="Harry S. Truman" id="mwAto">Harry S. Truman</a> and Joseph Stalin at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Potsdam_Conference" title="Potsdam Conference" id="mwAts">Potsdam Conference</a>, July 1945</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAtw">In April 1945, the Red Army seized Berlin, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Death_of_Adolf_Hitler" title="Death of Adolf Hitler" id="mwAt0">Hitler committed suicide</a>, and Germany surrendered.<sup about="#mwt1262" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004474Khlevniuk2015247_540-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"474"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"247"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004474Khlevniuk2015247-540" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 536;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[536]</span></a></sup> Stalin had wanted Hitler captured alive; he had his remains brought to Moscow to prevent them becoming a relic for Nazi sympathisers.<sup about="#mwt1263" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004479–480_541-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"479–480"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004479–480-541" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 537;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[537]</span></a></sup> As the Red Army had conquered German territory, they discovered the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Extermination_camp" title="Extermination camp" id="mwAt4">extermination camps</a> that the Nazi administration had run.<sup about="#mwt1264" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004473_539-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"473"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004473-539" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 535;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[535]</span></a></sup> Many Soviet soldiers engaged in looting, pillaging, and rape, both in Germany and parts of Eastern Europe.<sup about="#mwt1265" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991265Service2004473Khlevniuk2015234_542-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"265"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"473"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"234"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991265Service2004473Khlevniuk2015234-542" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 538;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[538]</span></a></sup> Stalin refused to punish the offenders.<sup about="#mwt1266" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004473_539-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"473"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004473-539" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 535;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[535]</span></a></sup> After receiving a complaint about this from Yugoslav communist <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Milovan_Djilas" title="Milovan Djilas" id="mwAt8" class="mw-redirect">Milovan Djilas</a>, Stalin asked how after experiencing the traumas of war a soldier could "react normally? And what is so awful in his having fun with a woman, after such horrors?"<sup about="#mwt1267" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991265–266Service2004473Khlevniuk2015235_543-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"265–266"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"473"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"235"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991265–266Service2004473Khlevniuk2015235-543" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 539;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[539]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAuA">With Germany defeated, Stalin switched focus to the war with Japan, transferring half a million troops to the Far East.<sup about="#mwt1268" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004474_544-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"474"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004474-544" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 540;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[540]</span></a></sup> Stalin was pressed by his allies to enter the war and wanted to cement the Soviet Union's strategic position in Asia.<sup about="#mwt1269" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGlantz1983_545-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Glantz"},"2":{"wt":"1983"},"p":{"wt":"xvii"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGlantz1983-545" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 541;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[541]</span></a></sup> On 8 August, in between the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Atomic_bombings_of_Hiroshima_and_Nagasaki" title="Atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki" id="mwAuE">atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki</a>, the Soviet army <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_invasion_of_Manchuria" title="Soviet invasion of Manchuria" id="mwAuI">invaded Japanese-occupied Manchuria</a> and defeated the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kwantung_Army" title="Kwantung Army" id="mwAuM">Kwantung Army</a>.<sup about="#mwt1270" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004476Khlevniuk2015248–249_546-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"476"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"248–249"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004476Khlevniuk2015248–249-546" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 542;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[542]</span></a></sup> These events led to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Japanese_surrender" title="Japanese surrender" id="mwAuQ" class="mw-redirect">Japanese surrender</a> and the war's end.<sup about="#mwt1271" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991268Khlevniuk2015248_547-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"268"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"248"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991268Khlevniuk2015248-547" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 543;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[543]</span></a></sup> Soviet forces continued to expand until they occupied all their territorial concessions, but the U.S. rebuffed Stalin's desire for the Red Army to take a role in the Allied <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Occupation_of_Japan" title="Occupation of Japan" id="mwAuU">occupation of Japan</a>.<sup about="#mwt1272" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991267Khlevniuk2015249_548-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"267"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"249"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991267Khlevniuk2015249-548" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 544;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[544]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAuY">Stalin attended the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Potsdam_Conference" title="Potsdam Conference" id="mwAuc">Potsdam Conference</a> in July–August 1945, alongside his new British and U.S. counterparts, Prime Minister <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Clement_Attlee" title="Clement Attlee" id="mwAug">Clement Attlee</a> and President <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Harry_Truman" title="Harry Truman" id="mwAuk" class="mw-redirect">Harry Truman</a>.<sup about="#mwt1273" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991267Service2004475_549-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"267"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"475"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991267Service2004475-549" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 545;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[545]</span></a></sup> At the conference, Stalin repeated previous promises to Churchill that he would refrain from a "Sovietization" of Eastern Europe.<sup about="#mwt1274" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts2006274–5_550-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"pp":{"wt":"274–5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts2006274–5-550" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 546;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[546]</span></a></sup> Stalin pushed for reparations from Germany without regard to the base minimum supply for German citizens' survival, which worried Truman and Churchill who thought that Germany would become a financial burden for Western powers.<sup about="#mwt1275" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWettig200890–1_551-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Wettig"},"2":{"wt":"2008"},"pp":{"wt":"90–1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWettig200890–1-551" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 547;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[547]</span></a></sup> He also pushed for "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./War_booty" title="War booty" id="mwAuo" class="mw-redirect">war booty</a>", which would permit the Soviet Union to directly seize property from conquered nations without quantitative or qualitative limitation, and a clause was added permitting this to occur with some limitations.<sup about="#mwt1276" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWettig200890–1_551-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Wettig"},"2":{"wt":"2008"},"pp":{"wt":"90–1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWettig200890–1-551" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 547;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[547]</span></a></sup> Germany was divided into four zones: Soviet, U.S., British, and French, with Berlin itself—located within the Soviet area—also subdivided thusly.<sup about="#mwt1277" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004506_552-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"506"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004506-552" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 548;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[548]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="25" id="mwAus"><h2 id="Post-war_era">Post-war era</h2>

<section data-mw-section-id="26" id="mwAuw"><h3 id="Post-war_reconstruction_and_famine:_1945–1947"><span id="Post-war_reconstruction_and_famine:_1945.E2.80.931947" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Post-war reconstruction and famine: 1945–1947</h3>
<p id="mwAu0">After the war, Stalin was—according to Service—at the "apex of his career".<sup about="#mwt1278" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004481_553-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"481"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004481-553" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 549;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[549]</span></a></sup> Within the Soviet Union he was widely regarded as the embodiment of victory and patriotism.<sup about="#mwt1279" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004484_554-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"484"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004484-554" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 550;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[550]</span></a></sup> His armies controlled <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Central_and_Eastern_Europe" title="Central and Eastern Europe" id="mwAu4">Central and Eastern Europe</a> up to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./River_Elbe" title="River Elbe" id="mwAu8" class="mw-redirect">River Elbe</a>.<sup about="#mwt1280" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004481_553-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"481"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004481-553" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 549;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[549]</span></a></sup>
In June 1945, Stalin adopted the title of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Generalissimus_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Generalissimus of the Soviet Union" id="mwAvA">Generalissimus</a>,<sup about="#mwt1281" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004493Khlevniuk2015247_555-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"493"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"247"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004493Khlevniuk2015247-555" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 551;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[551]</span></a></sup> and stood atop Lenin's Mausoleum to watch a celebratory parade led by Zhukov through Red Square.<sup about="#mwt1282" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004480–481_556-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"480–481"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004480–481-556" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 552;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[552]</span></a></sup> At a banquet held for army commanders, he described the Russian people as "the outstanding nation" and "leading force" within the Soviet Union, the first time that he had unequivocally endorsed the Russians over other Soviet nationalities.<sup about="#mwt1283" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004479_557-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"479"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004479-557" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 553;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[553]</span></a></sup> In 1946, the state published Stalin's <i id="mwAvE">Collected Works</i>.<sup about="#mwt1284" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004541_558-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"541"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004541-558" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 554;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[554]</span></a></sup> In 1947, it brought out a second edition of his official biography, which eulogised him to a greater extent than its predecessor.<sup about="#mwt1285" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004543–544_559-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"543–544"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004543–544-559" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 555;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[555]</span></a></sup> He was quoted in <i id="mwAvI">Pravda</i> on a daily basis and pictures of him remained pervasive on the walls of workplaces and homes.<sup about="#mwt1286" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004548_560-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"548"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004548-560" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 556;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[556]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAvM"><a href="./File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376,_Budapest,_II._Weltfestspiele,_Festumzug,_Komsomolzen.jpg" id="mwAvQ"><img resource="./File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376,_Budapest,_II._Weltfestspiele,_Festumzug,_Komsomolzen.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376%2C_Budapest%2C_II._Weltfestspiele%2C_Festumzug%2C_Komsomolzen.jpg/220px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376%2C_Budapest%2C_II._Weltfestspiele%2C_Festumzug%2C_Komsomolzen.jpg" data-file-width="500" data-file-height="763" data-file-type="bitmap" height="336" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376%2C_Budapest%2C_II._Weltfestspiele%2C_Festumzug%2C_Komsomolzen.jpg/440px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376%2C_Budapest%2C_II._Weltfestspiele%2C_Festumzug%2C_Komsomolzen.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/17/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376%2C_Budapest%2C_II._Weltfestspiele%2C_Festumzug%2C_Komsomolzen.jpg/330px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-R78376%2C_Budapest%2C_II._Weltfestspiele%2C_Festumzug%2C_Komsomolzen.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAvU"/></a><figcaption id="mwAvY">Banner of Stalin in Budapest in 1949</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwAvc">Despite his strengthened international position, Stalin was cautious about internal dissent and desire for change among the population.<sup about="#mwt1287" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004485Khlevniuk2015262_561-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"485"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"262"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004485Khlevniuk2015262-561" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 557;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[557]</span></a></sup> He was also concerned about his returning armies, who had been exposed to a wide range of consumer goods in Germany, much of which they had looted and brought back with them. In this he recalled the 1825 <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Decembrist_Revolt" title="Decembrist Revolt" id="mwAvg" class="mw-redirect">Decembrist Revolt</a> by Russian soldiers returning from having defeated France in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Napoleonic_Wars" title="Napoleonic Wars" id="mwAvk">Napoleonic Wars</a>.<sup about="#mwt1288" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004485_562-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"485"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004485-562" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 558;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[558]</span></a></sup> He ensured that returning Soviet prisoners of war went through "filtration" camps as they arrived in the Soviet Union, in which 2,775,700 were interrogated to determine if they were traitors. About half were then imprisoned in labour camps.<sup about="#mwt1289" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004493Roberts2006202_563-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"493"},"2a1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"202"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004493Roberts2006202-563" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 559;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[559]</span></a></sup> In the Baltic states, where there was much opposition to Soviet rule, de-kulakisation and de-clericalisation programs were initiated, resulting in 142,000 deportations between 1945 and 1949.<sup about="#mwt1290" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004492_531-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"492"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004492-531" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 527;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[527]</span></a></sup> The Gulag system of labour camps was expanded further. By January 1953, three percent of the Soviet population was imprisoned or in internal exile, with 2.8 million in "special settlements" in isolated areas and another 2.5 million in camps, penal colonies, and prisons.<sup about="#mwt1291" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015268_564-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"268"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015268-564" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 560;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[560]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAvo">The NKVD were ordered to catalogue the scale of destruction during the war.<sup about="#mwt1292" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004482_565-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"482"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004482-565" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 561;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[561]</span></a></sup> It was established that 1,710 Soviet towns and 70,000 villages had been destroyed.<sup about="#mwt1293" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004482–483_566-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"482–483"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004482–483-566" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 562;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[562]</span></a></sup> The NKVD recorded that <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./World_War_II_casualties_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="World War II casualties of the Soviet Union" id="mwAvs">between 26 and 27 million Soviet citizens had been killed</a>, with millions more being wounded, malnourished, or orphaned.<sup about="#mwt1294" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004482Khlevniuk2015261_567-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"482"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"261"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004482Khlevniuk2015261-567" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 563;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[563]</span></a></sup> In the war's aftermath, some of Stalin's associates suggested modifications to government policy.<sup about="#mwt1295" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004500_568-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"500"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004500-568" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 564;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[564]</span></a></sup> Post-war Soviet society was more tolerant than its pre-war phase in various respects. Stalin allowed the Russian Orthodox Church to retain the churches it had opened during the war.<sup about="#mwt1296" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004496_569-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"496"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004496-569" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 565;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[565]</span></a></sup> Academia and the arts were also allowed greater freedom than they had prior to 1941.<sup about="#mwt1297" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004497_570-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"497"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004497-570" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 566;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[566]</span></a></sup> Recognising the need for drastic steps to be taken to combat inflation and promote economic regeneration, in December 1947 Stalin's government devalued the ruble and abolished the ration-book system.<sup about="#mwt1298" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004497Khlevniuk2015274–278_571-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"497"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"274–278"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004497Khlevniuk2015274–278-571" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 567;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[567]</span></a></sup> Capital punishment was abolished in 1947 but reinstalled in 1950.<sup about="#mwt1299" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991289_572-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"289"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991289-572" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 568;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[568]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAvw">Stalin's health was deteriorating, and heart problems forced a two-month vacation in the latter part of 1945.<sup about="#mwt1300" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991269Service2004491_573-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"269"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"491"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991269Service2004491-573" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 569;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[569]</span></a></sup>
He grew increasingly concerned that senior political and military figures might try to oust him; he prevented any of them from becoming powerful enough to rival him and had their apartments bugged with listening devices.<sup about="#mwt1301" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004526Khlevniuk2015268_574-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"526"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"268"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004526Khlevniuk2015268-574" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 570;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[570]</span></a></sup> He demoted Molotov,<sup about="#mwt1302" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004531–532Khlevniuk2015272–273_575-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"531–532"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"272–273"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004531–532Khlevniuk2015272–273-575" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 571;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[571]</span></a></sup> and increasingly favoured Beria and Malenkov for key positions.<sup about="#mwt1303" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004534_576-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"534"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004534-576" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 572;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[572]</span></a></sup> In 1949, he brought <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikita_Khrushchev" title="Nikita Khrushchev" id="mwAv0">Nikita Khrushchev</a> from Ukraine to Moscow, appointing him a Central Committee secretary and the head of the city's party branch.<sup about="#mwt1304" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015303_577-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"303"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015303-577" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 573;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[573]</span></a></sup> In the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leningrad_Affair" title="Leningrad Affair" id="mwAv4" class="mw-redirect">Leningrad Affair</a>, the city's leadership was purged amid accusations of treachery; executions of many of the accused took place in 1950.<sup about="#mwt1305" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004534–535Khlevniuk2015282_578-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"534–535"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"282"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004534–535Khlevniuk2015282-578" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 574;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[574]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAv8">In the post-war period there were often food shortages in Soviet cities,<sup about="#mwt1306" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015300–301_579-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"300–301"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015300–301-579" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 575;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[575]</span></a></sup> and the USSR experienced a major <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Soviet_famine_of_1946–47" title="Soviet famine of 1946–47" id="mwAwA">famine from 1946 to 1947</a>.<sup about="#mwt1307" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004498Khlevniuk2015261_580-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"498"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"261"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004498Khlevniuk2015261-580" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 576;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[576]</span></a></sup> Sparked by a drought and ensuing bad harvest in 1946, it was exacerbated by government policy towards food procurement, including the state's decision to build up stocks and export food internationally rather than distributing it to famine hit areas.<sup about="#mwt1308" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2000611,_618–620_581-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2000"},"pp":{"wt":"611, 618–620"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2000611,_618–620-581" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 577;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[577]</span></a></sup> Current estimates indicate that between one million and 1.5 million people died from malnutrition or disease as a result.<sup about="#mwt1309" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman2000622Khlevniuk2015261_582-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"1y":{"wt":"2000"},"1p":{"wt":"622"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"261"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman2000622Khlevniuk2015261-582" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 578;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[578]</span></a></sup> While agricultural production stagnated, Stalin focused on a series of major infrastructure projects, including the construction of hydroelectric plants, canals, and railway lines running to the polar north.<sup about="#mwt1310" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015299_583-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"299"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015299-583" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 579;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[579]</span></a></sup> Much of this was constructed by prison labour.<sup about="#mwt1311" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015299_583-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"299"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015299-583" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 579;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[579]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="27" id="mwAwE"><h3 id="Cold_War_policy:_1947–1950"><span id="Cold_War_policy:_1947.E2.80.931950" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Cold War policy: 1947–1950</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAwI"><a href="./File:Mao,_Bulganin,_Stalin,_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg" id="mwAwM"><img resource="./File:Mao,_Bulganin,_Stalin,_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Mao%2C_Bulganin%2C_Stalin%2C_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg/220px-Mao%2C_Bulganin%2C_Stalin%2C_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg" data-file-width="466" data-file-height="297" data-file-type="bitmap" height="140" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Mao%2C_Bulganin%2C_Stalin%2C_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg/440px-Mao%2C_Bulganin%2C_Stalin%2C_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4b/Mao%2C_Bulganin%2C_Stalin%2C_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg/330px-Mao%2C_Bulganin%2C_Stalin%2C_Ulbricht_Tsedenbal.jpeg 1.5x" id="mwAwQ"/></a><figcaption id="mwAwU">Stalin at his seventieth birthday celebration with (left to right) <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mao_Zedong" title="Mao Zedong" id="mwAwY">Mao Zedong</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikolai_Bulganin" title="Nikolai Bulganin" id="mwAwc">Nikolai Bulganin</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Walter_Ulbricht" title="Walter Ulbricht" id="mwAwg">Walter Ulbricht</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Yumjaagiin_Tsedenbal" title="Yumjaagiin Tsedenbal" id="mwAwk">Yumjaagiin Tsedenbal</a></figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAwo">In the aftermath of the Second World War, the British Empire declined, leaving the U.S. and USSR as the dominant world powers.<sup about="#mwt1313" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004502–503_584-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"502–503"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004502–503-584" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 580;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[580]</span></a></sup> Tensions among these former Allies grew,<sup about="#mwt1314" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004484_554-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"484"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004484-554" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 550;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[550]</span></a></sup> resulting in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cold_War" title="Cold War" id="mwAws">Cold War</a>.<sup about="#mwt1315" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004503_585-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"503"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004503-585" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 581;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[581]</span></a></sup> Although Stalin publicly described the British and U.S. governments as aggressive, he thought it unlikely that a war with them would be imminent, believing that several decades of peace was likely.<sup about="#mwt1316" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004487_586-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"487"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004487-586" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 582;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[582]</span></a></sup> He nevertheless secretly intensified Soviet research into nuclear weaponry, intent on creating an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Atom_bomb" title="Atom bomb" id="mwAww" class="mw-redirect">atom bomb</a>.<sup about="#mwt1317" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004481_553-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"481"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004481-553" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 549;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[549]</span></a></sup> Still, Stalin foresaw the undesirability of a nuclear conflict, saying in 1949 that "atomic weapons can hardly be used without spelling the end of the world."<sup about="#mwt4556" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-587" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-587"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-587" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 583;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[583]</span></a></sup> He personally took a keen interest in the development of the weapon.<sup about="#mwt1319" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004508_588-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"508"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004508-588" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 584;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[584]</span></a></sup> In August 1949, the bomb was successfully tested in the deserts outside <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Semipalatinsk" title="Semipalatinsk" id="mwAw0" class="mw-redirect">Semipalatinsk</a> in Kazakhstan.<sup about="#mwt1320" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004508Khlevniuk2015293_589-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"508"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"293"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004508Khlevniuk2015293-589" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 585;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[585]</span></a></sup> Stalin also initiated a new military build-up; the Soviet army was expanded from 2.9 million soldiers, as it stood in 1949, to 5.8 million by 1953.<sup about="#mwt1321" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015297_590-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"297"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015297-590" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 586;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[586]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAw4">The US began pushing its interests on every continent, acquiring air force bases in Africa and Asia and ensuring pro-U.S. regimes took power across Latin America.<sup about="#mwt1322" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004502_591-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"502"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004502-591" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 587;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[587]</span></a></sup> It launched the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Marshall_Plan" title="Marshall Plan" id="mwAw8">Marshall Plan</a> in June 1947, with which it sought to undermine Soviet hegemony in eastern Europe. The US also offered financial assistance as part of the Marshall Plan on the condition that they opened their markets to trade, aware that the Soviets would never agree.<sup about="#mwt1323" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004504Khlevniuk2015267_592-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"504"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"267"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004504Khlevniuk2015267-592" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 588;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[588]</span></a></sup>
The Allies demanded that Stalin withdraw the Red Army from northern Iran, which he did in April 1947.<sup about="#mwt1324" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004504_593-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"504"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004504-593" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 589;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[589]</span></a></sup>
Stalin also tried to maximise Soviet influence on the world stage, unsuccessfully pushing for Libya—recently liberated from Italian occupation—to become a Soviet protectorate.<sup about="#mwt1325" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004494_594-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"494"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004494-594" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 590;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[590]</span></a></sup> He sent Molotov as his representative to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./San_Francisco" title="San Francisco" id="mwAxA">San Francisco</a> to take part in negotiations to form the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./United_Nations" title="United Nations" id="mwAxE">United Nations</a>, insisting that the Soviets have a place on the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Security_Council" title="Security Council" id="mwAxI" class="mw-redirect">Security Council</a>.<sup about="#mwt1326" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004503_585-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"503"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004503-585" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 581;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[581]</span></a></sup> In April 1949, the Western powers established the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./NATO" title="NATO" id="mwAxM">North Atlantic Treaty Organisation</a> (NATO), an international military alliance of capitalist countries.<sup about="#mwt1327" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004507Khlevniuk2015281_595-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"507"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"281"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004507Khlevniuk2015281-595" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 591;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[591]</span></a></sup> Within Western countries, Stalin was increasingly portrayed as the "most evil dictator alive" and compared to Hitler.<sup about="#mwt1328" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004551_596-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"551"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004551-596" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 592;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[592]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAxQ">In 1948, Stalin edited and rewrote sections of <i id="mwAxU"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Falsifiers_of_History" title="Falsifiers of History" id="mwAxY">Falsifiers of History</a></i>, published as a series of <i id="mwAxc">Pravda</i> articles in February 1948 and then in book form. Written in response to public revelations of the 1939 Soviet alliance with Germany, it focused on blaming Western powers for the war.<sup about="#mwt1329" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERoberts200296–98_597-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Roberts"},"2":{"wt":"2002"},"pp":{"wt":"96–98"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERoberts200296–98-597" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 593;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[593]</span></a></sup> He erroneously claimed that the initial German advance in the early part of the war was not a result of Soviet military weakness, but rather a deliberate Soviet strategic retreat.<sup about="#mwt1330" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015264_598-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"264"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015264-598" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 594;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[594]</span></a></sup> In 1949, celebrations took place to mark Stalin's seventieth birthday (albeit not the correct year) at which Stalin attended an event in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bolshoi_Theatre" title="Bolshoi Theatre" id="mwAxg">Bolshoi Theatre</a> alongside Marxist–Leninist leaders from across Europe and Asia.<sup about="#mwt1331" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991296Service2004548–549Khlevniuk2015290_599-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"296"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"548–549"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"290"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991296Service2004548–549Khlevniuk2015290-599" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 595;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[595]</span></a></sup></p>

<section data-mw-section-id="28" id="mwAxk"><h4 id="The_Eastern_Bloc">The Eastern Bloc</h4>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAxo"><a href="./File:EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg" id="mwAxs"><img resource="./File:EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg/220px-EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg.png" data-file-width="404" data-file-height="612" data-file-type="drawing" height="333" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg/440px-EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/57/EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg/330px-EasternBloc_BasicMembersOnly.svg.png 1.5x" id="mwAxw"/></a><figcaption id="mwAx0">The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Eastern_Bloc" title="Eastern Bloc" id="mwAx4">Eastern Bloc</a> until 1989</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwAx8">After the war, Stalin sought to retain Soviet dominance across Eastern Europe while expanding its influence in Asia.<sup about="#mwt1332" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004492_531-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"492"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004492-531" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 527;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[527]</span></a></sup> Cautiously regarding the responses from the Western Allies, Stalin avoided immediately installing Communist Party governments across Eastern Europe, instead initially ensuring that Marxist-Leninists were placed in coalition ministries.<sup about="#mwt1333" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004494_594-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"494"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004494-594" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 590;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[590]</span></a></sup> In contrast to his approach to the Baltic states, he rejected the proposal of merging the new communist states into the Soviet Union, rather recognising them as independent nation-states.<sup about="#mwt1334" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004517_600-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"517"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004517-600" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 596;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[596]</span></a></sup>
He was faced with the problem that there were few Marxists left in Eastern Europe, with most having been killed by the Nazis.<sup about="#mwt1335" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004483_601-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"483"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004483-601" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 597;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[597]</span></a></sup> He demanded that war reparations be paid by Germany and its Axis allies Hungary, Romania, and the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Slovak_Republic_(1939–1945)" title="Slovak Republic (1939–1945)" id="mwAyA">Slovak Republic</a>.<sup about="#mwt1336" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004484_554-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"484"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004484-554" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 550;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[550]</span></a></sup> Aware that these countries had been pushed toward socialism through invasion rather than by proletarian revolution, Stalin referred to them not as "dictatorships of the proletariat" but as "people's democracies", suggesting that in these countries there was a pro-socialist alliance combining the proletariat, peasantry, and lower middle-class.<sup about="#mwt1337" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004518_602-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"518"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004518-602" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 598;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[598]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAyE">Churchill observed that an "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Iron_Curtain" title="Iron Curtain" id="mwAyI">Iron Curtain</a>" had been drawn across Europe, separating the east from the west.<sup about="#mwt1338" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991279Service2004503_603-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"279"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"503"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991279Service2004503-603" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 599;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[599]</span></a></sup> In September 1947, a meeting of East European communist leaders was held in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Szklarska_Poręba" title="Szklarska Poręba" id="mwAyM">Szklarska Poręba</a>, Poland, from which was formed <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cominform" title="Cominform" id="mwAyQ">Cominform</a> to co-ordinate the Communist Parties across Eastern Europe and also in France and Italy.<sup about="#mwt1339" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991286Service2004506Khlevniuk2015267_604-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"286"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"506"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"267"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991286Service2004506Khlevniuk2015267-604" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 600;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[600]</span></a></sup> Stalin did not personally attend the meeting, sending Zhdanov in his place.<sup about="#mwt1340" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004506_552-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"506"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004506-552" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 548;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[548]</span></a></sup> Various East European communists also visited Stalin in Moscow.<sup about="#mwt1341" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004511_605-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"511"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004511-605" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 601;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[601]</span></a></sup> There, he offered advice on their ideas; for instance he cautioned against the Yugoslav idea for a Balkan federation incorporating Bulgaria and Albania.<sup about="#mwt1342" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004511_605-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"511"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004511-605" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 601;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[601]</span></a></sup> Stalin had a particularly strained relationship with Yugoslav leader <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Josip_Broz_Tito" title="Josip Broz Tito" id="mwAyU">Josip Broz Tito</a> due to the latter's continued calls for Balkan federation and for Soviet aid for the communist forces in the ongoing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Greek_Civil_War" title="Greek Civil War" id="mwAyY">Greek Civil War</a>.<sup about="#mwt1343" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991286–287Service2004515_606-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"286–287"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"515"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991286–287Service2004515-606" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 602;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[602]</span></a></sup> In March 1948, Stalin launched an anti-Tito campaign, accusing the Yugoslav communists of adventurism and deviating from Marxist–Leninist doctrine.<sup about="#mwt1344" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004515_607-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"515"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004515-607" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 603;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[603]</span></a></sup> At the second Cominform conference, held in Bucharest in June 1948, East European communist leaders all denounced Tito's government, accusing them of being fascists and agents of Western capitalism.<sup about="#mwt1345" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004516_608-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"516"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004516-608" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 604;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[604]</span></a></sup> Stalin ordered several assassination attempts on Tito's life and contemplated invading Yugoslavia.<sup about="#mwt1346" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991287_609-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"287"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991287-609" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 605;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[605]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAyc">Stalin suggested that a unified, but demilitarised, German state be established, hoping that it would either come under Soviet influence or remain neutral.<sup about="#mwt1347" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004507_610-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"507"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004507-610" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 606;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[606]</span></a></sup> When the US and UK remained opposed to this, Stalin sought to force their hand by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Berlin_Blockade" title="Berlin Blockade" id="mwAyg">blockading Berlin</a> in June 1948.<sup about="#mwt1348" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991280Service2004507Khlevniuk2015281_611-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"280"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"507"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"281"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991280Service2004507Khlevniuk2015281-611" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 607;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[607]</span></a></sup> He gambled that the others would not risk war, but they airlifted supplies into West Berlin until May 1949, when Stalin relented and ended the blockade.<sup about="#mwt1349" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004507Khlevniuk2015281_595-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"507"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"281"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004507Khlevniuk2015281-595" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 591;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[591]</span></a></sup> In September 1949 the Western powers transformed Western Germany into an independent <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Federal_Republic_of_Germany" title="Federal Republic of Germany" id="mwAyk" class="mw-redirect">Federal Republic of Germany</a>; in response the Soviets formed East Germany into the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./German_Democratic_Republic" title="German Democratic Republic" id="mwAyo" class="mw-redirect">German Democratic Republic</a> in October.<sup about="#mwt1350" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004507_610-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"507"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004507-610" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 606;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[606]</span></a></sup> In accordance with their earlier agreements, the Western powers expected Poland to become an independent state with free democratic elections.<sup about="#mwt1351" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004476_612-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"476"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004476-612" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 608;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[608]</span></a></sup> In Poland, the Soviets merged various socialist parties into the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Polish_United_Workers'_Party" title="Polish United Workers' Party" id="mwAys">Polish United Workers' Party</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Electoral_fraud" title="Electoral fraud" id="mwAyw">vote rigging</a> was used to ensure that it secured office.<sup about="#mwt1352" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004515_607-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"515"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004515-607" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 603;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[603]</span></a></sup> The 1947 Hungarian elections were also rigged, with the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hungarian_Working_People's_Party" title="Hungarian Working People's Party" id="mwAy0">Hungarian Working People's Party</a> taking control.<sup about="#mwt1353" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004515_607-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"515"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004515-607" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 603;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[603]</span></a></sup> In Czechoslovakia, where the communists did have a level of popular support, they were elected the largest party in 1946.<sup about="#mwt1354" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004512,_513_613-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"512, 513"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004512,_513-613" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 609;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[609]</span></a></sup> Monarchy was abolished in Bulgaria and Romania.<sup about="#mwt1355" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004513_614-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"513"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004513-614" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 610;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[610]</span></a></sup> Across Eastern Europe, the Soviet model was enforced, with a termination of political pluralism, agricultural collectivisation, and investment in heavy industry.<sup about="#mwt1356" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004516_608-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"516"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004516-608" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 604;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[604]</span></a></sup> It was aimed for economic <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Autarky" title="Autarky" id="mwAy4">autarky</a> within the Eastern Bloc.<sup about="#mwt1357" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004516_608-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"516"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004516-608" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 604;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[604]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="29" id="mwAy8"><h4 id="Asia">Asia</h4>
<p id="mwAzA">In October 1949, Mao took power in China.<sup about="#mwt1358" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991301Service2004509Khlevniuk2015286_615-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"301"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"509"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"286"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991301Service2004509Khlevniuk2015286-615" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 611;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[611]</span></a></sup> With this accomplished, Marxist governments now controlled a third of the world's land mass.<sup about="#mwt1359" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004509_616-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"509"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004509-616" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 612;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[612]</span></a></sup> Privately, Stalin revealed that he had underestimated the Chinese Communists and their ability to win the civil war, instead encouraging them to make another peace with the KMT.<sup about="#mwt1360" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004553_617-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"553"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004553-617" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 613;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[613]</span></a></sup> In December 1949, Mao visited Stalin. Initially Stalin refused to repeal the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sino-Soviet_Treaty_of_Friendship_and_Alliance" title="Sino-Soviet Treaty of Friendship and Alliance" id="mwAzE">Sino-Soviet Treaty of 1945</a>, which significantly benefited the Soviet Union over China, although in January 1950 he relented and agreed to sign <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sino-Soviet_Treaty_of_Friendship,_Alliance_and_Mutual_Assistance" title="Sino-Soviet Treaty of Friendship, Alliance and Mutual Assistance" id="mwAzI">a new treaty between the two countries</a>.<sup about="#mwt1361" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004509Khlevniuk2015287–291_618-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"509"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"287–291"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004509Khlevniuk2015287–291-618" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 614;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[614]</span></a></sup> Stalin was concerned that Mao might follow Tito's example by pursuing a course independent of Soviet influence, and made it known that if displeased he would withdraw assistance from China; the Chinese desperately needed said assistance after decades of civil war.<sup about="#mwt1362" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004552Khlevniuk2015287_619-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"552"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"287"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004552Khlevniuk2015287-619" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 615;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[615]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwAzM"><a href="./File:Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg" id="mwAzQ"><img resource="./File:Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg/220px-Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg" data-file-width="2751" data-file-height="1593" data-file-type="bitmap" height="127" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg/440px-Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg/330px-Chinese_stamp_in_1950.jpg 1.5x" id="mwAzU"/></a><figcaption id="mwAzY">Stalin and Mao Zedong depicted on a Chinese postage stamp from 1950</figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwAzc">At the end of the Second World War, the Soviet Union and the United States divided up the Korean Peninsula, formerly a Japanese colonial possession, along the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Division_of_Korea" title="Division of Korea" id="mwAzg">38th parallel</a>, setting up a communist government in the north and a pro-Western government in the south.<sup about="#mwt1363" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004552Khlevniuk2015294_620-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"552"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"294"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004552Khlevniuk2015294-620" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 616;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[616]</span></a></sup> North Korean leader <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kim_Il-Sung" title="Kim Il-Sung" id="mwAzk" class="mw-redirect">Kim Il-Sung</a> visited Stalin in March 1949 and again in March 1950; he wanted to invade the south and although Stalin was initially reluctant to provide support, he eventually agreed by May 1950.<sup about="#mwt1364" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991302Service2004553Khlevniuk2015294–295_621-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"302"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"553"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3pp":{"wt":"294–295"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991302Service2004553Khlevniuk2015294–295-621" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 617;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[617]</span></a></sup> The <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Korean_People's_Army" title="Korean People's Army" id="mwAzo">North Korean Army</a> launched the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Korean_War" title="Korean War" id="mwAzs">Korean War</a> by invading the south in June 1950, making swift gains and capturing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Seoul" title="Seoul" id="mwAzw">Seoul</a>.<sup about="#mwt1365" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004554_622-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"554"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004554-622" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 618;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[618]</span></a></sup> Both Stalin and Mao believed that a swift victory would ensue.<sup about="#mwt1366" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004554_622-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"554"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004554-622" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 618;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[618]</span></a></sup> The U.S. went to the UN Security Council—which the Soviets were boycotting over its refusal to recognise Mao's government—and secured military support for the South Koreans. U.S. led forces pushed the North Koreans back.<sup about="#mwt1367" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004554Khlevniuk2015295–296_623-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"554"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"295–296"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004554Khlevniuk2015295–296-623" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 619;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[619]</span></a></sup> Stalin wanted to avoid direct Soviet conflict with the U.S., convincing the Chinese to aid the North.<sup about="#mwt1368" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004555–556Khlevniuk2015296_624-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"555–556"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"296"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004555–556Khlevniuk2015296-624" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 620;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[620]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwAz0">The Soviet Union was one of the first nations to extend diplomatic recognition to the newly created state of Israel in 1948. When the Israeli ambassador <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Golda_Meir" title="Golda Meir" id="mwAz4">Golda Meir</a> arrived in the USSR, Stalin was angered by the Jewish crowds who gathered to greet her.<sup about="#mwt1369" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991291_625-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"291"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991291-625" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 621;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[621]</span></a></sup> He was further angered by Israel's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Israel–United_States_relations" title="Israel–United States relations" id="mwAz8">growing alliance with the U.S.</a><sup about="#mwt1370" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015285_626-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"285"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015285-626" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 622;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[622]</span></a></sup> After Stalin fell out with Israel, he launched an anti-Jewish campaign within the Soviet Union and the Eastern Bloc.<sup about="#mwt1371" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004518_602-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"518"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004518-602" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 598;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[598]</span></a></sup> In November 1948, he abolished the JAC,<sup about="#mwt1372" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991291Service2004577Khlevniuk2015284_627-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"291"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"577"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"284"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991291Service2004577Khlevniuk2015284-627" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 623;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[623]</span></a></sup> and show trials took place for some of its members.<sup about="#mwt1373" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991567Brackman2001384–5_628-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"567"},"2a1":{"wt":"Brackman"},"2y":{"wt":"2001"},"2pp":{"wt":"384–5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991567Brackman2001384–5-628" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 624;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[624]</span></a></sup> The Soviet press engaged in attacks on <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Zionism" title="Zionism" id="mwA0A">Zionism</a>, Jewish culture, and "rootless cosmopolitanism",<sup about="#mwt1374" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991291Khlevniuk2015308–309_629-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"291"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"308–309"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991291Khlevniuk2015308–309-629" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 625;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[625]</span></a></sup> with growing levels of anti-Semitism being expressed across Soviet society.<sup about="#mwt1375" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004576–577_630-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"576–577"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004576–577-630" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 626;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[626]</span></a></sup> Stalin's increasing tolerance of anti-Semitism may have stemmed from his increasing Russian nationalism or from the recognition that anti-Semitism had proved a useful mobilising tool for Hitler and that he could do the same;<sup about="#mwt1376" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991290_631-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"290"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991290-631" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 627;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[627]</span></a></sup> he may have increasingly viewed the Jewish people as a "counter-revolutionary" nation whose members were loyal to the U.S.<sup about="#mwt1377" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015286_632-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"286"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015286-632" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 628;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[628]</span></a></sup> There were rumours, although they have never been substantiated, that Stalin was planning on deporting all Soviet Jews to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Jewish_Autonomous_Region" title="Jewish Autonomous Region" id="mwA0E" class="mw-redirect">Jewish Autonomous Region</a> in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Birobidzhan" title="Birobidzhan" id="mwA0I">Birobidzhan</a>, eastern Siberia.<sup about="#mwt1378" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004577Overy2004565Khlevniuk2015309_633-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"577"},"2a1":{"wt":"Overy"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"565"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"309"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004577Overy2004565Khlevniuk2015309-633" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 629;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[629]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="30" id="mwA0M"><h3 id="Final_years:_1950–1953"><span id="Final_years:_1950.E2.80.931953" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Final years: 1950–1953</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA0Q"><a href="./File:Vrachi-timashuk.png" id="mwA0U"><img resource="./File:Vrachi-timashuk.png" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Vrachi-timashuk.png/220px-Vrachi-timashuk.png" data-file-width="597" data-file-height="800" data-file-type="bitmap" height="295" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Vrachi-timashuk.png/440px-Vrachi-timashuk.png 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8e/Vrachi-timashuk.png/330px-Vrachi-timashuk.png 1.5x" id="mwA0Y"/></a><figcaption id="mwA0c">20 January 1953. Soviet <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ukaz" title="Ukaz" id="mwA0g" class="mw-redirect">ukaz</a> awarding Lydia Timashuk the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Order_of_Lenin" title="Order of Lenin" id="mwA0k">Order of Lenin</a> for "unmasking doctors-killers." Revoked after Stalin's death later that year.</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwA0o">In his later years, Stalin was in poor health.<sup about="#mwt1379" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004571_634-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"571"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004571-634" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 630;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[630]</span></a></sup> He took increasingly long holidays; in 1950 and again in 1951 he spent almost five months vacationing at his Abkhazian dacha.<sup about="#mwt1380" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004572Khlevniuk2015195_635-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"572"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"195"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004572Khlevniuk2015195-635" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 631;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[631]</span></a></sup> Stalin nevertheless mistrusted his doctors; in January 1952 he had one imprisoned after they suggested that he should retire to improve his health.<sup about="#mwt1381" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004571_634-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"571"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004571-634" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 630;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[630]</span></a></sup> In September 1952, several Kremlin doctors were arrested for allegedly plotting to kill senior politicians in what came to be known as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Doctors'_Plot" title="Doctors' Plot" id="mwA0s" class="mw-redirect">Doctors' Plot</a>; the majority of the accused were Jewish.<sup about="#mwt1382" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991309Etinger1995104Service2004576Khlevniuk2015307_636-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"309"},"2a1":{"wt":"Etinger"},"2y":{"wt":"1995"},"2p":{"wt":"104"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"576"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"307"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991309Etinger1995104Service2004576Khlevniuk2015307-636" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 632;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[632]</span></a></sup> He instructed the arrested doctors to be tortured to ensure confession.<sup about="#mwt1383" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991309Khlevniuk2015307–308_637-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"309"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"307–308"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991309Khlevniuk2015307–308-637" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 633;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[633]</span></a></sup> In November, the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Slánský_trial" title="Slánský trial" id="mwA0w">Slánský trial</a> took place in Czechoslovakia as 13 senior Communist Party figures, 11 of them Jewish, were accused and convicted of being part of a vast Zionist-American conspiracy to subvert Eastern Bloc governments.<sup about="#mwt1384" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991308Khlevniuk2015307_638-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"308"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"307"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991308Khlevniuk2015307-638" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 634;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[634]</span></a></sup> That same month, a much publicised trial of accused Jewish industrial wreckers took place in Ukraine.<sup about="#mwt1385" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991308_639-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"308"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991308-639" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 635;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[635]</span></a></sup> In 1951, he initiated the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mingrelian_affair" title="Mingrelian affair" id="mwA00">Mingrelian affair</a>, a purge of the Georgian branch of the Communist Party which resulted in over 11,000 deportations.<sup about="#mwt1386" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015304–305_640-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"304–305"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015304–305-640" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 636;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[636]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA04">From 1946 until his death, Stalin only gave three public speeches, two of which lasted only a few minutes.<sup about="#mwt1387" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004560_641-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"560"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004560-641" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 637;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[637]</span></a></sup> The amount of written material that he produced also declined.<sup about="#mwt1388" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004560_641-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"560"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004560-641" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 637;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[637]</span></a></sup> In 1950, Stalin issued the article "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Marxism_and_Problems_of_Linguistics" title="Marxism and Problems of Linguistics" id="mwA08">Marxism and Problems of Linguistics</a>", which reflected his interest in questions of Russian nationhood.<sup about="#mwt1389" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004564–565_642-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"564–565"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004564–565-642" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 638;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[638]</span></a></sup>
In 1952, Stalin's last book, <i id="mwA1A"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Economic_Problems_of_Socialism_in_the_USSR" title="Economic Problems of Socialism in the USSR" id="mwA1E">Economic Problems of Socialism in the USSR</a></i>, was published. It sought to provide a guide to leading the country for after his death.<sup about="#mwt1390" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991307Service2004566–567_643-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"307"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"566–567"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991307Service2004566–567-643" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 639;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[639]</span></a></sup> In October 1952, Stalin gave an hour and a half speech at the Central Committee plenum.<sup about="#mwt1391" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004578_644-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"578"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004578-644" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 640;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[640]</span></a></sup> There, he emphasised what he regarded as leadership qualities necessary in the future and highlighted the weaknesses of various potential successors, particularly Molotov and Mikoyan.<sup about="#mwt1392" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004579Khlevniuk2015306_645-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"579"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"306"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004579Khlevniuk2015306-645" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 641;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[641]</span></a></sup> In 1952, he also eliminated the Politburo and replaced it with a larger version which he called the Presidium.<sup about="#mwt1393" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015305–306_646-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"305–306"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015305–306-646" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 642;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[642]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="31" id="mwA1I"><h3 id="Death,_funeral_and_aftermath:_1953"><span id="Death.2C_funeral_and_aftermath:_1953" typeof="mw:FallbackId"></span>Death, funeral and aftermath: 1953</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1394" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Death and state funeral of Joseph Stalin"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA1M">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Death_and_state_funeral_of_Joseph_Stalin" title="Death and state funeral of Joseph Stalin">Death and state funeral of Joseph Stalin</a></div>
<p id="mwA1Q">On 1 March 1953, Stalin's staff found him semi-conscious on the bedroom floor of his <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kuntsevo_Dacha" title="Kuntsevo Dacha" id="mwA1U">Volynskoe dacha</a>.<sup about="#mwt1395" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991311Volkogonov1991571–572Service2004582–584Khlevniuk2015142,_191_647-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"311"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"571–572"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"582–584"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4pp":{"wt":"142, 191"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991311Volkogonov1991571–572Service2004582–584Khlevniuk2015142,_191-647" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 643;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[643]</span></a></sup> He had suffered a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cerebral_hemorrhage" title="Cerebral hemorrhage" id="mwA1Y" class="mw-redirect">cerebral hemorrhage</a>.<sup about="#mwt1396" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312_648-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"312"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312-648" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 644;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[644]</span></a></sup> He was moved onto a couch and remained there for three days.<sup about="#mwt1397" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991311–312Volkogonov1991572Khlevniuk2015142_649-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"311–312"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"572"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"142"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991311–312Volkogonov1991572Khlevniuk2015142-649" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 645;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[645]</span></a></sup> He was hand-fed using a spoon, given various medicines and injections, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leech_therapy" title="Leech therapy" id="mwA1c" class="mw-redirect">leeches were applied to him</a>.<sup about="#mwt1398" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312_648-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"312"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312-648" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 644;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[644]</span></a></sup> Svetlana and Vasily were called to the dacha on 2 March; the latter was drunk and angrily shouted at the doctors, resulting in him being sent home.<sup about="#mwt1399" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312Khlevniuk2015250_650-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"312"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"250"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312Khlevniuk2015250-650" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 646;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[646]</span></a></sup> Stalin died on 5 March 1953.<sup about="#mwt1400" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991313Volkogonov1991574Service2004586Khlevniuk2015313_651-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"313"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"574"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"586"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"313"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991313Volkogonov1991574Service2004586Khlevniuk2015313-651" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 647;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[647]</span></a></sup> According to Svetlana, it had been "a difficult and terrible death".<sup about="#mwt1401" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991313Khlevniuk2015313–314_652-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"313"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"313–314"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991313Khlevniuk2015313–314-652" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 648;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[648]</span></a></sup> An autopsy revealed that he had died of a cerebral hemorrhage and that he also suffered from severe damage to his cerebral arteries due to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Atherosclerosis" title="Atherosclerosis" id="mwA1g">atherosclerosis</a>.<sup about="#mwt1402" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015189_653-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"189"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015189-653" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 649;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[649]</span></a></sup> It is possible that Stalin was murdered.<sup about="#mwt1403" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004587_654-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"587"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004587-654" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 650;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[650]</span></a></sup> Beria has been suspected of murder, although no firm evidence has ever appeared.<sup about="#mwt1404" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312_648-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"312"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991312-648" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 644;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[644]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA1k">Stalin's death was announced on 6 March.<sup about="#mwt1405" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004588_655-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"588"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004588-655" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 651;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[651]</span></a></sup> The body was embalmed,<sup about="#mwt1406" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004588Khlevniuk2015314_656-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"588"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"314"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004588Khlevniuk2015314-656" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 652;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[652]</span></a></sup> and then placed on display in Moscow's House of Unions for three days.<sup about="#mwt1407" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015317_657-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"317"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015317-657" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 653;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[653]</span></a></sup> Crowds were such that a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Human_stampede" title="Human stampede" id="mwA1o" class="mw-redirect">crush</a> killed around 100 people.<sup about="#mwt1408" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004588Khlevniuk2015317_658-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"588"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"317"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004588Khlevniuk2015317-658" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 654;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[654]</span></a></sup> The funeral involved the body being laid to rest in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lenin's_Mausoleum" title="Lenin's Mausoleum" id="mwA1s">Lenin's Mausoleum</a> in Red Square on 9 March; hundreds of thousands attended.<sup about="#mwt1409" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991576Service2004589Khlevniuk2015318_659-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"576"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"589"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"318"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991576Service2004589Khlevniuk2015318-659" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 655;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[655]</span></a></sup> That month featured a surge in arrests for "anti-Soviet agitation" as those celebrating Stalin's death came to police attention.<sup about="#mwt1410" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015319_660-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"319"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015319-660" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 656;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[656]</span></a></sup> The Chinese government instituted a period of official mourning for Stalin's death.<sup about="#mwt1411" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELi200975_661-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Li"},"2":{"wt":"2009"},"p":{"wt":"75"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTELi200975-661" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 657;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[657]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA1w">Stalin left no anointed successor nor a framework within which a transfer of power could take place.<sup about="#mwt1413" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015310_662-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"310"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015310-662" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 658;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[658]</span></a></sup> The Central Committee met on the day of his death, with Malenkov, Beria, and Khruschev emerging as the party's key figures.<sup about="#mwt1414" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004586–587_663-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"586–587"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004586–587-663" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 659;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[659]</span></a></sup> The system of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Collective_leadership" title="Collective leadership" id="mwA10">collective leadership</a> was restored, and measures introduced to prevent any one member attaining autocratic domination again.<sup about="#mwt1415" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015312_664-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"312"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015312-664" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 660;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[660]</span></a></sup> The collective leadership included the following eight senior members of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Politburo_of_the_Central_Committee_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="Politburo of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwA14" class="mw-redirect">Presidium of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union</a> listed according to the order of precedence presented formally on 5 March 1953: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgy_Malenkov" title="Georgy Malenkov" id="mwA18">Georgy Malenkov</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lavrentiy_Beria" title="Lavrentiy Beria" id="mwA2A">Lavrentiy Beria</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vyacheslav_Molotov" title="Vyacheslav Molotov" id="mwA2E">Vyacheslav Molotov</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kliment_Voroshilov" title="Kliment Voroshilov" id="mwA2I">Kliment Voroshilov</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikita_Khrushchev" title="Nikita Khrushchev" id="mwA2M">Nikita Khrushchev</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikolai_Bulganin" title="Nikolai Bulganin" id="mwA2Q">Nikolai Bulganin</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lazar_Kaganovich" title="Lazar Kaganovich" id="mwA2U">Lazar Kaganovich</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anastas_Mikoyan" title="Anastas Mikoyan" id="mwA2Y">Anastas Mikoyan</a>.<sup about="#mwt4558" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-665" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-665"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-665" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 661;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[661]</span></a></sup> Reforms to the Soviet system were immediately implemented.<sup about="#mwt1417" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004591_666-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"591"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004591-666" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 662;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[662]</span></a></sup> Economic reform scaled back the mass construction projects, placed a new emphasis on house building, and eased the levels of taxation on the peasantry to stimulate production.<sup about="#mwt1418" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015315_667-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"315"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015315-667" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 663;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[663]</span></a></sup> The new leaders sought rapprochement with Yugoslavia and a less hostile relationship with the U.S.,<sup about="#mwt1419" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004593_668-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"593"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004593-668" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 664;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[664]</span></a></sup> pursuing a negotiated end to the Korean War in July 1953.<sup about="#mwt1420" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015316_669-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"316"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015316-669" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 665;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[665]</span></a></sup> The doctors who had been imprisoned were released and the anti-Semitic purges ceased.<sup about="#mwt1421" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEtinger1995120–121Conquest1991314Khlevniuk2015314_670-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Etinger"},"1y":{"wt":"1995"},"1pp":{"wt":"120–121"},"2a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"314"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"314"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEtinger1995120–121Conquest1991314Khlevniuk2015314-670" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 666;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[666]</span></a></sup> A mass amnesty for those imprisoned for non-political crimes was issued, halving the country's inmate population, while the state security and Gulag systems were reformed, with torture being banned in April 1953.<sup about="#mwt1422" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015315_667-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"315"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015315-667" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 663;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[663]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="32" id="mwA2c"><h2 id="Political_ideology">Political ideology</h2>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt1423" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Further","href":"./Template:Further"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Stalinism"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA2g">Further information: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stalinism" title="Stalinism">Stalinism</a></div>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA2k"><a href="./File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002,_Dresden,_Tod_Stalin,_Parade_KVP.jpg" id="mwA2o"><img resource="./File:Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002,_Dresden,_Tod_Stalin,_Parade_KVP.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002%2C_Dresden%2C_Tod_Stalin%2C_Parade_KVP.jpg/220px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002%2C_Dresden%2C_Tod_Stalin%2C_Parade_KVP.jpg" data-file-width="621" data-file-height="800" data-file-type="bitmap" height="283" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002%2C_Dresden%2C_Tod_Stalin%2C_Parade_KVP.jpg/440px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002%2C_Dresden%2C_Tod_Stalin%2C_Parade_KVP.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d4/Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002%2C_Dresden%2C_Tod_Stalin%2C_Parade_KVP.jpg/330px-Bundesarchiv_Bild_183-18684-0002%2C_Dresden%2C_Tod_Stalin%2C_Parade_KVP.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA2s"/></a><figcaption id="mwA2w">A mourning parade to Stalin in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dresden" title="Dresden" id="mwA20">Dresden</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./East_Germany" title="East Germany" id="mwA24">East Germany</a></figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwA28">Stalin claimed to have embraced Marxism at the age of fifteen,<sup about="#mwt1424" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERieber200532_671-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Rieber"},"2":{"wt":"2005"},"p":{"wt":"32"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERieber200532-671" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 667;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[667]</span></a></sup> and it served as the guiding philosophy throughout his adult life;<sup about="#mwt1425" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20049_672-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20049-672" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 668;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[668]</span></a></sup> according to Kotkin, Stalin held "zealous Marxist convictions",<sup about="#mwt1426" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014xi_673-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"xi"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014xi-673" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 669;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[669]</span></a></sup> while Montefiore suggested that Marxism held a "quasi-religious" value for Stalin.<sup about="#mwt1427" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007336_674-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"336"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007336-674" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 670;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[670]</span></a></sup> Although he never became a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgian_nationalism" title="Georgian nationalism" id="mwA3A">Georgian nationalist</a>,<sup about="#mwt1428" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERieber200543_675-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Rieber"},"2":{"wt":"2005"},"p":{"wt":"43"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERieber200543-675" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 671;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[671]</span></a></sup> during his early life elements from Georgian nationalist thought blended with Marxism in his outlook.<sup about="#mwt1429" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200767_676-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"67"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200767-676" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 672;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[672]</span></a></sup> The historian Alfred J. Rieber noted that he had been raised in "a society where rebellion was deeply rooted in folklore and popular rituals".<sup about="#mwt1430" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERieber200543_675-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Rieber"},"2":{"wt":"2005"},"p":{"wt":"43"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERieber200543-675" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 671;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[671]</span></a></sup> Stalin believed in the need to adapt Marxism to changing circumstances; in 1917, he declared that "there is dogmatic Marxism and there is creative Marxism. I stand on the ground of the latter".<sup about="#mwt1431" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004136Kotkin2014205Khlevniuk201547_677-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"136"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"205"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"47"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004136Kotkin2014205Khlevniuk201547-677" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 673;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[673]</span></a></sup> Volkogonov believed that Stalin's Marxism was shaped by his "dogmatic turn of mind", suggesting that this had been instilled in the Soviet leader during his education in religious institutions.<sup about="#mwt1432" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19917_678-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19917-678" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 674;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[674]</span></a></sup> According to scholar Robert Service, Stalin's "few innovations in ideology were crude, dubious developments of Marxism".<sup about="#mwt1433" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20049_672-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20049-672" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 668;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[668]</span></a></sup> Some of these derived from political expediency rather than any sincere intellectual commitment;<sup about="#mwt1434" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20049_672-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20049-672" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 668;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[668]</span></a></sup> Stalin would often turn to ideology <i id="mwA3E">post hoc</i> to justify his decisions.<sup about="#mwt1435" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20067_679-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20067-679" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 675;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[675]</span></a></sup> Stalin referred to himself as a <i id="mwA3I">praktik</i>, meaning that he was more of a practical revolutionary than a theoretician.<sup about="#mwt1436" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200492Kotkin2014462_680-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"92"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"462"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200492Kotkin2014462-680" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 676;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[676]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA3M">As a Marxist, Stalin believed in an inevitable <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Class_struggle" title="Class struggle" id="mwA3Q" class="mw-redirect">class war</a> between the world's proletariat and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bourgeoise" title="Bourgeoise" id="mwA3U" class="mw-redirect">bourgeoise</a>.<sup about="#mwt1493" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200493_681-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"93"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200493-681" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 677;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[677]</span></a></sup> He believed that the working classes would prove successful in this struggle and would establish a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dictatorship_of_the_proletariat" title="Dictatorship of the proletariat" id="mwA3Y">dictatorship of the proletariat</a>,<sup about="#mwt1494" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200493_681-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"93"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200493-681" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 677;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[677]</span></a></sup> regarding the Soviet Union as an example of such a state.<sup about="#mwt1495" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999216_682-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"216"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999216-682" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 678;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[678]</span></a></sup> He also believed that this proletarian state would need to introduce repressive measures to ensure the full crushing of the propertied classes,<sup about="#mwt1496" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200493–94_683-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"93–94"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200493–94-683" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 679;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[679]</span></a></sup> and thus the class war would intensify with the advance of socialism.<sup about="#mwt1497" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999214Khlevniuk20158_684-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"1y":{"wt":"1999"},"1p":{"wt":"214"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"8"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999214Khlevniuk20158-684" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 680;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[680]</span></a></sup> The new state would then be able to ensure that all citizens had access to work, food, shelter, healthcare, and education, with the wastefulness of capitalism eliminated by a new, standardised economic system.<sup about="#mwt1498" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200494_685-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"94"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200494-685" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 681;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[681]</span></a></sup> According to Sandle, Stalin was "committed to the creation of a society that was industrialized, collectivized, centrally planned and technologically advanced."<sup about="#mwt1499" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999211_686-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"211"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999211-686" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 682;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[682]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA3c">Stalin adhered to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leninism" title="Leninism" id="mwA3g">Leninist</a> variant of Marxism.<sup about="#mwt1658" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin201410,_699_687-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"pp":{"wt":"10, 699"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin201410,_699-687" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 683;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[683]</span></a></sup> In his book, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./The_Foundations_of_Leninism" title="The Foundations of Leninism" id="mwA3k" class="mw-redirect"><i id="mwA3o">Foundations of Leninism</i></a>, he stated that "Leninism is the Marxism of the epoch of imperialism and of the proletarian revolution".<sup about="#mwt1659" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014545_688-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"545"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014545-688" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 684;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[684]</span></a></sup> He claimed to be a loyal Leninist,<sup about="#mwt1660" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200492_689-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"92"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200492-689" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 685;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[685]</span></a></sup> although was—according to Service—"not a blindly obedient Leninist".<sup about="#mwt1661" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200494_685-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"94"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200494-685" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 681;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[681]</span></a></sup> Stalin respected Lenin, but not uncritically,<sup about="#mwt1662" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007211_690-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"211"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007211-690" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 686;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[686]</span></a></sup> and spoke out when he believed that Lenin was wrong.<sup about="#mwt1663" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200494_685-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"94"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200494-685" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 681;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[681]</span></a></sup> During the period of his revolutionary activity, Stalin regarded some of Lenin's views and actions as being the self-indulgent activities of a spoiled émigré, deeming them counterproductive for those Bolshevik activists based within the Russian Empire itself.<sup about="#mwt1664" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200495Montefiore2007211_691-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"95"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"211"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200495Montefiore2007211-691" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 687;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[687]</span></a></sup> After the October Revolution, they continued to have differences. Whereas Lenin believed that all countries across Europe and Asia would readily unite as a single state following proletariat revolution, Stalin argued that national pride would prevent this, and that different socialist states would have to be formed; in his view, a country like Germany would not readily submit to being part of a Russian-dominated federal state.<sup about="#mwt1665" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004179–180_692-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"179–180"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004179–180-692" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 688;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[688]</span></a></sup> Stalin biographer <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Oleg_Khlevniuk" title="Oleg Khlevniuk" id="mwA3s">Oleg Khlevniuk</a> nevertheless believed that the pair developed a "strong bond" over the years,<sup about="#mwt1666" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201567_693-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"67"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201567-693" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 689;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[689]</span></a></sup> while Kotkin suggested that Stalin's friendship with Lenin was "the single most important relationship in Stalin's life".<sup about="#mwt1667" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014531_694-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"531"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014531-694" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 690;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[690]</span></a></sup> After Lenin's death, Stalin relied heavily on Lenin's writings—far more so than those of Marx and Engels—to guide him in the affairs of state.<sup about="#mwt1668" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201593–94_695-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"93–94"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201593–94-695" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 691;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[691]</span></a></sup> Stalin adopted the Leninist view on the need for a revolutionary <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vanguardism" title="Vanguardism" id="mwA3w">vanguard</a> who could lead the proletariat rather than being led by them.<sup about="#mwt1669" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200493_681-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"93"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200493-681" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 677;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[677]</span></a></sup> Leading this vanguard, he believed that the Soviet peoples needed a strong, central figure—akin to a Tsar—whom they could rally around.<sup about="#mwt1670" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004333Kotkin2014586_696-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"333"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"586"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004333Kotkin2014586-696" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 692;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[692]</span></a></sup> In his words, "the people need a Tsar, whom they can worship and for whom they can live and work".<sup about="#mwt1671" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003158_697-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"158"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003158-697" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 693;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[693]</span></a></sup> He read about, and admired, two Tsars in particular: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ivan_the_Terrible" title="Ivan the Terrible" id="mwA30">Ivan the Terrible</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Peter_the_Great" title="Peter the Great" id="mwA34">Peter the Great</a>.<sup about="#mwt1672" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999256Service2004333Khlevniuk201594_698-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"1y":{"wt":"1999"},"1p":{"wt":"256"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"333"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"94"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999256Service2004333Khlevniuk201594-698" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 694;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[694]</span></a></sup> In the personality cult constructed around him, he was known as the <i id="mwA38"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vozhd" title="Vozhd" id="mwA4A">vozhd</a></i>, an equivalent to the Italian <i id="mwA4E"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Duce" title="Duce" id="mwA4I">duce</a></i> and German <i id="mwA4M"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Fuhrer" title="Fuhrer" id="mwA4Q" class="mw-redirect">fuhrer</a></i>.<sup about="#mwt1673" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin20177_699-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2017"},"p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin20177-699" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 695;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[695]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA4U"><a href="./File:Grutas_Stalin.jpg" id="mwA4Y"><img resource="./File:Grutas_Stalin.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Grutas_Stalin.jpg/220px-Grutas_Stalin.jpg" data-file-width="2560" data-file-height="1920" data-file-type="bitmap" height="165" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Grutas_Stalin.jpg/440px-Grutas_Stalin.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c2/Grutas_Stalin.jpg/330px-Grutas_Stalin.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA4c"/></a><figcaption id="mwA4g">A statue of Stalin in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Grūtas_Park" title="Grūtas Park" id="mwA4k">Grūtas Park</a>; it originally stood in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vilnius" title="Vilnius" id="mwA4o">Vilnius</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lithuania" title="Lithuania" id="mwA4s">Lithuania</a></figcaption></figure>
<p id="mwA4w"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stalinism" title="Stalinism" id="mwA40">Stalinism</a> was a development of Leninism,<sup about="#mwt2100" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007352_700-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"352"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007352-700" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 696;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[696]</span></a></sup> and while Stalin avoided using the term "Marxism-Leninism-Stalinism", he allowed others to do so.<sup about="#mwt2101" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004357_701-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"357"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004357-701" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 697;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[697]</span></a></sup> Following Lenin's death, Stalin contributed to the theoretical debates within the Communist Party, namely by developing the idea of "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Socialism_in_One_Country" title="Socialism in One Country" id="mwA44">Socialism in One Country</a>". This concept was intricately linked to factional struggles within the party, particularly against Trotsky.<sup about="#mwt2102" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999208–209_702-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"pp":{"wt":"208–209"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999208–209-702" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 698;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[698]</span></a></sup> He first developed the idea in December 1924 and elaborated upon in his writings of 1925–26.<sup about="#mwt2103" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999209_703-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"209"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999209-703" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 699;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[699]</span></a></sup> Stalin's doctrine held that socialism could be completed in Russia but that its final victory there could not be guaranteed because of the threat from capitalist intervention. For this reason, he retained the Leninist view that world revolution was still a necessity to ensure the ultimate victory of socialism.<sup about="#mwt2104" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999209_703-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"209"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999209-703" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 699;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[699]</span></a></sup> Although retaining the Marxist belief that the state would wither away as socialism transformed into pure communism, he believed that the Soviet state would remain until the final defeat of international capitalism.<sup about="#mwt2105" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999261_704-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"261"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999261-704" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 700;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[700]</span></a></sup> This concept synthesised Marxist and Leninist ideas with nationalist ideals,<sup about="#mwt2106" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999211_686-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"211"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999211-686" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 682;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[682]</span></a></sup> and served to discredit Trotsky—who promoted the idea of "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Permanent_revolution" title="Permanent revolution" id="mwA48">permanent revolution</a>"—by presenting the latter as a defeatist with little faith in Russian workers' abilities to construct socialism.<sup about="#mwt2107" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999210_705-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"p":{"wt":"210"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999210-705" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 701;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[701]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA5A">Stalin viewed nations as contingent entities which were formed by capitalism and could merge into others.<sup about="#mwt2109" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200498_706-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"98"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200498-706" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 702;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[702]</span></a></sup> Ultimately he believed that all nations would merge into a single, global human community,<sup about="#mwt2110" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200498_706-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"98"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200498-706" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 702;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[702]</span></a></sup> and regarded all nations as inherently equal.<sup about="#mwt2111" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEOvery2004552_707-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Overy"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"552"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEOvery2004552-707" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 703;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[703]</span></a></sup> In his work, he stated that "the right of secession" should be offered to the ethnic-minorities of the Russian Empire, but that they should not be encouraged to take that option.<sup about="#mwt2112" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200499_708-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"99"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200499-708" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 704;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[704]</span></a></sup> He was of the view that if they became fully autonomous, then they would end up being controlled by the most reactionary elements of their community; as an example he cited the largely illiterate <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tatar" title="Tatar" id="mwA5E" class="mw-redirect">Tatars</a>, whom he claimed would end up dominated by their <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mullah" title="Mullah" id="mwA5I">mullahs</a>.<sup about="#mwt2113" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200499_708-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"99"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200499-708" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 704;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[704]</span></a></sup> Stalin argued that the Jews possessed a "national character" but were not a "nation" and were thus unassimilable. He argued that Jewish nationalism, particularly <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Zionism" title="Zionism" id="mwA5M">Zionism</a>, was hostile to socialism.<sup about="#mwt2114" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEOvery2004565_709-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Overy"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"565"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEOvery2004565-709" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 705;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[705]</span></a></sup> Khlevniuk therefore argued that Stalin reconciled Marxism with imperialism.<sup about="#mwt2115" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20158_710-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"8"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20158-710" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 706;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[706]</span></a></sup> According to Service, Stalin's Marxism was imbued with a great deal of Russian nationalism.<sup about="#mwt2116" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20049_672-3" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20049-672" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 668;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[668]</span></a></sup> According to Montefiore, Stalin's embrace of the Russian nation was pragmatic, as the Russians were the core of the population of the USSR; it was not a rejection of his Georgian origins.<sup about="#mwt2117" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003310,_579_711-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"pp":{"wt":"310, 579"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003310,_579-711" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 707;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[707]</span></a></sup> Stalin's push for Soviet westward expansion into eastern Europe resulted in accusations of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_imperialism" title="Russian imperialism" id="mwA5Q" class="mw-redirect">Russian imperialism</a>.<sup about="#mwt2118" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20045_712-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20045-712" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 708;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[708]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="33" id="mwA5U"><h2 id="Personal_life_and_characteristics">Personal life and characteristics</h2>
<div class="quotebox pullquote floatright " style="
    width:25em; 
    
;
     
    
    " about="#mwt2125" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Quote box","href":"./Template:Quote_box"},"params":{"width":{"wt":"25em"},"align":{"wt":"right"},"quote":{"wt":"Stalin brutally, artfully, indefatigably built a personal dictatorship within the Bolshevik dictatorship. Then he launched and saw through a bloody socialist remaking of the entire former empire, presided over a victory in the greatest war in human history, and took the Soviet Union to the epicentre of global affairs. More than for any other historical figure, even Gandhi or Churchill, a biography of Stalin... eventually comes to approximate a history of the world."},"source":{"wt":"— Stephen Kotkin{{sfn|Kotkin|2014|p=4}}"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA5Y"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r856303512" about="#mwt3885" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Template:Quote_box/styles.css"}}'/>

<div class="quotebox-quote  left-aligned " style="
    ">Stalin brutally, artfully, indefatigably built a personal dictatorship within the Bolshevik dictatorship. Then he launched and saw through a bloody socialist remaking of the entire former empire, presided over a victory in the greatest war in human history, and took the Soviet Union to the epicentre of global affairs. More than for any other historical figure, even Gandhi or Churchill, a biography of Stalin... eventually comes to approximate a history of the world.</div>
<p><cite class="left-aligned" style="">— Stephen Kotkin<sup about="#mwt3887" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin20144_713-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"FOOTNOTEKotkin20144"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin20144-713"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin20144-713" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 709;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[709]</span></a></sup></cite></p>
</div>

<p id="mwA5c">Ethnically Georgian,<sup about="#mwt2126" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19911_714-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19911-714" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 710;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[710]</span></a></sup> Stalin grew up speaking the Georgian language,<sup about="#mwt2127" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19911Khlevniuk201597_715-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"1"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"97"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19911Khlevniuk201597-715" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 711;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[711]</span></a></sup> and did not begin learning <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Russian_language" title="Russian language" id="mwA5g">Russian</a> until the age of eight or nine.<sup about="#mwt2128" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201597_716-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"97"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201597-716" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 712;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[712]</span></a></sup> He remained proud of his Georgian identity,<sup about="#mwt2129" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200766–67_717-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"66–67"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200766–67-717" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 713;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[713]</span></a></sup> and throughout his life retained a heavy Georgian accent when speaking Russian.<sup about="#mwt2130" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19911Montefiore20032Montefiore200742Khlevniuk201597_718-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"1"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"2"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"42"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"97"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19911Montefiore20032Montefiore200742Khlevniuk201597-718" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 714;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[714]</span></a></sup> According to Montefiore, despite Stalin's affinity for Russia and Russians, he remained profoundly Georgian in his lifestyle and personality.<sup about="#mwt2131" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003579_719-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"579"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003579-719" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 715;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[715]</span></a></sup> Stalin's colleagues described him as "Asiatic", and he told a Japanese journalist that "I am not a European man, but an Asian, a Russified Georgian".<sup about="#mwt2132" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTERieber200518_720-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Rieber"},"2":{"wt":"2005"},"p":{"wt":"18"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTERieber200518-720" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 716;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[716]</span></a></sup> Service also noted that Stalin "would never be Russian", could not credibly pass as one, and never tried to pretend that he was.<sup about="#mwt2133" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200485_721-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"85"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200485-721" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 717;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[717]</span></a></sup> Montefiore was of the view that "after 1917, [Stalin] became quadri-national: Georgian by nationality, Russian by loyalty, internationalist by ideology, Soviet by citizenship."<sup about="#mwt2134" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007268_722-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"268"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007268-722" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 718;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[718]</span></a></sup></p> 

<p id="mwA5k">Stalin had a soft voice,<sup about="#mwt2135" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991183Volkogonov19915Kotkin20175_723-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"183"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"5"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2017"},"3p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991183Volkogonov19915Kotkin20175-723" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 719;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[719]</span></a></sup> and when speaking Russian did so slowly, carefully choosing his phrasing.<sup about="#mwt2136" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19911_714-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19911-714" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 710;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[710]</span></a></sup> In private he used coarse language, although avoided doing so in public.<sup about="#mwt2137" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199137_724-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"37"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199137-724" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 720;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[720]</span></a></sup> Described as a poor orator,<sup about="#mwt2138" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991149Volkogonov199149Service2004334Khlevniuk201552_725-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"149"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"49"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"334"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"52"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991149Volkogonov199149Service2004334Khlevniuk201552-725" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 721;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[721]</span></a></sup> according to Volkogonov, Stalin's speaking style was "simple and clear, without flights of fancy, catchy phrases or platform histrionics".<sup about="#mwt2139" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991xx–xxi_726-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"pp":{"wt":"xx–xxi"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991xx–xxi-726" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 722;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[722]</span></a></sup> He rarely spoke before large audiences, and preferred to express himself in written form.<sup about="#mwt2140" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015329_727-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"329"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015329-727" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 723;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[723]</span></a></sup> His writing style was similar, being characterised by its simplicity, clarity, and conciseness.<sup about="#mwt2141" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199121Khlevniuk201597_728-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"21"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"97"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199121Khlevniuk201597-728" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 724;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[724]</span></a></sup> Throughout his life, he used various nicknames and pseudonyms, including "Koba", "Soselo", and "Ivanov",<sup about="#mwt2142" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007395_729-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"395"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007395-729" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 725;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[725]</span></a></sup> adopting "Stalin" in 1912; it was based on the Russian word for "steel" and has often been translated as "Man of Steel".<sup about="#mwt2143" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269_150-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Himmer"},"2":{"wt":"1986"},"p":{"wt":"269"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHimmer1986269-150" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 146;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[146]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA5o"><a href="./File:Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg" id="mwA5s"><img resource="./File:Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg/220px-Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg" data-file-width="1552" data-file-height="1080" data-file-type="bitmap" height="153" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg/440px-Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fb/Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg/330px-Lavrenti_Beria_Stalins_family.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA5w"/></a><figcaption id="mwA50"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lavrenti_Beria" title="Lavrenti Beria" id="mwA54" class="mw-redirect">Lavrenti Beria</a> with Stalin's daughter, Svetlana, on his lap and Stalin seated in the background. Stalin's <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dacha" title="Dacha" id="mwA58">dacha</a> near <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Sochi" title="Sochi" id="mwA6A">Sochi</a>, mid- 1930s.</figcaption></figure> 
<p id="mwA6E">In adulthood, Stalin measured <span about="#mwt2147" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"convert","href":"./Template:Convert"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"5"},"2":{"wt":"ft"},"3":{"wt":"4"},"4":{"wt":"in"},"5":{"wt":"m"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA6I">5</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt2147"> </span><span about="#mwt2147">feet 4</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt2147"> </span><span about="#mwt2147">inches (1.63</span><span typeof="mw:Entity" about="#mwt2147"> </span><span about="#mwt2147">m)</span> tall.<sup about="#mwt2148" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Volkogonov19915_730-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"12"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199112Volkogonov19915-730" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 726;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[726]</span></a></sup> To appear taller, he wore stacked shoes, and stood on a small platform during parades.<sup about="#mwt2149" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest199112_731-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"12"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest199112-731" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 727;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[727]</span></a></sup> His mustached face was pock-marked from <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Smallpox" title="Smallpox" id="mwA6M">smallpox</a> during childhood; this was airbrushed from published photographs.<sup about="#mwt2150" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin20174_732-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2017"},"p":{"wt":"4"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin20174-732" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 728;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[728]</span></a></sup> He was born with a webbed left foot, and his left arm had been permanently injured in childhood which left it shorter than his right and lacking in flexibility,<sup about="#mwt2151" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200425Khlevniuk201513–14_733-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"25"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"13–14"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200425Khlevniuk201513–14-733" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 729;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[729]</span></a></sup> which was probably the result of being hit, at the age of 12, by a horse-drawn carriage.<sup about="#mwt2152" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200721,_29,_33–34_734-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"21, 29, 33–34"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200721,_29,_33–34-734" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 730;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[730]</span></a></sup> During his youth, Stalin cultivated a scruffy appearance in rejection of middle-class aesthetic values.<sup about="#mwt2153" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200444_735-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"44"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200444-735" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 731;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[731]</span></a></sup> He grew his hair long and often wore a beard; for clothing, he often wore a traditional Georgian <i id="mwA6Q"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Chokha" title="Chokha" id="mwA6U">chokha</a></i> or a red satin shirt with a grey coat and red fedora.<sup about="#mwt2154" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20079–10_736-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"9–10"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20079–10-736" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 732;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[732]</span></a></sup> From mid-1918 until his death he favoured military-style clothing, in particular long black boots, light-coloured collarless tunics, and a gun.<sup about="#mwt2155" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004167Kotkin20171_737-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"167"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2017"},"2p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004167Kotkin20171-737" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 733;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[733]</span></a></sup> He was a lifelong smoker, who smoked both a pipe and cigarettes.<sup about="#mwt2156" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991282Volkogonov1991146Service2004435,_438,_574Kotkin20171_738-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"282"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"146"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3pp":{"wt":"435, 438, 574"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2017"},"4p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991282Volkogonov1991146Service2004435,_438,_574Kotkin20171-738" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 734;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[734]</span></a></sup> He had few material demands and lived plainly, with simple and inexpensive clothing and furniture;<sup about="#mwt2157" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991311Volkogonov1991102Montefiore200336–37Service2004497–498_739-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"311"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"102"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2003"},"3pp":{"wt":"36–37"},"4a1":{"wt":"Service"},"4y":{"wt":"2004"},"4pp":{"wt":"497–498"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991311Volkogonov1991102Montefiore200336–37Service2004497–498-739" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 735;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[735]</span></a></sup> his interest was in power rather than wealth.<sup about="#mwt2158" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991102Service2004498_740-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"102"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"498"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991102Service2004498-740" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 736;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[736]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA6Y">As Soviet leader, Stalin typically awoke around 11<span class="nowrap" about="#mwt2159" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nbsp","href":"./Template:Nbsp"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA6c"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span>am,<sup about="#mwt2160" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200360_741-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"60"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200360-741" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 737;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[737]</span></a></sup> with lunch being served between 3 and 5<span class="nowrap" about="#mwt2161" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nbsp","href":"./Template:Nbsp"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA6g"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span>pm and dinner no earlier than 9<span class="nowrap" about="#mwt2162" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"nbsp","href":"./Template:Nbsp"},"params":{},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA6k"><span typeof="mw:Entity"> </span></span>pm;<sup about="#mwt2163" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200360Service2004525_742-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"60"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"525"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200360Service2004525-742" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 738;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[738]</span></a></sup> he then worked late into the evening.<sup about="#mwt2164" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004525_743-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"525"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004525-743" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 739;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[739]</span></a></sup> He often dined with other Politburo members and their families.<sup about="#mwt2165" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200335,_60_744-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"pp":{"wt":"35, 60"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200335,_60-744" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 740;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[740]</span></a></sup> As leader, he rarely left Moscow unless to go to one of his dachas;<sup about="#mwt2166" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004331_745-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"331"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004331-745" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 741;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[741]</span></a></sup> he disliked travel,<sup about="#mwt2167" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015102,_227_746-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"102, 227"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015102,_227-746" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 742;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[742]</span></a></sup> and refused to travel by plane.<sup about="#mwt2168" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015195Kotkin20173_747-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"1y":{"wt":"2015"},"1p":{"wt":"195"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2017"},"2p":{"wt":"3"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015195Kotkin20173-747" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 743;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[743]</span></a></sup> His choice of favoured holiday house changed over the years,<sup about="#mwt2169" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200364_748-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"64"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200364-748" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 744;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[744]</span></a></sup> although he holidayed in southern parts of the USSR every year from 1925 to 1936 and again from 1945 to 1951.<sup about="#mwt2170" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015191_749-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"191"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015191-749" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 745;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[745]</span></a></sup> Along with other senior figures, he had a dacha at Zubalova, 35km outside Moscow,<sup about="#mwt2171" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200357–58Kotkin2014594_750-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1pp":{"wt":"57–58"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"594"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200357–58Kotkin2014594-750" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 746;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[746]</span></a></sup> although ceased using it after Nadya's 1932 suicide.<sup about="#mwt2172" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003102_751-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"102"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003102-751" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 747;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[747]</span></a></sup> After 1932, he favoured holidays in Abkhazia, being a friend of its leader, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nestor_Lakoba" title="Nestor Lakoba" id="mwA6o">Nestor Lakoba</a>.<sup about="#mwt2173" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200366–67Service2004296_752-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1pp":{"wt":"66–67"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"296"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200366–67Service2004296-752" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 748;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[748]</span></a></sup> In 1934, his new <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kuntsevo_Dacha" title="Kuntsevo Dacha" id="mwA6s">Kuntsevo Dacha</a> was built; 9km from the Kremlin, it became his primary residence.<sup about="#mwt2174" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991215Montefiore2003103Service2004295_753-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"215"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"103"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"295"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991215Montefiore2003103Service2004295-753" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 749;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[749]</span></a></sup> In 1935 he began using a new dacha provided for him by Lakoba at <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Novy_Afon" title="Novy Afon" id="mwA6w" class="mw-redirect">Novy Afon</a>;<sup about="#mwt2175" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003178_754-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"178"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003178-754" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 750;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[750]</span></a></sup> in 1936, he had the Kholodnaya Rechka dacha built on the Abkhazian coast, designed by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Miron_Merzhanov" title="Miron Merzhanov" id="mwA60">Miron Merzhanov</a>.<sup about="#mwt2176" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004572_755-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"572"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004572-755" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 751;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[751]</span></a></sup></p>

<section data-mw-section-id="34" id="mwA64"><h3 id="Personality">Personality</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA68"><a href="./File:Stalin_birthday2.jpg" id="mwA7A"><img resource="./File:Stalin_birthday2.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Stalin_birthday2.jpg/220px-Stalin_birthday2.jpg" data-file-width="700" data-file-height="557" data-file-type="bitmap" height="175" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Stalin_birthday2.jpg/440px-Stalin_birthday2.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cb/Stalin_birthday2.jpg/330px-Stalin_birthday2.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA7E"/></a><figcaption id="mwA7I">Chinese Marxists celebrate Stalin's seventieth birthday in 1949</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwA7M">Trotsky and several other Soviet figures promoted the idea that Stalin was a mediocrity.<sup about="#mwt2177" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xviVolkogonov1991xxiiiService20044Montefiore2007xxiv_756-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"xvi"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"xxiii"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"4"},"4a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"4y":{"wt":"2007"},"4p":{"wt":"xxiv"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xviVolkogonov1991xxiiiService20044Montefiore2007xxiv-756" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 752;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[752]</span></a></sup> This gained widespread acceptance outside the Soviet Union during his lifetime but was misleading.<sup about="#mwt2178" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007xxiv_757-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"xxiv"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007xxiv-757" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 753;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[753]</span></a></sup> According to Montefiore, "it is clear from hostile and friendly witnesses alike that Stalin was always exceptional, even from childhood".<sup about="#mwt2179" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007xxiv_757-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"xxiv"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007xxiv-757" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 753;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[753]</span></a></sup> Stalin had a complex mind,<sup about="#mwt2180" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004343_758-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"343"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004343-758" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 754;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[754]</span></a></sup> great self-control,<sup about="#mwt2181" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19918Service2004337_759-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"8"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"337"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19918Service2004337-759" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 755;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[755]</span></a></sup> and an excellent memory.<sup about="#mwt2182" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991193,_274Volkogonov199163Service2004115Kotkin2014425Khlevniuk2015148_760-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"193, 274"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"63"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"115"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"425"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"148"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991193,_274Volkogonov199163Service2004115Kotkin2014425Khlevniuk2015148-760" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 756;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[756]</span></a></sup> He was a hard worker,<sup about="#mwt2183" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200442Montefiore2007353Kotkin2014424,_465,_597_761-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"42"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"353"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"424, 465, 597"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200442Montefiore2007353Kotkin2014424,_465,_597-761" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 757;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[757]</span></a></sup> and displayed a keen desire to learn;<sup about="#mwt2184" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004115_762-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"115"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004115-762" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 758;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[758]</span></a></sup> when in power, he scrutinised many details of Soviet life, from film scripts to architectural plans and military hardware.<sup about="#mwt2185" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20154–5_763-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"4–5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20154–5-763" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 759;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[759]</span></a></sup> According to Volkogonov, "Stalin's private life and working life were one and the same"; he did not take days off from political activities.<sup about="#mwt2186" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991145_764-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"145"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991145-764" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 760;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[760]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA7Q">Stalin could play different roles to different audiences,<sup about="#mwt2187" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991317Volkogonov1991xxviMcDermott200613_765-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"317"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"xxvi"},"3a1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"3y":{"wt":"2006"},"3p":{"wt":"13"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991317Volkogonov1991xxviMcDermott200613-765" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 761;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[761]</span></a></sup> and was adept at deception, often deceiving others as to his true motives and aims.<sup about="#mwt2188" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xviService200418McDermott200613_766-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"xvi"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"18"},"3a1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"3y":{"wt":"2006"},"3p":{"wt":"13"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xviService200418McDermott200613-766" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 762;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[762]</span></a></sup> Several historians have seen it appropriate to follow <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lazar_Kaganovich" title="Lazar Kaganovich" id="mwA7U">Lazar Kaganovich</a>'s description of there being "several Stalins" as a means of understanding his multi-faceted personality.<sup about="#mwt2189" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott200612–13_767-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"pp":{"wt":"12–13"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott200612–13-767" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 763;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[763]</span></a></sup> He was a good organiser,<sup about="#mwt2190" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200342Kotkin2014424_768-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"42"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"424"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200342Kotkin2014424-768" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 764;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[764]</span></a></sup> with a strategic mind,<sup about="#mwt2191" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014424_769-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"424"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014424-769" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 765;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[765]</span></a></sup> and judged others according to their inner strength, practicality, and cleverness.<sup about="#mwt2192" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004342_770-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"342"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004342-770" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 766;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[766]</span></a></sup> He acknowledged that he could be rude and insulting,<sup about="#mwt2193" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991120Kotkin2014648_771-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"120"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"648"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991120Kotkin2014648-771" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 767;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[767]</span></a></sup> although rarely raised his voice in anger;<sup about="#mwt2194" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004337_772-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"337"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004337-772" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 768;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[768]</span></a></sup> as his health deteriorated in later life he became increasingly unpredictable and bad tempered.<sup about="#mwt2195" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015145_773-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"145"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015145-773" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 769;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[769]</span></a></sup> Despite his tough-talking attitude, he could be very charming;<sup about="#mwt2196" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200392Montefiore200349–50Kotkin2014117,_465Kotkin20175_774-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"McCauley"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"92"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2pp":{"wt":"49–50"},"3a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"3y":{"wt":"2014"},"3pp":{"wt":"117, 465"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2017"},"4p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200392Montefiore200349–50Kotkin2014117,_465Kotkin20175-774" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 770;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[770]</span></a></sup> when relaxed, he cracked jokes and mimicked others.<sup about="#mwt2197" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004115_762-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"115"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004115-762" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 758;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[758]</span></a></sup> Montefiore suggested that this charm was "the foundation of Stalin's power in the Party".<sup about="#mwt2198" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200341_775-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"41"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200341-775" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 771;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[771]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA7Y">Stalin was ruthless,<sup about="#mwt2199" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004338Khlevniuk201553_776-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"338"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"53"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004338Khlevniuk201553-776" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 772;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[772]</span></a></sup> temperamentally cruel,<sup about="#mwt2200" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991318Khlevniuk20157_777-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"318"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991318Khlevniuk20157-777" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 773;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[773]</span></a></sup> and had a propensity for violence high even among the Bolsheviks.<sup about="#mwt2201" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004337_772-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"337"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004337-772" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 768;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[768]</span></a></sup> He lacked compassion,<sup about="#mwt2202" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19914Khlevniuk20157_778-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"4"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19914Khlevniuk20157-778" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 774;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[774]</span></a></sup> something Volkogonov suggested might have been accentuated by his many years in prison and exile,<sup about="#mwt2203" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19918_779-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"8"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19918-779" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 775;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[775]</span></a></sup> although he was capable of acts of kindness to strangers, even amid the Great Terror.<sup about="#mwt2204" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004334_780-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"334"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004334-780" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 776;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[776]</span></a></sup> He was capable of self-righteous indignation,<sup about="#mwt2205" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004258Montefiore2007285_781-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"258"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"285"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004258Montefiore2007285-781" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 777;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[777]</span></a></sup> and was resentful,<sup about="#mwt2206" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20044,_344_782-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"4, 344"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20044,_344-782" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 778;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[778]</span></a></sup> vindictive,<sup about="#mwt2207" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014597Kotkin20176_783-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"1y":{"wt":"2014"},"1p":{"wt":"597"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2017"},"2p":{"wt":"6"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014597Kotkin20176-783" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 779;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[779]</span></a></sup> and vengeful, holding onto grievances against others for many years.<sup about="#mwt2208" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200410,_344Kotkin20175_784-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"10, 344"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2017"},"2p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200410,_344Kotkin20175-784" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 780;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[780]</span></a></sup> By the 1920s, he was also suspicious and conspiratorial, prone to believing that people were plotting against him and that there were vast international conspiracies behind acts of dissent.<sup about="#mwt2209" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004336Kotkin2014736_785-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"336"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"736"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004336Kotkin2014736-785" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 781;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[781]</span></a></sup> He never attended torture sessions or executions,<sup about="#mwt2210" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003175_786-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"175"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003175-786" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 782;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[782]</span></a></sup> although Service thought Stalin "derived deep satisfaction" from degrading and humiliating people and keeping even close associates in a state of "unrelieved fear".<sup about="#mwt2211" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20045_712-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20045-712" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 708;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[708]</span></a></sup> Montefiore thought Stalin's brutality marked him out as a "natural extremist";<sup about="#mwt2212" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200742_787-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"42"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200742-787" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 783;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[783]</span></a></sup> Service suggested he had a paranoid or sociopathic personality disorder.<sup about="#mwt2213" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004343_758-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"343"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004343-758" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 754;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[754]</span></a></sup> Other historians linked his brutality not to any personality trait, but to his unwavering commitment to the survival of the Soviet Union and the international Marxist-Leninist cause.<sup about="#mwt2214" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott200612_788-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"12"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott200612-788" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 784;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[784]</span></a></sup></p>

<div class="quotebox pullquote floatleft " style="
    width:25em; 
    
;
     
    
    " about="#mwt2215" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"Quote box","href":"./Template:Quote_box"},"params":{"width":{"wt":"25em"},"align":{"wt":"left"},"quote":{"wt":"It is hard for me to reconcile the courtesy and consideration he showed me personally with the ghastly cruelty of his wholesale liquidations.  Others, who did not know him personally, see only the tyrant in Stalin. I saw the other side as well – his high intelligence, that fantastic grasp of detail, his shrewdness and his surprising human sensitivity that he was capable of showing, at least in the war years. I found him better informed than Roosevelt, more realistic than Churchill, in some ways the most effective of the war leaders... I must confess that for me Stalin remains the most inscrutable and contradictory character I have known – and leave the final word to the judgment of history."},"source":{"wt":"— U.S. ambassador [[W. Averell Harriman]]{{sfn|Leffler|2007|pp=55–56}}"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA7c"><link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r856303512" about="#mwt4265" typeof="mw:Extension/templatestyles" data-mw='{"name":"templatestyles","attrs":{"src":"Template:Quote_box/styles.css"}}'/>

<div class="quotebox-quote  left-aligned " style="
    ">It is hard for me to reconcile the courtesy and consideration he showed me personally with the ghastly cruelty of his wholesale liquidations.  Others, who did not know him personally, see only the tyrant in Stalin. I saw the other side as well – his high intelligence, that fantastic grasp of detail, his shrewdness and his surprising human sensitivity that he was capable of showing, at least in the war years. I found him better informed than Roosevelt, more realistic than Churchill, in some ways the most effective of the war leaders... I must confess that for me Stalin remains the most inscrutable and contradictory character I have known – and leave the final word to the judgment of history.</div>
<p><cite class="left-aligned" style="">— U.S. ambassador <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./W._Averell_Harriman" title="W. Averell Harriman">W. Averell Harriman</a><sup about="#mwt4281" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTELeffler200755–56_789-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"FOOTNOTELeffler200755–56"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-FOOTNOTELeffler200755–56-789"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTELeffler200755–56-789" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 785;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[785]</span></a></sup></cite></p>
</div>

<p id="mwA7g">Keenly interested in the arts,<sup about="#mwt2216" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014620_790-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"620"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014620-790" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 786;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[786]</span></a></sup> Stalin admired artistic talent.<sup about="#mwt2217" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200760_791-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"60"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200760-791" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 787;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[787]</span></a></sup> He protected several Soviet writers, such as <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mikhail_Bulgakov" title="Mikhail Bulgakov" id="mwA7k">Mikhail Bulgakov</a>, even when their work was labelled harmful to his regime.<sup about="#mwt2218" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201596_792-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"96"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201596-792" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 788;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[788]</span></a></sup> He enjoyed music,<sup about="#mwt2219" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200373Khlevniuk20156_793-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"73"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"6"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200373Khlevniuk20156-793" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 789;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[789]</span></a></sup> owning around 2,700 albums,<sup about="#mwt2220" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20156_794-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"6"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20156-794" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 790;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[790]</span></a></sup> and frequently attending the Bolshoi Theatre during the 1930s and 1940s.<sup about="#mwt2221" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991127,_148_795-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"pp":{"wt":"127, 148"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991127,_148-795" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 791;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[791]</span></a></sup> His taste in music and theatre was conservative, favouring classical drama, opera, and ballet over what he dismissed as experimental "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Formalism_(art)" title="Formalism (art)" id="mwA7o">formalism</a>".<sup about="#mwt2222" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201597_716-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"97"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201597-716" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 712;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[712]</span></a></sup> He also favoured classical forms in the visual arts, disliking avant-garde styles like <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Cubism" title="Cubism" id="mwA7s">cubism</a> and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Futurism" title="Futurism" id="mwA7w">futurism</a>.<sup about="#mwt2223" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991131_796-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"131"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991131-796" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 792;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[792]</span></a></sup> He was a voracious reader, with a library of over 20,000 books.<sup about="#mwt2224" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200386Service20049McDermott200619Kotkin20171–2,_5_797-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"86"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"9"},"3a1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"3y":{"wt":"2006"},"3p":{"wt":"19"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2017"},"4pp":{"wt":"1–2, 5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200386Service20049McDermott200619Kotkin20171–2,_5-797" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 793;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[793]</span></a></sup> Little of this was fiction,<sup about="#mwt2225" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201593_798-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"93"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk201593-798" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 794;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[794]</span></a></sup> although he could cite passages from <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Alexander_Pushkin" title="Alexander Pushkin" id="mwA70">Alexander Pushkin</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nikolay_Nekrasov" title="Nikolay Nekrasov" id="mwA74">Nikolay Nekrasov</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Walt_Whitman" title="Walt Whitman" id="mwA78">Walt Whitman</a> by heart.<sup about="#mwt2226" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200760_791-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"60"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200760-791" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 787;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[787]</span></a></sup> He favoured historical studies, keeping up with debates in the study of Russian, Mesopotamian, ancient Roman, and Byzantine history.<sup about="#mwt2227" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004560_641-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"560"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004560-641" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 637;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[637]</span></a></sup> An <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Autodidacticism" title="Autodidacticism" id="mwA8A">autodidact</a>,<sup about="#mwt2228" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200386Kotkin2014117,_676_799-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"86"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2014"},"2p":{"wt":"117, 676"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200386Kotkin2014117,_676-799" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 795;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[795]</span></a></sup> he claimed to read as many as 500 pages a day,<sup about="#mwt2229" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200393Montefiore200386Service2004560McDermott200619_800-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"McCauley"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"93"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"86"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"560"},"4a1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"4y":{"wt":"2006"},"4p":{"wt":"19"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200393Montefiore200386Service2004560McDermott200619-800" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 796;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[796]</span></a></sup> with Montefiore regarding him as an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Intellectual" title="Intellectual" id="mwA8E">intellectual</a>.<sup about="#mwt2230" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200386_801-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"86"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200386-801" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 797;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[797]</span></a></sup> Stalin also enjoyed watching films late at night at cinemas installed in the Kremlin and his dachas.<sup about="#mwt2231" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991127Khlevniuk20152–3_802-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"127"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2pp":{"wt":"2–3"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991127Khlevniuk20152–3-802" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 798;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[798]</span></a></sup> He favoured the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Western_(genre)" title="Western (genre)" id="mwA8I">Western</a> genre;<sup about="#mwt2232" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991282McCauley200390_803-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"282"},"2a1":{"wt":"McCauley"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"90"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991282McCauley200390-803" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 799;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[799]</span></a></sup> his favourite film was the 1938 picture <i id="mwA8M"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Volga-Volga" title="Volga-Volga" id="mwA8Q">Volga Volga</a></i>.<sup about="#mwt2233" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003145_804-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"145"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003145-804" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 800;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[800]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA8U">Stalin was a keen and accomplished <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Billiards" title="Billiards" id="mwA8Y" class="mw-redirect">billiards</a> player,<sup about="#mwt2234" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200358,_507Kotkin20171_805-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1pp":{"wt":"58, 507"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2y":{"wt":"2017"},"2p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200358,_507Kotkin20171-805" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 801;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[801]</span></a></sup> and collected watches.<sup about="#mwt2235" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin20171_806-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2017"},"p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin20171-806" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 802;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[802]</span></a></sup> He also enjoyed practical jokes; he for instance would place a tomato on the seat of Politburo members and wait for them to sit on it.<sup about="#mwt2236" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991283Service2004437_807-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"283"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"437"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991283Service2004437-807" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 803;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[803]</span></a></sup> When at social events, he encouraged singing,<sup about="#mwt2237" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004522_808-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"522"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004522-808" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 804;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[804]</span></a></sup> as well as alcohol consumption; he hoped that others would drunkenly reveal their secrets to him.<sup about="#mwt2238" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200390Service2004437,_522–523Khlevniuk20155_809-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"McCauley"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"90"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2pp":{"wt":"437, 522–523"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200390Service2004437,_522–523Khlevniuk20155-809" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 805;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[805]</span></a></sup> As an infant, Stalin displayed a love of flowers,<sup about="#mwt2239" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200724_810-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"24"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200724-810" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 806;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[806]</span></a></sup> and later in life he became a keen gardener.<sup about="#mwt2240" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200724_810-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"24"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200724-810" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 806;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[806]</span></a></sup> His Volynskoe suburb had a 50-acre park, with Stalin devoting much attention to its agricultural activities.<sup about="#mwt2241" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20153–4_811-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"3–4"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk20153–4-811" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 807;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[807]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA8c">Stalin publicly condemned anti-Semitism,<sup about="#mwt2242" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007319,_637_812-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"319, 637"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007319,_637-812" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 808;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[808]</span></a></sup> although <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stalin_and_antisemitism" title="Stalin and antisemitism" id="mwA8g">was repeatedly accused of it</a>.<sup about="#mwt2243" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200455_813-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"55"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200455-813" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 809;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[809]</span></a></sup> People who knew him, such as Khrushchev, suggested he long harbored negative sentiments toward Jews,<sup about="#mwt2244" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEtinger1995103Montefiore2007165_814-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Etinger"},"1y":{"wt":"1995"},"1p":{"wt":"103"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"165"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEtinger1995103Montefiore2007165-814" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 810;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[810]</span></a></sup> and anti-Semitic trends in his policies were further fueled by Stalin's struggle against Trotsky.<sup about="#mwt2245" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEtinger1995103Rappaport1999297_815-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Etinger"},"1y":{"wt":"1995"},"1p":{"wt":"103"},"2a1":{"wt":"Rappaport"},"2y":{"wt":"1999"},"2p":{"wt":"297"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEtinger1995103Rappaport1999297-815" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 811;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[811]</span></a></sup> After Stalin's death, Khrushchev claimed that Stalin encouraged him to incite anti-Semitism in Ukraine, allegedly telling him that "the good workers at the factory should be given clubs so they can beat the hell out of those Jews."<sup about="#mwt2246" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPinkus1984107–108Brackman2001390_816-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Pinkus"},"1y":{"wt":"1984"},"1pp":{"wt":"107–108"},"2a1":{"wt":"Brackman"},"2y":{"wt":"2001"},"2p":{"wt":"390"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPinkus1984107–108Brackman2001390-816" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 812;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[812]</span></a></sup> In 1946, Stalin allegedly said privately that "every Jew is a potential spy."<sup about="#mwt2247" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBrentNaumov2004184_817-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Brent"},"2":{"wt":"Naumov"},"3":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"184"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBrentNaumov2004184-817" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 813;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[813]</span></a></sup> Conquest stated that although Stalin had Jewish associates, he promoted anti-Semitism.<sup about="#mwt2248" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest19918_818-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"8"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest19918-818" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 814;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[814]</span></a></sup> Service cautioned that there was "no irrefutable evidence" of anti-Semitism in Stalin's published work, although his private statements and public actions were "undeniably reminiscent of crude antagonism towards Jews";<sup about="#mwt2249" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004567–568_819-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"567–568"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004567–568-819" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 815;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[815]</span></a></sup> he added that throughout Stalin's lifetime, the Georgian "would be the friend, associate or leader of countless individual Jews".<sup about="#mwt2250" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200477_820-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"77"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200477-820" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 816;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[816]</span></a></sup> According to Beria, Stalin had affairs with several Jewish women.<sup about="#mwt2251" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003237_821-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"237"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003237-821" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 817;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[817]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="35" id="mwA8k"><h3 id="Relationships_and_family">Relationships and family</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA8o"><a href="./File:Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana,_1935.jpg" id="mwA8s"><img resource="./File:Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana,_1935.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/79/Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana%2C_1935.jpg/220px-Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana%2C_1935.jpg" data-file-width="1500" data-file-height="1171" data-file-type="bitmap" height="172" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/79/Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana%2C_1935.jpg/440px-Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana%2C_1935.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/79/Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana%2C_1935.jpg/330px-Joseph_Stalin_with_daughter_Svetlana%2C_1935.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA8w"/></a><figcaption id="mwA80">Stalin carrying his daughter, Svetlana</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwA84">Friendship was important to Stalin,<sup about="#mwt2252" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200749Fitzpatrick201565_822-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2007"},"1p":{"wt":"49"},"2a1":{"wt":"Fitzpatrick"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"65"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200749Fitzpatrick201565-822" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 818;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[818]</span></a></sup> and he used it to gain and maintain power.<sup about="#mwt2253" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200749_823-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"49"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200749-823" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 819;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[819]</span></a></sup> Kotkin observed that Stalin "generally gravitated to people like himself: parvenu intelligentsia of humble background".<sup about="#mwt2254" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin20149_824-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin20149-824" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 820;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[820]</span></a></sup> He gave nicknames to his favourites, for instance referring to Yezhov as "my blackberry".<sup about="#mwt2255" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003151_825-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"151"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003151-825" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 821;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[821]</span></a></sup> Stalin was sociable and enjoyed a joke.<sup about="#mwt2256" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004112_826-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"112"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004112-826" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 822;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[822]</span></a></sup> According to Montefiore, Stalin's friendships "meandered between love, admiration, and venomous jealousy".<sup about="#mwt2257" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003135_827-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"135"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003135-827" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 823;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[823]</span></a></sup> While head of the Soviet Union he remained in contact with many of his old friends in Georgia, sending them letters and gifts of money.<sup about="#mwt2258" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004522Montefiore2003135Montefiore2007368_828-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"522"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"135"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"368"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004522Montefiore2003135Montefiore2007368-828" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 824;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[824]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA88">Stalin was attracted to women and there are no reports of any homosexual tendencies;<sup about="#mwt2259" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200390_829-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McCauley"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"90"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200390-829" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 825;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[825]</span></a></sup> according to Montefiore, in his early life Stalin "rarely seems to have been without a girlfriend".<sup about="#mwt2260" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200773_54-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"73"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200773-54" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 50;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[50]</span></a></sup> He was sexually promiscuous, although rarely talked about his sex life.<sup about="#mwt2261" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007209_830-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"209"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007209-830" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 826;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[826]</span></a></sup> Montefiore noted that Stalin's favoured types were "young, malleable teenagers or buxom peasant women",<sup about="#mwt2262" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007209_830-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"209"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007209-830" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 826;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[826]</span></a></sup> who would be supportive and unchallenging toward him.<sup about="#mwt2263" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200480Montefiore2007209_831-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"80"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"209"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200480Montefiore2007209-831" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 827;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[827]</span></a></sup> According to Service, Stalin "regarded women as a resource for sexual gratification and domestic comfort".<sup about="#mwt2264" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200480_832-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"80"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200480-832" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 828;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[828]</span></a></sup> Stalin married twice and had several offspring.<sup about="#mwt2265" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200390_829-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McCauley"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"90"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcCauley200390-829" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 825;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[825]</span></a></sup> He married his first wife, Ekaterina Svanidze, in 1906. According to Montefiore, theirs was "a true love match";<sup about="#mwt2266" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20075_833-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20075-833" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 829;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[829]</span></a></sup> Volkogonov suggested that she was "probably the one human being he had really loved".<sup about="#mwt2267" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19914_834-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"4"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov19914-834" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 830;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[830]</span></a></sup> They had a son, Yakov, who often frustrated and annoyed Stalin.<sup about="#mwt2268" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991149Service200464Montefiore2007167Khlevniuk201525_835-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"149"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"64"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"167"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"25"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991149Service200464Montefiore2007167Khlevniuk201525-835" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 831;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[831]</span></a></sup> Yakov had a daughter, Galina, before fighting for the Red Army in the Second World War. He was captured by the German Army and then committed suicide.<sup about="#mwt2269" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991150–151Montefiore2007364_836-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1pp":{"wt":"150–151"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"364"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991150–151Montefiore2007364-836" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 832;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[832]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA9A">Stalin's second wife was <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Nadezhda_Alliluyeva-Stalina" title="Nadezhda Alliluyeva-Stalina" id="mwA9E" class="mw-redirect">Nadezhda Alliluyeva</a>; theirs was not an easy relationship, and they often rowed.<sup about="#mwt2271" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20035_837-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20035-837" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 833;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[833]</span></a></sup> They had two biological children—a son, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vasily_Dzhugashvili" title="Vasily Dzhugashvili" id="mwA9I" class="mw-redirect">Vasily</a>, and a daughter, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Svetlana_Alliluyeva" title="Svetlana Alliluyeva" id="mwA9M">Svetlana</a>—and adopted another son, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Artyom_Sergeyev_(general)" title="Artyom Sergeyev (general)" id="mwA9Q">Artyom Sergeev</a>, in 1921.<sup about="#mwt2272" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20039_838-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20039-838" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 834;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[834]</span></a></sup> During his marriage to Nadezhda, Stalin had affairs with many other women, most of whom were fellow revolutionaries or their wives.<sup about="#mwt2273" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200313Khlevniuk2015255_839-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"13"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"255"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200313Khlevniuk2015255-839" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 835;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[835]</span></a></sup> Nadezdha suspected that this was the case,<sup about="#mwt2274" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200312_840-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"12"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore200312-840" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 836;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[836]</span></a></sup> and committed suicide in 1932.<sup about="#mwt2275" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991154Montefiore200316Khlevniuk2015255_841-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"154"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2003"},"2p":{"wt":"16"},"3a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"3y":{"wt":"2015"},"3p":{"wt":"255"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991154Montefiore200316Khlevniuk2015255-841" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 837;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[837]</span></a></sup> Stalin regarded Vasily as spoiled and often chastised his behaviour; as Stalin's son, Vasily nevertheless was swiftly promoted through the ranks of the Red Army and allowed a lavish lifestyle.<sup about="#mwt2276" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015257,_259–260_842-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"257, 259–260"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015257,_259–260-842" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 838;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[838]</span></a></sup> Conversely, Stalin had an affectionate relationship with Svetlana during her childhood,<sup about="#mwt2277" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991215Volkogonov1991153Montefiore20039,_227Khlevniuk2015256_843-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"215"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"153"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2003"},"3pp":{"wt":"9, 227"},"4a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"4y":{"wt":"2015"},"4p":{"wt":"256"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991215Volkogonov1991153Montefiore20039,_227Khlevniuk2015256-843" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 839;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[839]</span></a></sup> and was also very fond of Artyom.<sup about="#mwt2278" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20039_838-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore20039-838" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 834;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[834]</span></a></sup> In later life, he disapproved of Svetlana's various suitors and husbands, putting a strain on his relationship with her.<sup about="#mwt2279" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991260Service2004521_844-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"260"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"521"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991260Service2004521-844" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 840;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[840]</span></a></sup> After the Second World War he made little time for his children and his family played a decreasingly important role in his life.<sup about="#mwt2280" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015250,_259_845-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"pp":{"wt":"250, 259"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015250,_259-845" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 841;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[841]</span></a></sup> After Stalin's death, Svetlana changed her surname from Stalin to Allilueva,<sup about="#mwt2281" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004593_668-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"593"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004593-668" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 664;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[664]</span></a></sup> and defected to the U.S.<sup about="#mwt2282" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015260_846-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"260"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015260-846" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 842;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[842]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA9U">After Nadezdha's death, Stalin became increasingly close to his sister-in-law Zhenya Alliluyeva;<sup about="#mwt2283" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003142–144_847-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"pp":{"wt":"142–144"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003142–144-847" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 843;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[843]</span></a></sup> Montefiore believed that they were probably lovers.<sup about="#mwt2284" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003144_848-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"144"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003144-848" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 844;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[844]</span></a></sup> There are unproven rumours that from 1934 onward he had a relationship with his housekeeper Valentina Istomina.<sup about="#mwt2285" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004521_849-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"521"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004521-849" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 845;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[845]</span></a></sup> Stalin had at least two illegitimate children,<sup about="#mwt2286" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007365_850-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"365"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007365-850" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 846;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[846]</span></a></sup> although he never recognised them as being his.<sup about="#mwt2287" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015252_851-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"252"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015252-851" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 847;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[847]</span></a></sup> One of them, Constantin Kuzakova, later taught philosophy at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leningrad_Military_Mechanical_Institute" title="Leningrad Military Mechanical Institute" id="mwA9Y" class="new">Leningrad Military Mechanical Institute</a>, but never met his father.<sup about="#mwt2288" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007365–366_852-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"pp":{"wt":"365–366"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007365–366-852" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 848;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[848]</span></a></sup> The other, Alexander, was the son of Lidia Pereprygia; he was raised as the son of a peasant fisherman and the Soviet authorities made him swear never to reveal that Stalin was his biological father.<sup about="#mwt2289" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007366_853-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"366"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007366-853" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 849;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[849]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="36" id="mwA9c"><h2 id="Legacy">Legacy</h2>
<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA9g"><a href="./File:A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin,_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg" id="mwA9k"><img resource="./File:A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin,_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin%2C_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg/220px-A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin%2C_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg" data-file-width="1772" data-file-height="1974" data-file-type="bitmap" height="245" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin%2C_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg/440px-A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin%2C_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9a/A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin%2C_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg/330px-A_German_civilian_looks_at_a_large_poster_portrait_of_Stalin_on_the_Unter-den-Linden_in_Berlin%2C_3_June_1945._BU8572.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA9o"/></a><figcaption id="mwA9s">A poster of Stalin on the Unter-den-Linden in Berlin in 1945</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwA9w">The historian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Robert_Conquest" title="Robert Conquest" id="mwA90">Robert Conquest</a> stated that Stalin, "perhaps[…] determined the course of the twentieth century" more than any other individual.<sup about="#mwt2292" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xi_854-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"xi"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xi-854" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 850;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[850]</span></a></sup> Biographers like Service and Volkogonov have considered him an outstanding and exceptional politician;<sup about="#mwt2293" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991108Service20045_855-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"108"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991108Service20045-855" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 851;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[851]</span></a></sup> Montefiore labelled Stalin as "that rare combination: both 'intellectual' and killer", a man who was "the ultimate politician" and "the most elusive and fascinating of the twentieth-century titans".<sup about="#mwt2294" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007xxii_856-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2007"},"p":{"wt":"xxii"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2007xxii-856" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 852;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[852]</span></a></sup> According to historian Kevin McDermott, interpretations of Stalin range from "the sycophantic and adulatory to the vitriolic and condemnatory".<sup about="#mwt2295" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20061_857-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20061-857" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 853;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[853]</span></a></sup> For most Westerners and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anti-communism" title="Anti-communism" id="mwA94">anti-communist</a> Russians, he is viewed overwhelmingly negatively as a mass murderer;<sup about="#mwt2296" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20061_857-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20061-857" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 853;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[853]</span></a></sup> for significant numbers of Russians and Georgians, he is regarded as a great statesman and state-builder.<sup about="#mwt2297" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20061_857-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20061-857" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 853;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[853]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA98">Stalin strengthened and stabilised the Soviet Union;<sup about="#mwt2299" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20043_858-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"3"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20043-858" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 854;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[854]</span></a></sup> Service suggested that without him the country might have collapsed long before 1991.<sup about="#mwt2300" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20043_858-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"3"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20043-858" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 854;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[854]</span></a></sup> In under three decades, Stalin transformed the Soviet Union into a major industrial world power,<sup about="#mwt2301" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991546Service20043_859-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"546"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"3"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991546Service20043-859" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 855;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[855]</span></a></sup> one which could "claim impressive achievements" in terms of urbanisation, military strength, education, and Soviet pride.<sup about="#mwt2302" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004602_860-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"602"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004602-860" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 856;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[856]</span></a></sup> Under his rule, the average Soviet life expectancy grew due to improved living conditions, nutrition, and medical care;<sup about="#mwt4560" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-upwards_861-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"upwards"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-upwards-861"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-upwards-861" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 857;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[857]</span></a></sup> mortality rates declined.<sup about="#mwt2304" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman20021164_862-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2002"},"p":{"wt":"1164"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman20021164-862" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 858;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[858]</span></a></sup> Although millions of Soviet citizens despised him, support for Stalin was nevertheless widespread throughout Soviet society.<sup about="#mwt2305" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004602_860-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"602"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004602-860" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 856;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[856]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA-A">Stalin's Soviet Union has been characterised as a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Totalitarianism" title="Totalitarianism" id="mwA-E">totalitarian</a> state,<sup about="#mwt2307" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004602Khlevniuk2015190_863-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"602"},"2a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2y":{"wt":"2015"},"2p":{"wt":"190"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004602Khlevniuk2015190-863" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 859;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[859]</span></a></sup> with Stalin its <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Authoritarianism" title="Authoritarianism" id="mwA-I">authoritarian</a> leader.<sup about="#mwt2308" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014732_864-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"732"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014732-864" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 860;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[860]</span></a></sup> Various biographers have described him as a <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dictator" title="Dictator" id="mwA-M">dictator</a>,<sup about="#mwt2309" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcCauley20038Service200452Montefiore20079Kotkin2014xiiKhlevniuk201512_865-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"McCauley"},"1y":{"wt":"2003"},"1p":{"wt":"8"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"52"},"3a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"3y":{"wt":"2007"},"3p":{"wt":"9"},"4a1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"4y":{"wt":"2014"},"4p":{"wt":"xii"},"5a1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"5y":{"wt":"2015"},"5p":{"wt":"12"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcCauley20038Service200452Montefiore20079Kotkin2014xiiKhlevniuk201512-865" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 861;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[861]</span></a></sup> an <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Autocracy" title="Autocracy" id="mwA-Q">autocrat</a>,<sup about="#mwt2310" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991194Volkogonov199131Service2004370_866-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"194"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2p":{"wt":"31"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"370"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991194Volkogonov199131Service2004370-866" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 862;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[862]</span></a></sup> or accused him of practicing <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Caesarism" title="Caesarism" id="mwA-U">Caesarism</a>.<sup about="#mwt2311" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199177_867-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"77"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov199177-867" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 863;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[863]</span></a></sup> Montefiore argued that while Stalin initially ruled as part of a Communist Party <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Oligarchy" title="Oligarchy" id="mwA-Y">oligarchy</a>, in 1934 the Soviet government transformed from this oligarchy into a personal dictatorship,<sup about="#mwt2312" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003124_868-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"124"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003124-868" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 864;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[864]</span></a></sup> with Stalin only becoming "absolute dictator" between March and June 1937, when senior military and NKVD figures were eliminated.<sup about="#mwt2313" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003215_869-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2":{"wt":"2003"},"p":{"wt":"215"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMontefiore2003215-869" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 865;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[865]</span></a></sup> According to Kotkin, Stalin "built a personal dictatorship within the Bolshevik dictatorship".<sup about="#mwt2314" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin20144_713-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"4"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin20144-713" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 709;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[709]</span></a></sup> In both the Soviet Union and elsewhere he came to be portrayed as an "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Despotism" title="Despotism" id="mwA-c">Oriental despot</a>".<sup about="#mwt2315" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xviiMcDermott20065_870-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"xvii"},"2a1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xviiMcDermott20065-870" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 866;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[866]</span></a></sup> The biographer <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Dmitri_Volkogonov" title="Dmitri Volkogonov" id="mwA-g">Dmitri Volkogonov</a> characterised him as "one of the most powerful figures in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./History_of_the_world" title="History of the world" id="mwA-k">human history</a>",<sup about="#mwt2316" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991xviii_871-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"xviii"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991xviii-871" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 867;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[867]</span></a></sup> while McDermott stated that Stalin had "concentrated unprecedented political authority in his hands",<sup about="#mwt2317" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20062_872-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"p":{"wt":"2"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20062-872" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 868;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[868]</span></a></sup> and Service noted that by the late 1930s, Stalin "had come closer to personal despotism than almost any monarch in history".<sup about="#mwt2318" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004370_873-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"370"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004370-873" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 869;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[869]</span></a></sup> According to historian James Harris, contemporary archival research shows that the motivation behind the purges was not Stalin attempting to establish his own personal dictatorship; evidence suggests he was committed to building the socialist state envisioned by Lenin. The real motivation for the terror, according to Harris, was an over-exaggerated fear of counterrevolution.<sup about="#mwt4562" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-874" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-874"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-874" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 870;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[870]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA-o"><a href="./File:May_Day_in_London.jpg" id="mwA-s"><img resource="./File:May_Day_in_London.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/May_Day_in_London.jpg/220px-May_Day_in_London.jpg" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="768" data-file-type="bitmap" height="165" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/May_Day_in_London.jpg/440px-May_Day_in_London.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c8/May_Day_in_London.jpg/330px-May_Day_in_London.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA-w"/></a><figcaption id="mwA-0">A contingent from the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_of_Great_Britain_(Marxist–Leninist)" title="Communist Party of Great Britain (Marxist–Leninist)" id="mwA-4">Communist Party of Great Britain (Marxist–Leninist)</a> carrying a banner of Stalin at a May Day march through London in 2008.</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwA-8">McDermott nevertheless cautioned against "over-simplistic stereotypes"—promoted in the fiction of writers like <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Aleksandr_Solzhenitsyn" title="Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn" id="mwA_A">Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vasily_Grossman" title="Vasily Grossman" id="mwA_E">Vasily Grossman</a>, and <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Anatoly_Rybakov" title="Anatoly Rybakov" id="mwA_I">Anatoly Rybakov</a>—that portrayed Stalin as an omnipotent and omnipresent tyrant who controlled every aspect of Soviet life through repression and totalitarianism.<sup about="#mwt2320" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20065–6_875-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"McDermott"},"2":{"wt":"2006"},"pp":{"wt":"5–6"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMcDermott20065–6-875" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 871;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[871]</span></a></sup> Service similarly warned of the portrayal of Stalin as an "unimpeded despot", noting that "powerful though he was, his powers were not limitless", and his rule depended on his willingness to conserve the Soviet structure he had inherited.<sup about="#mwt2321" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20048,_9_876-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"8, 9"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20048,_9-876" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 872;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[872]</span></a></sup> Kotkin observed that Stalin's ability to remain in power relied on him having a majority in the Politburo at all times.<sup about="#mwt2322" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014596_877-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kotkin"},"2":{"wt":"2014"},"p":{"wt":"596"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKotkin2014596-877" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 873;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[873]</span></a></sup> Khlevniuk noted that at various points, particularly when Stalin was old and frail, there were "periodic manifestations" in which the party oligarchy threatened his autocratic control.<sup about="#mwt2323" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015145_773-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"145"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015145-773" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 769;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[769]</span></a></sup> Stalin denied to foreign visitors that he was a dictator, stating that those who labelled him such did not understand the Soviet governance structure.<sup about="#mwt2324" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991182_878-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"182"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991182-878" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 874;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[874]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA_M">A vast literature devoted to Stalin has been produced.<sup about="#mwt2325" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015ix_879-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"ix"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015ix-879" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 875;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[875]</span></a></sup> During Stalin's lifetime, his approved biographies were largely <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Hagiographic" title="Hagiographic" id="mwA_Q" class="mw-redirect">hagiographic</a> in content.<sup about="#mwt2326" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20044_880-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"4"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20044-880" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 876;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[876]</span></a></sup> Stalin ensured that these works gave very little attention to his early life, particularly because he did not wish to emphasise his Georgian origins in a state numerically dominated by Russians.<sup about="#mwt2327" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService200413_881-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"13"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService200413-881" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 877;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[877]</span></a></sup> Since his death many more biographies have been written,<sup about="#mwt2328" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20046_882-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"6"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20046-882" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 878;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[878]</span></a></sup> although until the 1980s  these relied largely on the same sources of information.<sup about="#mwt2329" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20046_882-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"6"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20046-882" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 878;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[878]</span></a></sup> Under <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Mikhail_Gorbachev" title="Mikhail Gorbachev" id="mwA_U">Mikhail Gorbachev</a>'s Soviet administration various previously classified files on Stalin's life were made available to historians,<sup about="#mwt2330" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20046_882-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"6"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20046-882" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 878;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[878]</span></a></sup> at which point Stalin became "one of the most urgent and vital issues on the public agenda" in the Soviet Union.<sup about="#mwt2331" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xiii_883-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"xiii"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991xiii-883" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 879;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[879]</span></a></sup> After the dissolution of the Union in 1991, the rest of the archives were opened to historians, resulting in much new information about Stalin coming to light,<sup about="#mwt2332" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20046Montefiore2007xxi_884-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Service"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1p":{"wt":"6"},"2a1":{"wt":"Montefiore"},"2y":{"wt":"2007"},"2p":{"wt":"xxi"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20046Montefiore2007xxi-884" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 880;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[880]</span></a></sup> and producing a flood of new research.<sup about="#mwt2333" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015ix_879-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"ix"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015ix-879" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 875;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[875]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwA_Y">Leninists remain divided in their views on Stalin; some view him as Lenin's authentic successor, while others believe he betrayed Lenin's ideas by deviating from them.<sup about="#mwt2334" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20045_712-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"5"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20045-712" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 708;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[708]</span></a></sup> The socio-economic nature of Stalin's Soviet Union has also been much debated, varyingly being labelled a form of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./State_socialism" title="State socialism" id="mwA_c">state socialism</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./State_capitalism" title="State capitalism" id="mwA_g">state capitalism</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Bureaucratic_collectivism" title="Bureaucratic collectivism" id="mwA_k">bureaucratic collectivism</a>, or a totally unique mode of production.<sup about="#mwt2335" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESandle1999265–266_885-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Sandle"},"2":{"wt":"1999"},"pp":{"wt":"265–266"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESandle1999265–266-885" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 881;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[881]</span></a></sup> Socialist writers like Volkogonov have acknowledged that Stalin's actions damaged "the enormous appeal of socialism generated by the October Revolution".<sup about="#mwt2336" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991173_886-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"173"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991173-886" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 882;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[882]</span></a></sup></p>

<section data-mw-section-id="37" id="mwA_o"><h3 id="Death_toll_and_allegations_of_genocide">Death toll and allegations of genocide</h3>
<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable" about="#mwt2337" typeof="mw:Transclusion" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"main","href":"./Template:Main"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Excess mortality in the Soviet Union under Joseph Stalin"}},"i":0}}]}' id="mwA_s">Main article: <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Excess_mortality_in_the_Soviet_Union_under_Joseph_Stalin" title="Excess mortality in the Soviet Union under Joseph Stalin">Excess mortality in the Soviet Union under Joseph Stalin</a></div>

<p id="mwA_w">With a high number of excess deaths occurring under his rule, Stalin has been labeled "one of the most notorious figures in history".<sup about="#mwt2338" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20043_858-2" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"3"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20043-858" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 854;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[854]</span></a></sup> These deaths occurred as a result of  collectivisation, famine, terror campaigns, disease, war and mortality rates in the Gulag. As the majority of excess deaths under Stalin were not direct killings, the exact number of victims of Stalinism is difficult to calculate due to lack of consensus among scholars on which deaths can be attribute to the regime.<sup about="#mwt2339" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman20021163-1164_887-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2002"},"p":{"wt":"1163-1164"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman20021163-1164-887" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 883;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[883]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwA_0"><a href="./File:GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg" id="mwA_4"><img resource="./File:GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg/220px-GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg" data-file-width="800" data-file-height="600" data-file-type="bitmap" height="165" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg/440px-GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/15/GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg/330px-GULag_2_Museum_Moscow_Russia.jpg 1.5x" id="mwA_8"/></a><figcaption id="mwBAA">Interior of the Gulag Museum in Moscow</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwBAE">Official records reveal 799,455 documented executions in the Soviet Union between 1921 and 1953; 681,692 of these were carried out between 1937 and 1938, the years of the Great Purge.<sup about="#mwt2342" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGettyRitterspornZemskov19931022_888-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Getty"},"2":{"wt":"Rittersporn"},"3":{"wt":"Zemskov"},"4":{"wt":"1993"},"p":{"wt":"1022"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGettyRitterspornZemskov19931022-888" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 884;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[884]</span></a></sup> However, according to <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Michael_Ellman" title="Michael Ellman" id="mwBAI">Michael Ellman</a>, the best modern estimate for the number of repression deaths during the Great Purge is 950,000–1.2 million, which includes executions, deaths in detention, or soon after their release.<sup about="#mwt2343" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman20021162-1163_889-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2002"},"p":{"wt":"1162-1163"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman20021162-1163-889" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 885;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[885]</span></a></sup> In addition, while archival data shows that 1,053,829 perished in the Gulag from 1934 to 1953,<sup about="#mwt2344" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGettyRitterspornZemskov19931024_890-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Getty"},"2":{"wt":"Rittersporn"},"3":{"wt":"Zemskov"},"4":{"wt":"1993"},"p":{"wt":"1024"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGettyRitterspornZemskov19931024-890" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 886;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[886]</span></a></sup> the current historical consensus is that of the 18 million people who passed through the Gulag system from 1930 to 1953, between 1.5 and 1.7 million died as a result of their incarceration.<sup about="#mwt4564" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-891" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-891"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-891" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 887;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[887]</span></a></sup> The historian and archival researcher <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stephen_G._Wheatcroft" title="Stephen G. Wheatcroft" id="mwBAM">Stephen G. Wheatcroft</a> and Michael Ellman attribute roughly 3 million deaths to the Stalinist regime, including executions and deaths from criminal negligence.<sup about="#mwt2346" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWheatcroft19961334,_1348_892-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"2":{"wt":"1996"},"pp":{"wt":"1334, 1348"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWheatcroft19961334,_1348-892" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 888;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[888]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt2347" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman20021172_893-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2002"},"p":{"wt":"1172"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman20021172-893" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 889;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[889]</span></a></sup> The estimates of famine deaths have varied from 5.5–6.5 million<sup about="#mwt2348" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2004401_894-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"3":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"401"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2004401-894" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 890;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[890]</span></a></sup> to 8.7 million.<sup about="#mwt2366" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-895" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-895"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-895" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 891;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[891]</span></a></sup> The American historian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Timothy_D._Snyder" title="Timothy D. Snyder" id="mwBAQ">Timothy D. Snyder</a> summarizes modern data, made after the opening of the Soviet archives in the 1990s, and concludes that Stalin was directly responsible for 6 million deaths along with three million indirect deaths. He notes that the estimate is far lower than the estimates of 20 million or above which were made before access to the archives. He also compares this number to the estimate of 11–12 million non-combatants killed by the Nazi regime, thereby negating claims that Stalin killed more than Hitler.<sup about="#mwt2349" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTESnyder2010384Snyder2011_896-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Snyder"},"1y":{"wt":"2010"},"1p":{"wt":"384"},"2a1":{"wt":"Snyder"},"2y":{"wt":"2011"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTESnyder2010384Snyder2011-896" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 892;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[892]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBAU">Historians continue to debate whether or not the 1932–33 Ukrainian famine—known in Ukraine as the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Holodomor" title="Holodomor" id="mwBAY">Holodomor</a>—<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Holodomor_genocide_question" title="Holodomor genocide question" id="mwBAc">should be called a genocide</a>.<sup about="#mwt2354" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMoore2012367_897-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Moore"},"2":{"wt":"2012"},"p":{"wt":"367"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMoore2012367-897" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 893;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[893]</span></a></sup> Twenty-six countries officially recognize it under the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Convention_on_the_Prevention_and_Punishment_of_the_Crime_of_Genocide" title="Convention on the Prevention and Punishment of the Crime of Genocide" id="mwBAg" class="mw-redirect">legal definition of genocide</a>. In 2006, the Ukrainian Parliament declared it to be such,<sup about="#mwt4566" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-898" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-898"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-898" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 894;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[894]</span></a></sup> and in 2010 a Ukrainian court <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Posthumous_trial" title="Posthumous trial" id="mwBAk">posthumously convicted</a> Stalin, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Lazar_Kaganovich" title="Lazar Kaganovich" id="mwBAo">Lazar Kaganovich</a>, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Stanislav_Kosior" title="Stanislav Kosior" id="mwBAs">Stanislav Kosior</a>, and other Soviet leaders of genocide.<sup about="#mwt4267" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-899" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-899"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-899" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 895;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[895]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt4269" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-TNYRoBSZTDS_900-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"TNYRoBSZTDS"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-TNYRoBSZTDS-900"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-TNYRoBSZTDS-900" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 896;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[896]</span></a></sup> Popular among some <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Ukrainian_nationalism" title="Ukrainian nationalism" id="mwBAw">Ukrainian nationalists</a> is the idea that Stalin consciously organised the famine to suppress national desires among the Ukrainian people. This interpretation has been rejected by more recent historical studies.<sup about="#mwt2359" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTETauger20011_901-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Tauger"},"2":{"wt":"2001"},"p":{"wt":"1"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTETauger20011-901" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 897;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[897]</span></a></sup> These have articulated the view that—while Stalin's policies contributed significantly to the high mortality rate—there is no evidence that Stalin or the Soviet government consciously engineered the famine.<sup about="#mwt2360" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2004xiv,_441DaviesWheatcroft2006628_902-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"1a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"1y":{"wt":"2004"},"1pp":{"wt":"xiv, 441"},"2a1":{"wt":"Davies"},"2a2":{"wt":"Wheatcroft"},"2y":{"wt":"2006"},"2p":{"wt":"628"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDaviesWheatcroft2004xiv,_441DaviesWheatcroft2006628-902" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 898;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[898]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt4568" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-903" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-903"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-903" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 899;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[899]</span></a></sup> The idea that this was a targeted attack on the Ukrainians is complicated by the widespread suffering that also affected other Soviet peoples in the famine, including the Russians, and the fact that more died in Kazakhstan than Ukraine itself.<sup about="#mwt2362" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENaimark200846Kuromiya2008667_904-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Naimark"},"1y":{"wt":"2008"},"1p":{"wt":"46"},"2a1":{"wt":"Kuromiya"},"2y":{"wt":"2008"},"2p":{"wt":"667"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTENaimark200846Kuromiya2008667-904" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 900;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[900]</span></a></sup> Within Ukraine, ethnic Poles and Bulgarians died in similar proportions to ethnic Ukrainians.<sup about="#mwt2363" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKuromiya2008668_905-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Kuromiya"},"2":{"wt":"2008"},"p":{"wt":"668"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKuromiya2008668-905" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 901;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[901]</span></a></sup> Despite any lack of clear intent on Stalin's part, the historian <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Norman_Naimark" title="Norman Naimark" id="mwBA0">Norman Naimark</a> noted that although there may not be sufficient "evidence to convict him in an international court of justice as a genocidaire[...] that does not mean that the event itself cannot be judged as genocide".<sup about="#mwt2364" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTENaimark200845_906-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Naimark"},"2":{"wt":"2008"},"p":{"wt":"45"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTENaimark200845-906" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 902;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[902]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBA4">Michael Ellman argues that mass deaths from famines are not a "uniquely Stalinist evil", and compares the behavior of the Stalinist regime vis-à-vis the Holodomor to that of the British empire (towards Ireland and India) and even the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./G8" title="G8" id="mwBA8" class="mw-redirect">G8</a> in contemporary times, saying that he is sympathetic to the idea that the latter "are guilty of mass manslaughter or mass deaths from criminal negligence because of their not taking obvious measures to reduce mass deaths." He argues that a possible defense of Stalin and his associates is that "their behaviour was no worse than that of many rulers in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries."<sup about="#mwt2367" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEEllman20021172_893-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Ellman"},"2":{"wt":"2002"},"p":{"wt":"1172"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEEllman20021172-893" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 889;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[889]</span></a></sup></p>

</section><section data-mw-section-id="38" id="mwBBA"><h3 id="In_the_Soviet_Union_and_its_successor_states">In the Soviet Union and its successor states</h3>
<figure class="mw-default-size" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwBBE"><a href="./File:Exponáty_v_Muzeu.jpg" id="mwBBI"><img resource="./File:Exponáty_v_Muzeu.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Expon%C3%A1ty_v_Muzeu.jpg/220px-Expon%C3%A1ty_v_Muzeu.jpg" data-file-width="2816" data-file-height="1880" data-file-type="bitmap" height="147" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Expon%C3%A1ty_v_Muzeu.jpg/440px-Expon%C3%A1ty_v_Muzeu.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Expon%C3%A1ty_v_Muzeu.jpg/330px-Expon%C3%A1ty_v_Muzeu.jpg 1.5x" id="mwBBM"/></a><figcaption id="mwBBQ">Interior of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Joseph_Stalin_Museum,_Gori" title="Joseph Stalin Museum, Gori" id="mwBBU">Joseph Stalin Museum</a> in Gori, Georgia</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwBBY">Shortly after his death, the Soviet Union went through a period of <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./De-Stalinization" title="De-Stalinization" id="mwBBc">de-Stalinization</a>. Malenkov denounced the Stalin personality cult,<sup about="#mwt2368" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991314_907-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"314"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991314-907" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 903;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[903]</span></a></sup> which was subsequently criticised in <i id="mwBBg">Pravda</i>.<sup about="#mwt2369" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004592_908-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"592"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004592-908" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 904;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[904]</span></a></sup>  In 1956, Khruschev gave his "Secret Speech", titled "<a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./On_the_Cult_of_Personality_and_Its_Consequences" title="On the Cult of Personality and Its Consequences" id="mwBBk">On the Cult of Personality and Its Consequences</a>", to a closed session of the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./20th_Congress_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="20th Congress of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwBBo">Party's 20th Congress</a>. There, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Khrushchev_Thaw" title="Khrushchev Thaw" id="mwBBs">Khrushchev denounced Stalin</a> for both his mass repression and his personality cult.<sup about="#mwt2370" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991314Volkogonov1991577–579Service2004594_909-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"314"},"2a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"2y":{"wt":"1991"},"2pp":{"wt":"577–579"},"3a1":{"wt":"Service"},"3y":{"wt":"2004"},"3p":{"wt":"594"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991314Volkogonov1991577–579Service2004594-909" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 905;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[905]</span></a></sup> He repeated these denunciations at the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./22nd_Congress_of_the_Communist_Party_of_the_Soviet_Union" title="22nd Congress of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union" id="mwBBw">22nd Party Congress</a> in October 1962.<sup about="#mwt2371" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004594_910-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"594"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004594-910" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 906;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[906]</span></a></sup> In October 1961, Stalin's body was removed from the mausoleum and buried in the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kremlin_Wall_Necropolis" title="Kremlin Wall Necropolis" id="mwBB0">Kremlin Wall Necropolis</a> next to the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kremlin_wall" title="Kremlin wall" id="mwBB4" class="mw-redirect">Kremlin walls</a>, the location marked only by a simple bust.<sup about="#mwt2372" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991576Service2004594_911-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Volkogonov"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"576"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"594"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEVolkogonov1991576Service2004594-911" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 907;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[907]</span></a></sup> Stalingrad was renamed Volgograd.<sup about="#mwt2373" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004595_912-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"595"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004595-912" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 908;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[908]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBB8">Khrushchev's de-Stalinisation process in Soviet society ended when he was replaced as leader by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Leonid_Brezhnev" title="Leonid Brezhnev" id="mwBCA">Leonid Brezhnev</a> in 1964; the latter introduced a level of re-Stalinisation within the Soviet Union.<sup about="#mwt2375" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991315Service2004595_913-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfnm","href":"./Template:Sfnm"},"params":{"1a1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"1y":{"wt":"1991"},"1p":{"wt":"315"},"2a1":{"wt":"Service"},"2y":{"wt":"2004"},"2p":{"wt":"595"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991315Service2004595-913" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 909;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[909]</span></a></sup> In 1969 and again in 1979, plans were proposed for a full rehabilitation of Stalin's legacy, but on both occasions were defeated by critics within the Soviet and international Marxist-Leninist movement.<sup about="#mwt2376" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEConquest1991315_914-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Conquest"},"2":{"wt":"1991"},"p":{"wt":"315"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEConquest1991315-914" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 910;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[910]</span></a></sup> Gorbachev saw the total denunciation of Stalin as necessary for the regeneration of Soviet society.<sup about="#mwt2377" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004596_915-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"596"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004596-915" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 911;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[911]</span></a></sup> After the fall of the Soviet Union in 1991, the first President of the new Russian Federation, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Boris_Yeltsin" title="Boris Yeltsin" id="mwBCE">Boris Yeltsin</a>, continued Gorbachev's denunciation of Stalin but added to it a denunciation of Lenin.<sup about="#mwt2378" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004596_915-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"596"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004596-915" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 911;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[911]</span></a></sup> His successor, <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Vladimir_Putin" title="Vladimir Putin" id="mwBCI">Vladimir Putin</a>, did not seek to rehabilitate Stalin but emphasised the celebration of Soviet achievements under Stalin's leadership rather than the Stalinist repressions;<sup about="#mwt2379" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004596–597_916-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"pp":{"wt":"596–597"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004596–597-916" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 912;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[912]</span></a></sup> however, in October 2017 Putin opened the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Wall_of_Grief" title="Wall of Grief" id="mwBCM">Wall of Grief</a> memorial in Moscow, noting that the "terrible past" would neither be "justified by anything" nor "erased from the national memory".<sup about="#mwt4570" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-memorial_917-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"memorial"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-memorial-917"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-memorial-917" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 913;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[913]</span></a></sup></p>

<figure class="mw-default-size mw-halign-left" typeof="mw:Image/Thumb" id="mwBCQ"><a href="./File:RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin's_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg" id="mwBCU"><img resource="./File:RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin's_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin%27s_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg/220px-RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin%27s_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg" data-file-width="1024" data-file-height="764" data-file-type="bitmap" height="164" width="220" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin%27s_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg/440px-RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin%27s_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg 2x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5a/RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin%27s_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg/330px-RIAN_archive_535278_Laying_flowers_and_wreaths_to_Iosif_Stalin%27s_grave_at_Kremlin_wall.jpg 1.5x" id="mwBCY"/></a><figcaption id="mwBCc">Marxist–Leninist activists from the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Communist_Party_of_the_Russian_Federation" title="Communist Party of the Russian Federation" id="mwBCg">Communist Party of the Russian Federation</a> laying wreaths at Stalin's Moscow grave in 2009</figcaption></figure>

<p id="mwBCk">Amid the social and economic turmoil of the post-Soviet period, many Russians viewed Stalin as having overseen an era of order, predictability, and pride.<sup about="#mwt2383" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004598_918-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"598"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004598-918" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 914;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[914]</span></a></sup> He remains a revered figure among many Russian nationalists, who feel nostalgic about the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Eastern_Front_(World_War_II)" title="Eastern Front (World War II)" id="mwBCo">Soviet victory over Nazi Germany in World War II</a>,<sup about="#mwt2384" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20047_919-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20047-919" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 915;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[915]</span></a></sup> and he is regularly invoked approvingly within both Russia's far-left and far-right.<sup about="#mwt2385" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004599_920-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"599"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004599-920" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 916;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[916]</span></a></sup> In the 2008 <i id="mwBCs"><a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Name_of_Russia_(Russia_TV)" title="Name of Russia (Russia TV)" id="mwBCw">Name of Russia</a></i> television show, Stalin was voted as the third most notable personality in Russian history.<sup about="#mwt4572" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-921" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-921"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-921" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 917;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[917]</span></a></sup> A 2017 poll revealed that Stalin's popularity reached a 16-year high among the Russian population, with 46% expressing a favourable view of him.<sup about="#mwt4574" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-922" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-922"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-922" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 918;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[918]</span></a></sup> At the same time, there was a growth in pro-Stalinist literature in Russia, much relying upon the misrepresentation or fabrication of source material.<sup about="#mwt2388" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015x_923-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"x"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015x-923" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 919;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[919]</span></a></sup> In this literature, Stalin's repressions are regarded either as a necessary measure to defeat "enemies of the people" or the result of lower-level officials acting without Stalin's knowledge.<sup about="#mwt2389" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015x_923-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Khlevniuk"},"2":{"wt":"2015"},"p":{"wt":"x"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKhlevniuk2015x-923" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 919;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[919]</span></a></sup></p>

<p id="mwBC0">The only part of the former Soviet Union where admiration for Stalin has remained consistently widespread is <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Georgia_(country)" title="Georgia (country)" id="mwBC4">Georgia</a>.<sup about="#mwt2396" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService2004597_924-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"597"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService2004597-924" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 920;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[920]</span></a></sup> Many Georgians resent criticism of Stalin, the most famous figure from their nation's modern history;<sup about="#mwt2397" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEService20047_919-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Transclusion  mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"parts":[{"template":{"target":{"wt":"sfn","href":"./Template:Sfn"},"params":{"1":{"wt":"Service"},"2":{"wt":"2004"},"p":{"wt":"7"}},"i":0}}]}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-FOOTNOTEService20047-919" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 915;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[915]</span></a></sup> a 2013 survey by <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Tbilisi_State_University" title="Tbilisi State University" id="mwBC8">Tbilisi University</a> found 45% of Georgians expressing "a positive attitude" to him.<sup about="#mwt4576" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-925" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-925"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-925" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 921;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[921]</span></a></sup> Some positive sentiment can also be found elsewhere in the former Soviet Union. A 2012 survey commissioned by the <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Carnegie_Endowment_for_International_Peace" title="Carnegie Endowment for International Peace" id="mwBDA">Carnegie Endowment</a> found 38% of Armenians concurring that their county "will always have need of a leader like Stalin".<sup about="#mwt4271" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-926" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-926"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-926" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 922;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[922]</span></a></sup><sup about="#mwt4273" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-927" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-927"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-927" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 923;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[923]</span></a></sup> In early 2010 a new monument to Stalin was erected in <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Zaporizhia" title="Zaporizhia" id="mwBDE">Zaporizhia</a>, Ukraine;<sup about="#mwt2405" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-TNYRoBSZTDS_900-1" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"TNYRoBSZTDS"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-TNYRoBSZTDS-900" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 896;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[896]</span></a></sup> in December unknown persons cut off its head and in 2011 it was destroyed in an explosion.<sup about="#mwt4275" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-RIAN25212YS_928-0" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{"name":"RIAN25212YS"},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-RIAN25212YS-928"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-RIAN25212YS-928" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 924;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[924]</span></a></sup> In a 2016 <a rel="mw:WikiLink" href="./Kiev_International_Institute_of_Sociology" title="Kiev International Institute of Sociology" id="mwBDI">Kiev International Institute of Sociology</a> poll, 38% of respondents had a negative attitude to Stalin, 26% a neutral one and 17% a positive (19% refused to answer).<sup about="#mwt4277" class="mw-ref" id="cite_ref-929" rel="dc:references" typeof="mw:Extension/ref" data-mw='{"name":"ref","attrs":{},"body":{"id":"mw-reference-text-cite_note-929"}}'><a href="./Joseph_Stalin#cite_note-929" style="counter-reset: mw-Ref 925;"><span class="mw-reflink-text">[925]</span></a></sup></p>

</section></section><section data-mw-section-id="39" id="mwBDM"><h2 id="See_also">See also</h2>
